<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="REV" stage="Final" version="H">
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu</p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Sasuri Yohanis lula-nèti ngaa dhu j'aj'i<bt>Yohanis' writing about what will happen</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">ropa èle rai-haha toke<bt>at the end of the world until there is</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu<bt>a New Model/Type/Form World</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1-2" />Lii maho'o nèti ja'a, Yohanis, ana pua-paleha nèti Yesus Kristus.<bt>Greetings from me, Yohanis, Yesus Kristus' servant.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ja'a suri ètu d'ara sasuri ne'e, ngaa dhu j'aj'i bèli-camèd'a. Ja'a ke'a j'ara se'e se, sèmi ne'e ka: Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu peka tèke mi Yesus Kristus. Hèia Ama Lamatua pua Yesus ho lole mi dhèu unu Na sèra. Èle èèna ka, Yesus pua ana pajuu Na ca dhèu nèti sorga, mai bhoke pad'elo j'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i mi ja'a, sèna ka ja'a suri mema. Te nèbhu heka j'ara aa'i-aa'i se, tatu j'aj'i. De nanene paie-iie Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua dhu Yesus peka ne.<bt>In this writing, I write about what is going to happen in the future (doublet). I got to know these things like this: God himself is who revealed them in.advance to Yesus Kristus. And God ordered Yesus to tell the Lord's people. Then Yesus ordered one of his underlings from heaven (*angels) to reveal show all these things to me, so that I write them in.advance. Cuz (elaboration) much not longer, all these things will surely happen. So (consequently), you-pl must listen well/carefully to God's Words which Yesus has told here. [DISCOURSE (book-level): Gk is distant 3rd person “to his servants”, “to his servant John”, and in vs.3 “the ones who read/whoever reads”. In the Timor region, this comes across as for and about someone else, completely removed from and not relevant to the readers of the letter. The last sentence above makes explicit that this message from Jesus is for the readers of John's letter (see also Ex. Summ. #1 re: “to his servants”).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="apokálypsis: revealing, let someone know things"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">apokálypsis: revealing, let someone know things that had been hidden but were now to be made known to the right people. More like declassifying information than like letting the cat out of the bag or leaking a story eseémanen: make known by means of signs, foretell, make explicit<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>send ... make clear: Jesus wen send his angel messenja guy [from da sky] fo tell me, John, [all dis stuff,] cuz I one a his worka guys. Dass how he wen make clear all dat stuff. Let somebody know, make um know, make um clear fo dem Follow NIV for format with quotation levels; also Acts 28:25.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu baca sasuri ne'e toke dhèu bisa nanene, na, rèngu oto titu kèna. Aa dhèu dhu nanene isi na, aa tao madhutu sèmi dhu na moa, rèngu oto kahèi. Te lod'o mamai na dètu ae le.<bt>Everyone/all people who read this writing to the point that (other) people can hear/listen, na, they are most fortunate. And the people who hear its contents and follow/obey/do according to its message/advice/instructions, they are also fortunate. Cuz (elaboration) its time, is very near. [EXEG: KT: blessed from Gk /makarios/ -- ontong ‘fortunate’, not kasi berkat (which can skew it to giving material blessings. Avoid TB ‘happy’ as that is not really a meaning element of the Gk word.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te Ama Lamatua dhu moa le,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Te Ama Lamatua dhu moa le, peka na, bèli-camèda Nèngu pala-bagi mèngi-nale ma dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu baca sasuri ne'e, do nanene isi na, aa madhutu sèmi dhu Na moa. Te lod'o na, oe èle kèna.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="makários: fortunate, rather than &quot;happy&quot;. See"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">makários: fortunate, rather than "happy". See the Beatitudes anaginoóskoon: the focus is on reading the letter publicly in church on the one hand, and on hearing it read in public -- more than an individual reading it privately. In any case, this part hasn't happened as of the time he was writing; it's only potential readers and hearers. It's not just the predictions; it's the prophetic revelation of what Jesus is like.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis suri lii maho'o ho pa'adhu asa pidhu juma'at ètu propensi Asia<bt>Yohanis writes greetings to the seven congregations in Asia province</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Lii maho'o nèti ja'a, hia mi pidhu juma'at ètu propensi Asia.<bt>Greetings from me to the Lord's seven congregations in Asia province.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Ama Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na hia miu, ho miu mamuri padame dènge mera-milu. Te Ama Lamatua abhu mema le, karèi nèti uru ka. Nèngu dhu deo ne'e, bèli-camèd'a, toke d'ai mia-mia. Ja'a manèngi kahèi sèna ka Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na hia miu, ho miu mamuri padame dènge mera-milu. Ja'a ladhe kèdhi Roh Mola-Mèci ne, nuka sèmi abhu pidhu roh sa dhu patangara dènge kadera paredha Ama Lamatua.<bt>I request that God show His goodness/grace/ kindness/generosity so that you-pl can live in restored relationships (relational peace) and safety/security/prosperity (external peace). Cuz (elaboration) God has been from long ago. He is now, and later He will be forever. I also request that His Spirit show His goodness/grace/ kindness/generosity so that you-pl can live in restored relationships (relational peace) and safety/security/prosperity (external peace). I saw His Spirit, like there were seven spirits who face God's ruling chair. [NOTE to daughter translations: Use standard epistle greeting formula for “Grace to you and peace from...”] [EXEG: 7 spirits -- 1) Holy Spirit "symbolism of a sevenfold or complete manifestation of his being", from LXX rendering of Is. 11:2; Ramsey says "a symbolic or allegorical way of expressing the full range of exercise of the Divine power in the seven churches,”; favoured by Hughes, TH M.Crofts, and NLT, but problematic for Rev. 3:1, 4:6 &amp; 5:6 which could be seen as requiring 7 individual entities (in 5:6 going to different locations); 2) the seven archangels of Jewish tradition; favoured by IVP commentary; 3) seven spirits (or angels) of some sort, favoured by all English translations except NLT and Mounce "it would seem that “the seven spirits before [God’s] throne” are best understood as part of a heavenly entourage that has a special ministry in connection with the Lamb."; TH advises "The translation of the phrase in this verse must be quite literal; as with all other symbolic figures and events in this book,"; Mounce says "the seven spirits of God are enigmatic at best."; challenge is 1) reporting faithfully what John says he saw in his vision, and 2) what does it mean, without insisting that it makes good sense in a book that is full of mind-blowing and far out things.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ama Lamatua hia miu aa'i-aa'i mi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Ama Lamatua hia miu aa'i-aa'i mi mèngi-nale, ... Ja'a manèngi kahèi mèngi-nale, aa dame nèti Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. J</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cháris: acting graciously erchómenos: continued activity"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">cháris: acting graciously erchómenos: continued activity on behalf of his people, not just living forever<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>heptà: seven was strongly associated with the idea of completeness. It could be used of the Holy Spirit in all his completeness, all aspects of his being pneumátoon: probably a picturesque way to speak of the Holy Spirit, also used in the Old Testament. Not obake or local spirits or evil spirits or what survives after a person dies or a life force that inhabits people and animals and plants or an angel, or an embodiment of mana (check all of them, and make notes for the consultant)<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>eireénee: general well-being, more than just absence of conflict. Like Hebrew "shalom"</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani ètu ne'e, suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;pidhu roh dhu patangara dènge kadera paredha Ama Lamatua&gt;&gt;. Madhutu dhèu d'èlu-mèu Alkitab, nomer pidhu, sasoa na, nuka j'ara dhu mèci aa dhu tesa. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu d'èlu-mèu cahag'e peka na, pidhu roh se'e, sasoa na, Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Dènge j'ara ne'e, ètu ayat èpa toke lèmi, Yohanis padhai lii mèngi-nale 1) nèti Ama Lamatua, 2) nèti Roh Na, aa 3) nèti Yesus Kristus.<bt>The Yunani language writings here write, saying, “7 spirits who face God's throne”. According to Biblical experts (people who are knowledgable/clever about the Bible, the meaning of number 7 is things that are enough, that are complete, and that are whole. That is why some experts say that here the meaning of those 7 spirits is God's *Holy Spirit. In that way, in verses 4-5 here, Yohanis is speaking blessing from 1) Lord God, from 2) His Spirit, and from 3) Yesus Kristus.</bt></note><note reference="1:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 3:14, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 4:5</note><v n="5" />Ja'a manèngi kahèi ho Yesus Kristus pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na hia miu, sèna ka miu mamuri padame dènge mera-milu. Nèngu ne loe boe padhai lii paled'a j'ara-j'ara dhu Ama Lamatua peka dènge Ne. Uru èèna Na madhe, te ngaa Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne, ka Na j'aj'i dhèu uru tèka, dhu mamuri hari nèti mamadhe. Pe Nèngu ka dhu paredha dhèu aae aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>I also request that Yesus Kristus show His goodness/grace/ kindness/generosity so that you-pl can live in restored relationships (relational peace) and safety/security/prosperity (external peace). He always (does not cease) speaks forthrightly/clearly about that which God told Him. Previously He died, but God made Him live again, and/so He would become the first/most prominant person who lives again from death. Later He will command/govern all rajas in this world. [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk term is ambiguous (see notes), and its ambiguities are mirrored by the Kupang. Make sure your rendering skews in the right direction.] [EXEG: Gk here is /archwn/ not /kurios/, so don't force your standard term for ‘lord’ if it doesn't fit here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="prootótokos: has a triple sense of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">prootótokos: has a triple sense of "firstborn" and "superior to everything else in its class", as in Colossians 1:15 and "existing before something else"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lula Yesus sue èdhi, nèti èèna ka Na pasuti raa Na hia mi èdhi. Nèti mamadhe Na, Na bhoke j'ara sèna ka patabuli èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi.<bt>Because Yesus loves us-inc, that's why He shed/spilled His blood (for a high moral cause) for us. With/by that death of his, He opened the way to free/release/save us from the power/authority of our wrongs. [EXEG: combination of “freed ... by shedding his blood” should evoke the /tumpa dara/ vocabulary which implies dying for a high moral cause.]</bt><note reference="1:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 55:4, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 89:27</note><v n="6" />Ka Na ded'e nare èdhi, j'aj'i ana kabarai Na, sèna ka èdhi sab'a hia Ama Na, Ama Lamatua. Yesus Kristus ne, kapai titu kèna, lula koasa Na èle boe. Lèke sèmi èèna!<bt>Then He raised us up to become His citizens, so that we would work for His Father, God. Yesus Kristus is truly great/amazing, and His power/authority lasts for forever. That's how it is!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hieréis: was one pries guy dat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">hieréis: was one pries guy dat wen say "prieses". "All" may be needed to keep the plural from being understood as "us apostles" or something restrictive; having everybody in the kingdom be a priest is a shocking idea for both Jews and Greeks</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 19:6, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 5:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />De bhoke musi madha ho ladhe paie-iie! Yesus dènge Ama Na, limuri ne ètu sorga nèi. Te ngaa nèbhu heka Na puru mai d'ara ra'i-liru. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha, èèna na ladhe rèdhi Ne, sèmi èèna kahèi dènge rèngu dhu uru na kèj'i Ne. Bèli-camèd'a dhèu aa'i-aa'i nèti mia-mia ètu rai-haha ne manyasa, aa tangi d'ara pèd'a, lula tadhe Ne. Se'e se, mema tare'a-re'a j'aj'i. Lèke tare'a sèmi èèna.<bt>So (consequently), open your eyes to see well! Now Yesus and His Father are in heaven. But not much longer, He will come down in cloud. All people on the world will be able to see Him. Like that also (=including) the people who previously pierced (w/knife or spear) Him. Later all people everywhere on this world will regret and cry loudly/bitterly because they know/recognise Him then. This all will truly happen. It's true like that. [EXEG: “because of Him” should be something that evokes/reflects His Christness, death, resurrection, Saviour, King, not merely “because they see Him (physically)”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nuka ètu = ada di ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">nuka ètu = ada di ; kèj'i = tikam (piso, tombak)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="idoù: starts quotations from Deuteronomy and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">idoù: starts quotations from Deuteronomy and Zechariah. The double "look!" fits the context more dramatically than a single "try look!", which is actually fairly low key and might be used mainly by kids who are wowed by rather simple things érkhetai: implicitly, coming back as Judge, which is what causes all the consternation<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>nephelóon: not like an airplane letting down through a cloud layer for a landing, flaps extended, but with clouds as a beautiful part of the stage setting, an embellishment of his grand entry, as in the medieval paintings páas ophthalmòs: part for the whole, but no reason for not carrying it through in company with a verb<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>exekéntesan: Roman swords were used for both slashing and thrusting, but the spear was used exclusively for penetration. Spears fit better with the crucifixion story as well, without being anachronistic. I guess we don't have Opukaha`ia's biography, but I seem to remember that he narrowly escaped death from either a spear thrust or a javelin throw, which is what his name ("slit belly" from kaha 'slice lengthwise') refers to: Gavan Daws in The Shoal of Time under "Arts of War" mentions spears (for thrusting), javelins (for throwing), and daggers (for stabbing). There was nothing corresponding to a sword; clubs were used instead kópsontai (koptomai): ritualized expression of grief in mourning, such as one sees today in the Palestinian funerals that are shown on TV, with loud outcries and throwing one's body around. People do feel genuinely bad when they do this, and that is the socially accepted way to express how they feel. It's not just weeping quietly or grieving, it's noisy and embarrassing to Westerners. I saw it close at hand in Spain with a North African woman picked up for smuggling drugs. Some commentators think the motivation is a sudden realization of the awful things they have done. Others think people are scared spitless by having the Judge show up when they aren't ready to deal with him, and they know they don't have a chance of getting acquitted. Since the word is most associated with genuine grief, I'd pick remorse -- even if it's too late<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="1:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:13, Mateos 24:30, Markus 13:26, Lukas 21:27, 1 Tesalonika 4:17, Sakaria 12:10, Yohanis 19:34, 37</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ama Lamatua peka na,<bt>God says,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a ne,<bt>“I am</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Alpa toke d'ai Omega.<bt>Alpha until Omega.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a ne,<bt>I am</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">A toke d'ai Z.<bt>A until Z.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa'i-aa'i ra kapua nèti Ja'a,<bt>Everything originates/is rooted/sourced from Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">karèi nèti uru tèka toke d'ai èle.<bt>beginning from the first/start until the end.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a ne dhu abhu mema le karèi nèti uru ka mai.<bt>I am who has truly been from long ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a dhu deo ne'e.<bt>I am who is now.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa Ja'a dhu bèli-camèd'a, toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>And I am who later will be continually forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mema-mema = ada memang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mema-mema = ada memang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ka Ja'a mesa-mesa Ku dhu dènge koasa kapai risi eele!&gt;&gt;<bt>And2 only I alone am the one who is most powerful!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eimi: it's only the A to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">eimi: it's only the A to Z that's in first person inside the quotation; the rest is third person and presumably represents John's words, which he repeats later in the book kýrios ho theós: a marked construction<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="1:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 22:13, Kalua nèti Masir 3:14</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis ladhe nèdhi Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a<bt>Yohanis sees the Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Lula èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti parcaya, na, Yesus ne Dhèu Aae èdhi, nèti èèna ka èdhi pa'a'ari. Abhu dhèu leo dhu nasa kahèi lula èdhi madhutu Yesus, ka rèngu paj'èra èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti. Te ngaa Yesus pa'èra d'ara èdhi, ka bisa taha taruu. Lula ja'a aj'a-nori le dhèu lula-nèti Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua aa lole j'ara-j'ara lula-nèti Yesus, ka abhu dhèu dhu tèka d'ara. Nèti èèna ka, limuri ne ra kèpe rare ja'a, ka hue eele asa pulu Patmos ne'e.<bt>Because we(inc) all believe together that that Yesus, [is] our King, that's why we-inc are reciprocal siblings. There are other people who are angry because we follow Yesus, so they cause all of us-inc to suffer. But Yesus has strengthened/encouraged our livers, so that we can endure continually. Because I told about God's Words, and taught about Yesus, there were people who resented/objected to that. That's why now they have captured/arrested and thrown me to this Patmos island.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hue = muat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hue = muat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="egenómeen: may imply that he wasn't"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">egenómeen: may imply that he wasn't on Patmos any more when he sent out the letter pátmooi: Patmos Island is about 10 miles long and 6 miles wide, almost exactly the size of Kaho`olawe. It has a small harbor, and is about as far southwest of Ephesus as Kaua`i is from O`ahu (62 miles). It was used by the Romans as a penal colony or concentration camp. It may be that John was on a prison island there because he wouldn't stop preaching, or he could have been a pastor there with the job of preaching. They show tourists a cave he is supposed to have lived in<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>martyrían Ieesóu: the testimony Jesus presented, as in Verse 2 en Ieesóu: most likely goes with "trouble" and "kingdom" and "endurance", not just the last one<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ka d'ara ca lod'o, lèke dènge lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i, ja'a abhu Roh Ama Lamatua. Kaca'a laa, ja'a tadèngi lii rodhe nèti kabodho. Lii èèna nuka sèmi lii tiu tèbhe sa.<bt>Then one time, exactly on the worship day, I was affected by God's Spirit. Unexpectedly, I heard a loud voice that shouted/called out from behind (me). It's/His sound was like a trumpet. [CHECK: does /abhu/ imply first time? NO]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tiu tèbhe = siput atau tanduk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">tiu tèbhe = siput atau tanduk</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kyriakéei heeméraai: the earliest Christian designation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">kyriakéei heeméraai: the earliest Christian designation for Sunday: the day for the Lord</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Lii ne, pua ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis! Ja'a neo bhoke j'ara èci, ho pad'elo dènge èu. Aa'i-aa'i dhu èu ladhe mèdhi se, èu hud'i suri more ku. Èle èèna, èu hud'i pa'adhu hia pidhu juma'at, nuka ètu kota Epesus, kota Smirna, kota Pergamus, kota Tiatira, kota Sardis, kota Piladelfia, dènge kota Laodikia.&gt;&gt;<bt>That voice ordered me saying, “Yohanis! I want to reveal and show you something. All that you see here, you must write down. After that, you must pass it on to seven congregations, that is in the city of Efesus, Smirna city, Pergamus city, Tiatira city, Sardis city, Piladelfia city, and Laodekia city.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa tadèngi kore lii ne'e, ja'a kabib'a asa kabodho, neo ke'a cee ka dhu lii deo na. Te ngaa ja'a kèdhi labhu èi mènyi pidhu bua dhu pamadhèdi ètu dedha tatèka labhu, dhu tao nèti hualaa.<bt>Hearing like that, then I turned around to see who was speaking. But I saw seven wick lanterns that were sitting on top of a lamp place/stand that was made of gold.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tatèka = tampa taro, tampa simpan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">tatèka = tampa taro, tampa simpan ; labhu èi mènyi rai = lampu minyak tanah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lychnías: lamp holders, poles with lamps"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">lychnías: lamp holders, poles with lamps on top. They might have been made from wood or iron for strength and covered with gold leaf for beauty. Probably not solid gold; they would have weighed tons. The lamps were shallow clay bowls full of olive oil, with a wick lying partly in the oil, the other end burning. One lampstand might have had several oil lamps on it, but 2:5 makes it sound like there was one lampstand for each church, and possibly just one oil lamp per lampstand</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Abhu Dhèu èci dhu titu ètu talora aae labhu se'e. Rèhu Na nuka sèmi Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Na pake kodho èci dhu robho d'ai rai, aa dhu cape dènge saledha hualaa ca bèla ètu kakara Na.<bt>And there was a Person standing in the middle of those lamps. His face/appearance was like the Ideal Human (*Son of Man). He was wearing a long dress/robe down to His feet, and he wore a golden shoulder sash (diagonally) across his chest.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bane = letakkan ; cape ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bane = letakkan ; cape = put sash on diagonally</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hómoion hyiòn anthroópou: no article, at"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">hómoion hyiòn anthroópou: no article, at this point not to be identified with Daniel's "Son of Man" figure or Christ, but just "something with a human form" periezoosménon pròs tóis mastóis: not a belt, but either one strip crossing the chest from shoulder to waist, or two strips crossing each other in the middle of the chest. Not an Empress waistline that would make him look like he was in drag. Some commentators suggest it was the way the High Priest dressed, but he had more on his chest than a zooneé<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="1:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:13, 10:5</note><v n="14" />Rèu kètu Na pudhi lao-lao nuka sèmi rèu kahib'i-kalèbho pudhi.<bt>His hair, was pure white like cotton.</bt><note reference="1:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;Kètu dènge rèu kètu Na pudhi nuka sèmi rèu kahib'i-kalèbho pudhi, aa nuka sèmi salju.&gt;&gt; Dua-dua ra peka mi mèdha èci dhu pudhi lao-lao.<bt>The Yunani language writings write, saying, “His head and His hair were white like the white fur/wool of sheep, and white like snow (Indo loan, not known except through media).” Both of them give a picture of something that is pure white.</bt></note>Musi madha Na heo lo'a-lo'a sèmi ai.<bt>His eyes, flashed like fire.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="leukaì: what does white symbolize locally?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">leukaì: what does white symbolize locally? In the Bible, it is usually purity, or here it may suggest the wisdom of great age phlòx pyròs: blazing like fire (Daniel 10:6), generally understood to symbolize fierce opposition to enemies. What is the symbolism? burning, intense -- how did Kamehameha I look when he was chasing the O`ahu army up Nu`uanu Valley? ["mean look" DM] Not the evil eye, and not stink eye. But you know he's not going to put up with any opposition or any nonsense. [Literally (in footnote?) "Da eye, jalike da fire!"]<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="1:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:9</note><v n="15" />Haga Na mea gèu-gèu sèmi tabaga dhu tunu ètu d'ara ai karoo. Lii Na kadèru sèmi lii bèbhe naha dhasi kapai.<bt>His feet, were shiny red like copper/bronze that people burn/bake in the hot fire. His voice was roaring like large waves breaking (in the west monsoon).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ai karoo = bara api yg"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ai karoo = bara api yg panas tinggi ; mea gèu-gèu = mera manyala (from fire) ; dou = bunyi bass ; kasee = bunyi gelombang ; kaciri = gemerincing (tinkling, clinking) ; kacère = (bitches arguing), kadèru = like large waves breaking or a bomb exploding</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lii Na dou sèmi lii èi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Lii Na dou sèmi lii èi hae nèti kolo ledhe.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chalkolibánooi: some mixed metal or alloy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">chalkolibánooi: some mixed metal or alloy like bronze or brass. The exact mix is not known. pepyrooménees: heated, so could be glowing red or white like lava. The heating was done to get rid of the junk. It's not the polished metal after refining (that idea must come from "burnished" in the old translations, not supported by the text no matter what UBS says), but the glowing hot metal during refining (present participle, not aorist)<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="1:14-15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 10:6; Yeskial 1:24, 43:2</note><v n="16" />Ètu ai g'ana, Na kèpe dènge hua-hètu pidhu bua. Nèti hèb'a Na, bhodho samala èci dhu dua rèka dhu madèka. Rèhu Na cèb'a-cèb'a nuka sèmi madha lod'o dhu re mèu rai.<bt>In His right hand, he was holding seven stars. From His mouth, there was coming out a double edged fighting sword that was sharp. His face, shone brightly like the sun at noon.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhodho = muncul, keluar ; cèba2"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bhodho = muncul, keluar ; cèba2 = blitz</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rhomphaía: UBS has the blade of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">rhomphaía: UBS has the blade of a sword (not the handle) extending forward out of his mouth. Either way it boggles the imagination, so here is not a good place to explain anything. It's identifying the symbols, not the description, that's probably important</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa ja'a ladhe kèdhi Dhèu ne'e, hèia ja'a bèbhe dènge ka sèmi dhèu dhu madhe ètu haga Na. Te ngaa Na gai ja'a dènge ai g'ana Na, hèia Na lii peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Baku madha'u! Te aa'i-aa'i se kapua ra nèti Ja'a, karèi nèti uru toke d'ai èle.<bt>When I saw that Person, then I fell right away like a person who had died, before His feet. But He touched me with His right hand, then He spoke saying, “Child, é! Don't be afraid! Cuz (elaboration) everything originates from Me, beginning the first/start until the end.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="They went literal to &lt;&lt;died&gt;&gt; here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">They went literal to &lt;&lt;died&gt;&gt; here</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="próotos: just like A to Z"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">próotos: just like A to Z in Verse 8. The symbols or icons established here get repeated again and again through the book, and they are supposed to be identifiable as the same symbol each time</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 44:6, 48:12, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 2:8, 22:13</note><v n="18" />Uru èèna, mema Ja'a madhe, te ngaa limuri ne, èu ladhe ku laa! Ja'a mamuri hari le, aa èèna na mamuri taa-taa. Aa Ja'a ka dhu kèd'u gagoe dhu bisa bhoke era pea dhèu madhe, sèna ka pamamuri hari si.<bt>Previously I died, but now you(sg) just look! I am alive again, and later I will live forever. And I am who holds the key which can open the place of the dead people in order to make them live again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***tweaked /dhu bisa/"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">***tweaked /dhu bisa/</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="idóu: attention getter for the important"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">idóu: attention getter for the important thing that comes next. Pidgin does a lot of this kléis: this is one of the icons that runs throughout the book<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>haaidou: abode of the dead, Hell</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Èu hud'i suri more aa'i ku dhu ladhe mèdhi se, aa suri kahèi ngaa dhu j'aj'i bèli-camèd'a.<bt>You must write all which you see now, and write all that will happen later.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="méllei: scheduled by God's authority, inevitable,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">méllei: scheduled by God's authority, inevitable, destined</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ja'a peka uuru ku sasoa na: labhu hualaa pidhu bua se, nuka pidhu juma'at. Aa pidhu hua-hètu dhu èu mèdhi ètu ai g'ana Ja'a ne, nuka ana pajuu dhèu pidhu nèti sorga dhu rèti lii Ama Lamatua hia mi pidhu juma'at sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will tell first the meaning like this: those seven golden lamps' meaning, is seven congregations. And those seven stars which you saw in My right hand there, they are seven underlings from heaven (*angels) who bring news from God to those seven congregations.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ánggeloi: messengers. People have interpreted them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">ánggeloi: messengers. People have interpreted them as pastors or representatives of the churches, or guardian angels, or the heavenly guardian or representative of each church. The latter matches an obscure concept found in Daniel 10:13, 20 and 12:1, Matthew 18:10, and Acts 12:15. All the other uses of "anggelos" in Revelation are supernatural beings, so it is probably best not to have these be human preachers. They are involved at a higher level, and there is no warning in the next chapters about them being snatched away if the people don't shape up</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'adhu lii moa hia juma'at ètu kota Epesus<bt>The Lord Yesus sends instructions to the congregation at Efesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a èèna paredha ja'a, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis, èu suri more ku sasuri èci. Isi na sèmi ne'e:<bt>After that, the (aforementioned) Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man) commanded me, saying, “Yohanis, you must write a letter. It's contents are like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mi juma'at ètu kota Epesus:<bt>&lt;To the congregation at Epesus city: [EXEG: “angel” referring to the churches themselves. See Ex. Summ. choice #2; ditto for all 7 letters. See Ex.Summ. and Hughes for wide disagreement on what this could mean.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sasuri ne, nèti Ja'a, Yesus. Ja'a ka dhu kèd'u pidhu hua-hètu ètu ai g'ana Ja'a. Ja'a dhu kako palème kahèi laladhe pidhu labhu hualaa se cue-cue. Nanene paie lii padhai Ja'a.<bt>This letter here, is from Me, Yesus. I am the one who holds seven stars in My right hand. I also walk around to see each of those seven gold lamps. Listen to this speaking of Mine. [EXEG: in this region it is more natural for ‘lamps’ (whole) to represent the ‘lampstand’ (part). Otherwise the heavy information load would skew the focus.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="All the &quot;Da One dat ...&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">All the "Da One dat ..." passages in chapters 2 and 3 take "m2" as standard format marker. All the quoted messages that follow them, and their internal breaks, take "m3". Fiesta resets these to "m"; they should be set back before publication. angel: We have interpreted this as an angel, as most commentaries and translations. The criticisms are not applicable to an angel, but to the church. As the messenger, he is to announce these things to them. In Pidgin, we cannot use the singular 'you' to apply to a church; it must be the plural.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>grápson: UBS recommends starting each section with a quotation margin, but to not give him any attributes in the margin -- they get in the way of the attributes that are given inside the message, which should constitute an adequate identification. Frank has felt that "da Guy" is needed, but that doesn't get in the way peripatóon: walking around, as if tending the flames of the lamps, taking care of the churches<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>lychnióon: oil lamps with wicks extending out over the side. Should not sound like street lights or floor lamps -- anything with a light bulb in it</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Ja'a ladhe kèdhi le, j'ara mamuri miu ètu kota Epesus, peka na, miu sab'a bia hia Lamatua. Ladhe abhu dhèu bhelu ètu talora aae miu, miu soro tèke boe ne. Ladhe dhèu mai dadugu, peka na, nèngu dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua, miu parisa paie-iie mamuri na, sèna ka me'a na, nèngu ne dhèu kapod'e-kabèli. Hèia miu tule eele, aa nanene boe ne.<bt>I have seen your lives in Efesus city, that you(p) always work hard for the Lord. If there is an evil person in your midsts, you don't give him any opportunity/space. If a person come twisting/lying, saying that he is God's commissioned person (*apostle), you always examine his life well, in order to know if/whether a person like that is a liar. Then you reject [him], so that you don't listen to/obey him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soro tèke boe = tidak membiarkan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">soro tèke boe = tidak membiarkan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sou: everything in the next two"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">sou: everything in the next two chapters is addressed to individuals, not groups. It's the person responsible for the church, not the rank and file of the church, although most of the admonishments have to do with the "messenger"'s responsibility to the rank and file. Commentators equate "messenger" to the pastor, or some representative of the church, or the church's guardian angel (the majority). The only exegetical position that implies plural takes the "angel" to be the presbyters collectively, but there is no support for this in the text. kópon: their persistent and painful struggles to maintain their Christian profession. Should be interpretable as just working hard for a living<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>dyneei: "can" doesn't fit, because it implies you might or might not apostólous: doesn't say who sent them. With Paul it's usually Jesus Christ, but false apostles might be claiming a wider base. Tossup.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>héures: you found out what they were as a result of testing them</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Masi ka dhèu paj'èra miu lula miu parcaya Ja'a, te ngaa miu taha taruu aa hari boe ciki sa.<bt>Even if people cause difficulty to you because you believe in Me, but you endure on, without any reversing/retreating.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hari = mondor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hari = mondor</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ebástasas: implies that there is an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">ebástasas: implies that there is an aggravation or unpleasant experience, usually caused by somebody else, that you have put up with</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa Ja'a ladhe, na, miu manahu ètu ca madha j'ara. Lula uru èèna, lod'o miu hiu-hiu parcaya Ja'a, miu mamuri pasue èci dènge èci. Te ngaa limuri ne, miu sèmi heka èèna.<bt>But I see, you are falling/lacking in one matter. Because, previously when you first believed in Me, you always loved each other. But now, you are no longer like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="proóteen: formerly, earlier = próteron; could"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">proóteen: formerly, earlier = próteron; could also be initial in an ordinal series, but doesn't have to be -- first, when you first believed in me, at the beginning of your Christian life. Despite inspiring talks on the enthusiasm of early love, he's probably saying that things aren't going as well as they were before, without strong emphasis on the starting moment proóteen: Pidgin does use "like" as a conjunction, and it is not ambiguous with the verb because the syntax is different. So please don't automatically modify it into "jalike": test both impartially<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>aphéekes: you have gotten away from your first or earlier love (could be for Christ, could be for other Christians: it doesn't say). Cooling down of fervor</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />De miu hud'i sanèd'e hari ku j'ara uru èèna! Te limuri ne, miu pakaj'èu ae nèti j'ara uru èèna. De miu ae eele ka nèti sasala miu se'e, sèna ka mi pasue hari sèmi uru èèna. Te aad'o na, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a mai kore hari labhu hualaa èèna nèti miu.<bt>So you must remember that former time. Cuz (elaboration) now you are too far from that prior state/way. So (consequently), you must stop this sin of yours, so that you love each other again like previously. Cuz (elaboration) if not, later I will come take that gold lamp from you. [NOTE: see note on ‘lamps’and ‘lampstands’ above]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="póthen péptookas: think where you were"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">póthen péptookas: think where you were before you fell metanoéin: have a change of heart<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Te ngaa d'ara Ja'a ako karej'e, lula miu tule eele lii aj'a-nori nèti Nikolai, dhu ana madhutu na sèra tao madhutu. Ja'a tule eele kahèi tatao kapod'e-kabèli ra sèra.<bt>But My liver is a bit happy, because you have rejected Nikolai's teaching which his underlings follow. I also reject their (evil/disruptive) deeds.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ngaa dara Ja'a ako karej'e,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Te ngaa dara Ja'a ako karej'e, lula miu mo'o boe nanene lii aj'a-nori nèti ana madhutu Nikolai. Ja'a tule eele kahèi lii aj'a-nori rèngu dhu kapod'e-kabèli èèna.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miséis: does Pidgin &quot;hate&quot; apply to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">miséis: does Pidgin "hate" apply to ideas and practices, or only to people? Nikolaïtóon: followers of one Nikolaus, otherwise unknown, who may have taught that the material and spiritual realms are completely separate, and that immoral conduct does not affect the spiritual life. Deibler has "who taught that Christians were to practice idolatry and immorality [historical knowledge]"<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="2:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu d'èlu-mèu Alkitab peka na, èdhi te'a boe ngaa dhu Nikolai aj'a-nori sèra.<bt>Experts knowledgable about the Bible say, those teachings of Nikolai are not clear (what they are).</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Nanene paie-iie, ngaa dhu Roh Lamatua neo peka dènge juma'at Na sèra. Dhèu cee dhu taha pa'èra madhutu Ja'a toke na madhe, pe Ja'a soro tèke na'a hua aj'u ètu d'ara talora oka Ama Lamatua. Te dhèu dhu na'a hua aj'u èèna, nèngu abhu mamuri taa-taa dènge Lamatua.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So! Listen well to what the Lord's Spirit is telling His congregations. The person/whoever endures strongly following/obeying Me until he dies, later I will give him/her permission to eat fruit from that tree which is in God's garden. Cuz (elaboration) the person/ whoever eats that tree's fruit, he gets/obtains true life that never ends (KT also used in John's gospel and epistles).”’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="táis ekkleesíais: not just church people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">táis ekkleesíais: not just church people as individuals, or the people in the Ephesus church, but in the seven different churches John is writing to, or in all churches no matter where they are oús: like Matthew 13:9<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ho nikóon: may not need an object, but if it does, Deibler suggests "conquers/overcomes the power of Satan" paradeisw: Luke 23:43 implies a pleasant, relaxing place (comes from a Persian word designating an area kept in game for government people to go hunting in as a break from court life). More beautiful than awesome -- we've got piles of awesome places in the book as is, and may as well lighten up when we can. [?]<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="2:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:9, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 22:2, Yeskial 28:13, 31:8</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'adhu lii moa hia juma'at ètu kota Smirna<bt>The Lord Yesus sends instructions to the congregation at Smirna</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Èle èèna ka, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a èèna, tuhu hari lii Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis, èu suri more hari ku sasuri leo èci, dhu isi na sèmi ne'e:<bt>Then that Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man) continued His speaking saying, “Yohanis, now you must write another letter, it's contents are like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mi juma'at ètu kota Smirna:<bt>&lt;To the congregation at Smirna city:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sasuri ne, nèti Ja'a, Yesus. Aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i nèti Ja'a, karèi nèti uru ka toke d'ai èle. Uru èèna mema Ja'a madhe, te ngaa limuri ne, Ja'a mamuri hari le. De miu nanene lii padhai Ja'a ne.<bt>This letter here, is from Me, Yesus. Everything originates from Me, beginning from the start/first until the end. Previously I really died, but now I live again. So listen to this speaking of mine.</bt><note reference="2:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 44:6, 48:12, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 1:17, 22:13</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />Ja'a ke'a le j'aj'èra mamuri miu ètu kota Smirna. Masi ka ètu madha dhèu rai-haha, miu unu aad'o, te ngaa ètu madha Lamatua miu kaja. Abhu dhèu dhu mangaku, na, rèngu sèra dhèu unu Lamatua, te ngaa padhai lii pakarehe kolongara miu. Te ngaa madhutu iia-iia na, rèngu se unu boe Lamatua. Rèngu madhutu dhoka dhèu aae nidhu di.<bt>I have seen your life of misery in Smirna city. Even though in the eyes of humans, you here are poor/impoverished, nevertheless in the eyes of the Lord you are rich/wealthy. There are people who acknowledge themselves to be God's people, but they speak making rotten your good name. Whereas in actual fact they, are not God's people. They just follow/obey the evil spirit's king (*Satan). [EXEG: ‘Jews’ here taken as codespeak for a group of people with a special relationship to God. (Also in later verses.) CEV, JG, high level; but commentaries divided.] [NOTE: shifting the “slander” clause to the end would skew the focus. The “I know” phrases signal the writer knows what is causing pain to the readers. From their perspective the symptom is what links empathy to the writer. To background that and front the more abstract reason denudes the potency of the bond.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="thlíipsin: rather close to &quot;presha&quot;, in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">thlíipsin: rather close to "presha", in that it implies circumstances that wear you down bit by bit more than by crisis Ioudaíous: Jewish people. John was a Jew, and there was a big colony of Jews in Smyrna. He is probably not talking ethnically, but in terms of their flaunting their special relationship to God, without the kind of behavior that makes it meaningful. The ethnic name alone could confuse the issue<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>synagoogeè tóu Satanáa: characterizes what their worship amounts too. It shouldn't sound like "the Satanist church is on the next corner; that's where they meet". The implication is "they think they are worshipping God in their ordinary Jewish religious meetings, but they aren't; they're acting like Satan's people even when they are at worship". Deibler has "synagogue or congregation of Jews serving not God but Satan [participant identification, implicature of argument and explication of genitive]" satanáa: Satan, "da guy who stay against us", a name for the Devil<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />De nanene paie-iie. Miu baku madha'u, ladhe abhu j'aj'èra era. Sad'i miu me'a, na, dhèu aae nidhu neo tenge dhèu ho kèpe miu cahag'e, sèna ka pamaso asa d'ara bèdho d'ai canguru lod'o. Dad'èi na, sèna ka miu rai tèke eele Ja'a. Masi ka nidhu neo pamadhe miu èèna ka, te ngaa miu baku bhèlu Ja'a kahèi. Te dhèu cee dhu taha madhutu Ja'a toke madhe, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a pala-bagi ne mamuri, sèna ka na mamuri taa-taa dènge Ja'a.<bt>So, listen well. You don't need to be afraid, if/when later you still obtain/experience difficulty. As long as you know, the king of the evil spirits wants to/is going to/is about find people to capture some of you-pl and put you in jail for ten days. His intent is for you to turn your backs and abandon Me. Even if the evil spirits want to kill you, nevertheless you don't forget Me. Cuz (elaboration) the person/whoever endures following Me until he dies, later I will reciprocate/compensate his/her reward, so that he lives continually together with Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baboa = samping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">baboa = samping</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mélleis: you are about to experience"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">mélleis: you are about to experience something. May carry the overtones of the Divine will and plan; but here it is not advisable to explicitly make God the subject bállein: put somebody in jail, or get somebody put in jail. The Devil will engineer it; this isn't a claim that he will physically push you inside and turn the key in the lock<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>peirasthéete: when the Devil does it, it isn't to prove to him or to you what kind of stuff you are made of inside. It's an assault on your personality to force you to give in to him. So "check out" doesn't fit this context stéphanon: this is a head lei of leaves, given as the first place medal in the Olympic games and other athletic contests. It's not the kind of crown a king would wear, in this context<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Nanene paie-iie, ngaa dhu Roh Lamatua neo peka dènge juma'at Na sèra. Dhèu cee dhu madhutu Ja'a toke madhe, èèna na nèngu abhu boe j'aj'èra ètu d'ara dhasi ai dhu heo robhe-robhe kura boe ciki sa èèna. Dènge sèmi ne'e, nèngu abhu boe mamadhe ka dua hari.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Listen well to what the Lord's Spirit is telling His congregations. The person/whoever endures following Me until s/he dies, later s/he will not be tormented in the fire sea (*hell) which has no letting up even a little. In that way, s/he does not get a second death.’”</bt><note reference="2:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 20:14, 21:8</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'adhu lii moa mi juma'at ètu Pergamus<bt>The Lord Yesus sends instructions to the congregation at Pergamus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, tuhu hari lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis, èu suri more hari ku sasuri leo èci, dhu peka sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>Next that Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man) continued His speaking, saying, “Yohanis, now you must written yet another letter, it's sound is like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mi juma'at ètu kota Pergamus:<bt>&lt;To the congregation at Pergamus:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sasuri ne, nèti Ja'a, Yesus. Ja'a ka dhu kèd'u samala rèka dua dhu madèka. Nanene lii padhai Ja'a.<bt>This letter here, is from Me, that is Yesus. I am who holds a double edge fighting sword that is sharp. Listen to this speaking of Mine.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev 2:1 dístomon: the sword is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev 2:1 dístomon: the sword is sharp along both edges. A machete or a cane knife is sharp along only one edge, but it still has two sides<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />Ja'a ke'a mèu le kota Pergamus miu èèna. Te, dhu nèd'u paredha ètu èèna, nuka dhèu aae nidhu. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa miu kèpe pa'èra kolongara Ja'a, aa parcaya taruu Ja'a. Uru èèna abhu dhèu Ja'a èci ètu èèna, ngara na Antipas. Nèngu aj'a lèke mola-mola j'ara mamuri Ja'a, te ngaa ra pamadhe ne. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa miu pasili boe Ja'a.<bt>I know that Pergamus city of yours. Cuz (elaboration) the that the one who holds authority there, is the king of the evil spirits. Even though it's like that, you still hold tight to My name/reputation, and continue to believe in Me. Previously there was a person of Mine there, named Antipas. He always taught correctly about My way of life, but they killed him. Even though it's like that, nevertheless you do not deny Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katoikéis ... katoikéi: permanent resident thronos:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">katoikéis ... katoikéi: permanent resident thronos: where Satan is king, where he rules. There was a giant altar to Zeus, the main Greek god, on a cliff above the city, and three temples dedicated to the worship of Roman emperors<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>Satanaa: da Devil ónoma: my name -- you are personally loyal to me, you hang on to what you know about my character<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa Ja'a ladhe, na, miu manahu ètu ca j'ara dua j'ara. Abhu nèti miu pèri-pèri dhèu dhu d'èi madhutu lii aj'a-nori nèti Balaam. Uru èèna Balaam aj'a Balak ho kakèj'i dhèu Isra'el, toke ra sisu dad'èi Lamatua. Balak kakèj'i dhèu Isra'el sèra, ho pae'a dènge ra'a-rinu mèdha sogo-tagu, aa ra tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali ra.<bt>But I am seeing, you are falling/lacking in one or two things. There are several people from among you who like to follow Balaam's teaching. Previously Balaam taught Balak to tempt the Israel people, until they transgressed the Lord's will. Balak persuaded/cajoled/ enticed/goaded them to go follow traditional.worship (=non-Christian), and to eat traditional.worship objects' food, and do evil with people who were not their spouse (=usually interpreted sexually). [CHECK carefully /pae'a/ if known, if needs Object, etc. OK]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pae'a = omong deng setan (@@PHON)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pae'a = omong deng setan (@@PHON) --eat food offerred to idols (known by young female UNS's)</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 22:5, 7, 25:1-3, 31:16, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 23:4</note><v n="15" />Abhu kahèi pèri-pèri dhèu nèti miu dhu madhutu lii aj'a-nori nèti Nikolai.<bt>There are also several people among you who follow Nikolai's teachings.</bt><note reference="2:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 2:6</note><v n="16" />De miu hud'i loe ku nèti sasala-sasigo miu sèra. Ladhe aad'o, na, nèbhu heka Ja'a dhiu pad'ui miu dènge lii sakaa dhu nuka sèmi pare dènge samala.<bt>So you must stop from those sins of yours. If not, not much longer, I will come burden you using harsh words that cut like a fighting.sword. [Explication of metonymy and participant identification.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii dhu madhèka = lii dhoo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">lii dhu madhèka = lii dhoo ; lii sakaa = harsh words (from anger, frustrated like parents fed up with a rebellious child) ; dènge lii sakaa dhu nuka sèmi pare miu dènge samala. pad'ui</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="na nèbhu heka Ja'a dhiu pare"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">na nèbhu heka Ja'a dhiu pare miu dènge samala dhu kalua nèti dara hèb'a Ja'a ne.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="romphaíaai: Deibler suggests &quot;come and judge/punish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">romphaíaai: Deibler suggests "come and judge/punish those false teachers by the words I speak [explication of metonymy and participant identification]"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />Nanene paie-iie, ngaa dhu Roh Lamatua peka dènge juma'at Na. Dhèu cee ka dhu taha madhutu Ja'a toke madhe, pe Ja'a hia ne na'a roti <span class="Italic">manna</span> nèti sorga dhu tèke paie iie ne. Pe Ja'a pangèd'u ne hèi, hadhu pudhi cue dhu suri tèke ngara hiu na. Dhodhoka nèngu mesa na di dhu ne'a ngara na; dhèu leo re'a boe.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Listen well to what the Lord's Spirit is telling His congregations. The person/whoever endures following Me to the point of death, later I will give him to eat the <span class="Italic">manna</span> bread from heaven which is put/stored away well. Later I will also give him a white rock on which is written his new name. Only just he himself knows that name; other people don't know [it].”&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev 2:11 kekrymménou: hidden away --"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev 2:11 kekrymménou: hidden away -- a Jewish oral tradition says that when the Jewish temple was about to be destroyed, Jeremiah took the jar of manna that was kept inside the sacred box, and hid it in a cave on Mount Nebo. The idea was that when the Messiah came, God would feed his people with it again. Deibler suggests "I will provide nourishment for their souls which I have hidden/preserved in heaven, like I provided manna for the Israelites [explication of metaphor and OT knowledge]"<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>pséephon: pebble, stone. White symbolizes victory. The stone may be like a pass to get into heaven, or it may carry the judge's "not guilty" verdict, since white and black pebbles were used to tally jury counts</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 16:14-15, 16:33-34, Yohanis 6:48-50, Yesaya 62:2, 65:15</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'adhu lii moa hia juma'at ètu Tiatira<bt>The Lord Yesus sends instructions to the congregation at Tiatira</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ka Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a èèna, tuhu hari lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis, èu suri more hari ku sasuri leo èci, dhu peka sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>Then that Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man) continued His speaking again saying, “Yohanis, now you must write yet another letter, that says like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mi juma'at ètu kota Tiatira:<bt>&lt;To the congregation at Tiatira city:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sasuri ne nèti Ja'a, Yesus, nuka Ana Ama Lamatua. Musi madha Ja'a heo lo'a-lo'a sèmi ai, aa haga Ja'a mea gèu-gèu sèmi tabaga ètu d'ara ai. Nanene ku lii padhai Ja'a.<bt>This letter here, is from Me, Yesus, that is God's Child! My eyes flicker like fire, and My feet shine bright reddish-brown like copper/bronze in the fire. Listen to this speaking of Mine.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 1:15 hoos phlóga pyrós: Deibler"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 1:15 hoos phlóga pyrós: Deibler suggests that the thought behind the figure is "his eyes penetrating with righteous wrath like a flame of fire [explication of symbols]"<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>chalkolibánooi: here "shining brass" is okay, because the detail "as it looks when it is molten" is omitted</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19" />Ja'a kèdhi le mamuri miu. Miu sue Ja'a tare'a, aa parcaya èra Ja'a kahèi. Miu madhutu taruu lii paredha Ja'a ho lalau-lalo'o dhèu. Masi ka dhèu paj'èra miu, te ngaa miu taha taruu. Ja'a ke'a kahèi, limuri ne miu sab'a bia risi hari hia Ja'a.<bt>I have seen your lives. You truly love Me and believe strongly in Me. You always follow my commands to serve people. Even if people cause tribulation to you, nevertheless you continue to endure. I also know that nowadays you are working even harder for Me. [NOTE: "first" or "former" implied by /risi hari/.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="éschata: not &quot;final&quot;, but &quot;most recent&quot;."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">éschata: not "final", but "most recent". This goes along with taking "proótoon" in a relative sense, not "initial", but "earlier" tóon proótoon: earlier, or possibly initially, when you became Christians, when you first believed in me<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa miu manahu ètu ca j'ara: miu sèmi mere dènge be'a, bhèni dhu ngara na Isabel, dhu padedha iisi peka na, nèngu èèna dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua. Ka miu hud'i na sène, aj'a j'ara-j'ara dhu lèke boe mi dhèu Ja'a. Lula lii a'aj'a na dhu kapod'e-kabèli èèna ka, dhèu Ja'a tao j'ara karehe dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali ra, aa ra'a nganga'a sogo-tagu.<bt>But you have fallen in one thing: you accept well that woman named Isabel, who raises herself up saying she [is] the Lord's spokesperson (*prophet). Then you give her opportunity to teach incorrectly My people. Because of that twisted teaching of hers, it's gotten to the point that My people have are doing evil things with people who are not their husband or their wife, and followed eating traditional.worship objects' food. [NOTE to daughter translations: Because of high level issues, for Gk /porneuw/ here, try to find a term that can carry both sexual and moral/loyalty senses, not just a term like ‘adultery’ that is exclusively sexual.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Iezábel: this is not the historical"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Iezábel: this is not the historical Jezebel, the Sidonian princess who married King Ahab and hassled Elijah. This is somebody that has an influence in the Thyatira church that is no better than the influence the first Jezebel had on God's people during her time. The historical Jezebel did not take on the role of a prophetess, nor did she teach. Deibler has "tolerate one who is like wicked queen Jezebel who lived long ago [explication of metaphor and OT knowledge]" planáai: more than telling lies, she influences them to get away from their spiritual identity by getting into promiscuity and idol worship<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ja'a dhu kai le bhèni èèna pèri-pèri hari le, sèna ka ele-ho'a nèti sasala na, te ngaa na d'èi boe.<bt>I have rebuked/forbidden that woman repeatedly, so that she would stop/repent of that sin. But she doesn't want to.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="22" />De ladhe paie-iie. Te Ja'a pama'ète kore le, ho hia ne lèke papèd'a èci, toke na bisa boe puru nèti era j'unu na. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge rèngu dhu j'unu pa'èci dènge ne. Ladhe rèngu tèke eele boe bhèni aapa ne, nèbhu boe Ja'a huku si kahèi.<bt>So (consequently) look well. Cuz (elaboration) now I have decided to judge/punish her with a sickness, until she can't leave her bed. Like that also all the people who sleep with with her. If they don't leave that evil woman, not much longer (=soon) I will also judge/punish them. [NOTE to daughter translations: ‘adultery’ is OK here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eis klíneen: throw her on a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">eis klíneen: throw her on a bed, probably a sick bed; I will punish her with an illness. He doesn't say he's going to dump all her lovers in the same bed too, which was the orgiastic picture I got as a kid because the grammatical gapping was too heavy. The lovers get punished, but in a different way and a different place. Deibler, "I will cause her to suffer punishment as one on a sickbed suffers along with those who participate in her lifestyle (i.e. unfaithfulness to God/adultery) [explication of genitive, metaphor, and metonymy]" moicheúontas met' autées: committing adultery with her -- this is a figure of speech used a lot in the Old Testament and the New to talk about people who are cheating on God. The people John is talking about were probably cheating on both their wives and on God<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Èèna na Ja'a pamadhe aa'i ana-ana nèti bhèni aapa ne. Dènge j'ara ne'e, dhèu-dhèu parcaya sèra re'a, na, Ja'a ne ke'a aa'i d'ara dhèu. Pe Ja'a b'ala miu madhutu tatao dhu miu ad'u-ue.<bt>Later I will kill all the children of this evil woman. In that way, believers will understand that I know the contents of humans' insides/hearts. And later I will reciprocate you according to your deeds.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tékna: followers who listened to her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">tékna: followers who listened to her teaching. The lovers are more like her associates. Deibler has "those who are like her children because they follow her wicked teaching [explication of metaphor]" eraunóon: searching out what is inside, in order to heal or punish<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>doósoo: implies punishment, though the words used are actually neutral -- I will give them whatever reward or punishment they deserve (CHECK PARALLELS).</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 7:10, 62:13, Yermia 17:10</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="24" />Te ngaa miu cahag'e ètu Tiatira sèra, dhu madhutu boe lii a'aj'a bhèni aapa ne. Miu tule eele le a'aj'a dhu pahuni èèna, dhu ra peka na, &lt;ilmu maroga nèti dhèu aae nidhu&gt;. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a parluu heka kai miu,<bt>But the rest of you in Tiatira over there don't follow the teaching of that evil woman. Cuz (elaboration) you have rejected that secret teaching which they call ‘king of evil spirits' dark/black magic’. Because of that, I don't need to scold/rebuke you any more,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ngaa Ja'a ke'a na miu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Te ngaa Ja'a ke'a na miu dhu leo ètu Tiatira sèra, madhutu boe lii a'aj'a nèti bhèni aapa ne. Te miu dhu tule eele le a'aj'a dhu pahuni èèna, dhu ra peka na, &lt;ilmu maroga nèti dhèu aae nidhu&gt;. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a parluu heka kai miu,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ouk égnoosan: have never gotten into"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">ouk égnoosan: have never gotten into this stuff. Deibler has "who have not learned/experienced the immoral lifestyle inspired by Satan [explication of `deep things' and genitive]" Satanaa: da Devil<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />sad'i miu kèpe pa'èra-èra lalèka miu mi dedha Ja'a, toke Ja'a lèpa hari mai.<bt>as long as you-pl hold firmly to your faith until I come.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="échete: your Christian commitment. Deibler has"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">échete: your Christian commitment. Deibler has "hold fast to the spiritual truth and zeal that you have [concept identification]"</Message></Annotation><v n="26-28" />Dhèu cee dhu taha madhutu Ja'a toke madhe, pe Ja'a hia ne koasa. Koasa èèna kapai, nuka sèmi koasa dhu Ja'a abhu nèti Ama Ku, ho paredha dhèu ètu rai-haha ne dènge tatea bèsi. Ladhe abhu dhu lab'a ne, pe na ab'o palaho si, nuka sèmi dhèu pamae èru rai.<bt>The person/whoever endures following Me to the point of death, later I will give him power/authority. That aforementioned authority is great, like the power-authority which I received from My Father, to command all the nations in the world with an iron staff. If there are those who oppose him, later he will destroy them, like a person breaks a earthern/clay pot. [NOTE to daughter translations: if "tangan besi" doesn't communicate, try "tongkat besi"]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ab'o = tumbuk, alu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ab'o = tumbuk, alu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The line marked m2 here should"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">The line marked m2 here should come left to be even with the second line in verse 26. en rábdooi sideeráai: with an iron-capped club. Rule them ruthlessly and not let anybody get out of line. We talk about "iron authority". Deibler has "rule over and destroy those opposed to him with severe judgment and destruction as earthen pots are destroyed with a rod of iron [participant identification and explication of metaphor]"<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="2:26-27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:8-9</note>Èèna na, Ja'a hia miu hua-hètu dhimu kahèi.<bt>Later I also will give the east star to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hua hètu dhimu = bintang fajar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hua hètu dhimu = bintang fajar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Venus or Mercury when they shine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Venus or Mercury when they shine early in the morning. Deibler has "my presence which will shine like the morning star (OR, he will receive glory as the shining of the morning star) [explication of metaphor and wider contextual information]"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="29" />Nanene paie-iie, ngaa dhu Roh Lamatua neo peka dènge juma'at Na sèra.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So! Listen well to what the Lord's Spirit wants to say to His congregations.”&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'adhu lii moa hia juma'at ètu Sardis<bt>The Lord Yesus sends instructions to the congregation at Sardis</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne lii hari dènge ja'a, aku nèngu Na, &lt;&lt;Èu suri more hari ku sasuri leo èci, dhu isi na sèmi ne'e:<bt>Then that Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man) continued speaking with me, saying, “You must write yet another letter, it's contents are like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mi juma'at ètu kota Sardis:<bt>&lt;To the congregation at Sardis city:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sasuri ne, nèti Ja'a, Yesus. Roh Ama Lamatua ètu Ja'a. Aa Roh ne, pidhu rupa. Ja'a dhu kèpe kahèi pidhu hua-hètu ètu d'ara ai Ja'a. Nanene lii padhai Ja'a.<bt>This letter here, is from Me, that is Yesus. God's Spirit is upon/exists in Me. And that Spirit has seven faces/facets/manifestations. I also am the one who holds seven stars in my hand. Listen to this speaking of mine (=what I have to say). [EXEG: see discussion and ftn at 1:4.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a ke'a le tatao miu ètu Sardis. Dhèu peka, na, miu se mamuri madhutu dad'èi Ja'a, te ngaa miu nuka sèmi samanga aad'o ètu kètu.<bt>I have seen your doings in Sardis. There are people who say you really live according to My will, whereas in actual fact you are as if you have no lifeforce in your head. [EXEG: life = reputation for spiritual vitality; see Mounce, Hughes]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="te ngaa miu oe madhe kèna."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">te ngaa miu oe madhe kèna.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />De kèd'i ka! Pa'èra parcaya miu dhu oe èle na. Te Ja'a dhu parisa le ngaa dhu miu sab'a, abhu boe dhu mèci ètu madha Ama Lamatua.<bt>So get/wake up! Strengthen that faith of yours which is almost gone. Cuz (elaboration) I have examined those deeds of yours, and there are none which are clean/orderly/right in God's eyes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gínou greegoróon: become alert, get with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">gínou greegoróon: become alert, get with it (not what you would usually say to a dead man) steérison: put a solid support under the other things<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>émellon apothanéin: on the point of death, Christian virtues that were about to disappear from their lives pepleerooména: brought to completion -- you start things and never finish them. Could also mean up to my standards, everything they are supposed to be<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />De baku bhèlu lii aj'a-nori dhu mola, dhu miu nanene aa abhu nèti uru èèna. Madhutu paie-iie dad'èi Ama Lamatua, aa tèke eele sasala-sasigo miu sèra. Ladhe miu kèd'i malai boe, ho mi tao madhutu j'ara sèra, cag'ag'a laa Ja'a dhiu nuka sèmi dhèu mana'u dhu miu me'a mere boe.<bt>So (consequently), don't forget all that straight/correct teaching which you have heard and accepted from before. Truly follow the Lord's will, and leave your wrongs. If you don't get up quickly to do like that, later I will come suddenly like a thief, whom you do not really know/expect.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mase'a = sadar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mase'a = sadar</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 24:43-44, Lukas 12:39-40, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 16:15</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa abhu cahag'e era nèti miu ètu Sardis dhu mamuri mola, nuka sèmi dhèu dhu pakaj'alu boe mèdha-papake ra. Lula miu mamuri mola, ka miu nia kako palere-lere dènge Ja'a, pake mèdha-papake pudhi.<bt>But there are still some of you in Sardis who live straight/right, like people who don't dirty their clothes. Because of your straight/righteous lives, later you are the ones who are appropriate/worthy to walk together with Me wearing white clothes. [NOTE: Dhao shifts to 2p for context and genre reasons]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="olíga: a few people leukà: white,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">olíga: a few people leukà: white, symbolizing purity<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Dhèu cee dhu taha madhutu Ja'a toke madhe, bèli-camèd'a nèngu pake mèdha-papake pudhi kahèi. Bèli-camèd'a Ja'a roso eele boe ngara na nèti d'ara sasuri dhu suri ngara dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu èèna na mamuri taa-taa dènge Lamatua. Èèna na Ja'a mangaku ne ètu madha Ama Ku, dènge ètu madha ana pajuu Ama Ku ètu sorga, peka na, nèngu ne dhèu Ja'a.<bt>The person/whoever endures following My way of life to the point of death, later he will also wear white clothes. In the future I will not erase his name from that writing which lists all the people's names who will live continually with the Lord. Later I will also acknowledge him in front of My Father, and in front of My Father's underlings/angels in heaven, saying he is my person.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roso = hapus, gosok (writing from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">roso = hapus, gosok (writing from a list) ~ saku = sweep,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 2:7"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 2:7</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 32:32-33, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:29, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 2:7, 20:12, Mateos 10:32, Lukas 12:8</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Nanene paie-iie, ngaa dhu Roh Lamatua peka dènge juma'at Na sèra.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So! Listen well to what the Lord's Spirit is telling His congregations.”&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'adhu lii moa hia juma'at ètu Piladelfia<bt>The Lord Yesus sends instructions to the congregation at Piladelfia</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis, èu hud'i suri more hari ku sasuri leo èci, dhu lii na sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>Then that Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man) spoke on again, saying, “Yohanis, now you must write yet another letter, it's sound/message is like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mi juma'at ètu kota Piladelfia:<bt>&lt;To the congregation at Piladelfia city:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sasuri ne nèti Ja'a, Yesus. Ja'a dhu Mola-Mèci dènge dhu Lèke Tare'a. Ja'a ka dhu kèd'u gagoe dhèu aae Daud. Ladhe Ja'a bhoke kore babèdho, abhu boe ca dhèu sa bisa bèdho hari. Ladhe Ja'a bèdho kore, abhu boe ca dhèu sa bisa bhoke.<bt>This letter here, is from Me, Yesus. I here, am who is Holy/Clean and True. I am who hold's king Daud's key. If I open a door, there is no one who can close it again. If I close [it], there is no one who can open [it].</bt><note reference="3:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 22:22, Ayub 12:14</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Ja'a ke'a aa'i ngaa dhu miu tao. Ja'a ke'a kahèi, pangaru miu kapai boe. Masi ka sèmi èèna, miu pasili boe Ja'a, aa madhutu taruu lii a'aj'a Ja'a. Sanèd'e paie, te Ja'a dhu conge le babèdho hia miu, de dhèu èci sa bisa boe bèdho hari.<bt>I know all that which you have done. I also know your influence is not great. Even though it's like that, you don't deny Me, and [you] continue to follow My teaching. Remember well, cuz (elaboration) I have opened the door for you, so there is no one who can close [it] again. [EXEG: “little strength/power” has a broad range of interpretations (Ex. Summ). The meaning of “few people” is a minority possibility with little support, so keep it broader.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="conge = bhoke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">conge = bhoke</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="thýran eeneooigméneen: a door that has"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">thýran eeneooigméneen: a door that has already been opened and is still open -- symbol of opportunity to serve or to preach the Gospel, or to enter God's kingdom freely mikràn: you have a little power, but not a lot -- still, it's enough that you can do something<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>dýnamin: clout, prestige in the community, good reputation with leverage about getting things done eteéreesas: you have kept what I told you, you've done it and not let it get away from you<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />Nanene paie-iie! Te abhu dhèu leko-monya dhu peka na, rèngu sèra dhèu unu Lamatua. Te ngaa rèngu sèra, dhèu kapod'e-kabèli dhu madhutu dhèu aae nidhu. Pe me'a unu mi! Ja'a tao si, sèna ka ra dhiu patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha miu, aa ra mangaku na, Ja'a tare'a-re'a sue miu.<bt>Listen carefully! Cuz (elaboration) there are people who lie saying that they are God2's people. But they are deceivers, who follow/obey the king of the evil spirits. But later you will just see for yourselves (=watch what will happen!). I will make them come kneel in front of you, and acknowledge that I truly love you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Satanaa: da Devil See Rev. 2:9|i(9)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Satanaa: da Devil See Rev. 2:9<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="3:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 49:23, 60:14, 43:4</note><v n="10" />Lula miu madhutu le paredha Ja'a, ka miu taha madhutu Ja'a, nèti èèna ka, Ja'a bhabhae miu nèti j'aj'èra dhu Lamatua neo hia mai, ho sèku dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Because you have followed My command to endure following Me, that's why later I will protect you well from the suffering that God will sent to test all in this world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhabhae = pele ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bhabhae = pele ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Nèbhu heka, Ja'a dhiu. De miu kèpe pa'èra-èra lii aj'a-nori Ja'a, dhu miu abhu le karèi nèti uru ka. Te mage dhoka abhu dhu parame rare rui-j'aj'èra dhu Lamatua neo b'ala hia miu.<bt>Not much longer I will come. So (consequently) hold tightly to My teaching which you have accepted from long ago. Cuz (elaboration) may it not be that someone snatches away your reward which God2 wants to give you. [EXEG: crown = reward (for service/faithfulness, not salvation)]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rui j'aj'èra = upah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">rui j'aj'èra = upah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ladhe miu madhutu lii aj'a-nori"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Te ladhe miu madhutu lii aj'a-nori dhu leo, èèna na ele aa'i ngaa dhu Lamatua neo bala hia miu.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="See Rev. 2:25, 10."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">See Rev. 2:25, 10.</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Dhèu cee ka dhu taha madhutu Ja'a toke madhe, bèli-camèd'a nèngu pea taruu dènge Lamatua, sama sèmi agarii aae dhu titu mèno ètu d'ara Èmu Ama Lamatua. Pe Ja'a suri ngara Lamatua Ja'a, dènge ngara kota Lamatua ètu ngi'u dhèu ne. Kota èèna ra pangare, na, &lt;Yerusalem Hiu&gt;, dhu bèli-camèd'a Lamatua papuru mai nèti sorga. Aa èèna na, Ja'a suri kahèi ngara hiu Ja'a mi ngi'u dhèu ne.<bt>The person/whoever endures following Me to the point of death, later he will live continually with the Lord, like a big pole/pillar that is placed/stood firmly in God's House. Later I will write My Lord's name, and the Lord's city's name on that person's body. That city there, they refer to as ‘New Yerusalem’, which later the Lord will send down from heaven. And later I will also write my new name on that person's body.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="See Rev. 2:7."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">See Rev. 2:7.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 21:2, Yesaya 62:2, 65:15</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />Nanene paie-iie, ngaa dhu Roh Ama Lamatua peka mi juma'at Na sèra.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So! Listen well to what the God's Spirit is telling His congregations.”&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="See Rev. 2:7."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">See Rev. 2:7.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'adhu lii moa hia juma'at ètu Laodikia<bt>The Lord Yesus sends instructions to the congregation at Laodikia</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èle ka, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, tuhu hari lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis, èu hud'i suri more ku sasuri dhu limuri tèka, dhu isi na sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>Then that Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man) continued speaking, saying, “Yohanis, now you must write the final letter, it's contents are like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mi juma'at ètu kota Laodikia:<bt>&lt;To the congregation at Laodikia city:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sasuri ne nèti Ja'a, Yesus, dhu dhèu paroa na, &lt;Tare'a sèmi èèna&gt;. Ja'a ne loe boe padhai lii dènge mola Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua. Dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu Lamatua ad'u-ue sèra, j'aj'aj'i ra nèti Ja'a.<bt>This letter is from Me, Yesus, whom people call, saying &lt;It's True like that&gt;. I here, always speak truthfully God's Words. And all those things which the Lord has made, they originate from Me.</bt><note reference="3:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Hini 8:22</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />Ja'a ladhe kèdhi le tatao miu ètu Laodikia. Te ngaa miu sèmi ngaa mèro?! Pana aad'o, aa pacuhi aad'o kahèi. Ladhe pana, na, hud'i tare'a-re'a pana! Aa ladhe pacuhi, na, hud'i tare'a-re'a pacuhi!<bt>I have seen your deeds in Laodikia. But how is it with you? Hot, no, not cold either. If [you're going to be] hot, na, be truly hot! If [you're going to be] cold, na, be truly cold!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèro = idiomatic particle, speaker attitude"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mèro = idiomatic particle, speaker attitude ; pamèro = panggil kucing ; camèro = suka makan bagi yang hamil, nafsu makan, cravings</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="psychròs: cold, indifferent, don't care zestòs:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">psychròs: cold, indifferent, don't care zestòs: hot, enthusiastic, pumping<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Te ngaa, lula d'ara miu kajari, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a sabhuu eele miu nèti d'ara hèb'a Ja'a, sama sèmi dhèu sabhuu ilu.<bt>But because your insides are branched/uncertain/double-minded, I'm going to spit expel you from My mouth, like a person spits expels saliva. [EXEG: Gk aspect is explicit “I'm about to (spit)”. So try and get it more precise than just ‘later’ or ‘will’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kajari = bacabang = kacanga (more"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kajari = bacabang = kacanga (more like hati mendua, bimbang ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />Miu padhai lii padedha iisi, peka na, &lt;Ji'i se, kaja-su'i. Ji'i mamuri be'a, kura boe ngaa-ngaa!&gt; Te ngaa madhutu iia-iia na, d'ara miu dhu bèdhu le, ka me'a heka mia ka dhu be'a. Nèti èèna ka, miu j'aj'i mi dhèu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa, aa dhu dènge boe mèdha ètu ua mi.<bt>You speak proudly/arrogantly [negative: superiority, not justifiable pride], saying, ‘We here, are rich people. We live well, not lacking anything!&gt; While in actual fact, your insides are blind, and you don't know which (of choices) is good. That's why you have become like a destitute poor and naked person/people. [EXEG: See Ex. Summ. for basis of 3rd sentence--both mental and spiritual blindness. LN, BAGD, HCE]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="talaípooros: pathetic, wretched, in bad shape"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">talaípooros: pathetic, wretched, in bad shape eleeinos: pitiable<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />De hua iia mai ho hèli mere poe-pai nèti Ja'a, sèna ka miu tare'a-re'a j'aj'i dhèu kaja-su'i. Aa hèli mere mèdha-papake pudhi, ho pahutu era makae mi. Aa hèli mere kahèi èi na'i musi madha, sèna ka roso mi musi madha miu, ho mèdhi mèu hari.<bt>So (consequently) it's better if you come buy pure/original gold from Me, so that you become people who are truly rich. And buy white clothes to cover that embarrassment place of yours. And buy eye medicine to rub in your eyes, so that you can see again clearly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poe-pai = mas tulen ; roso"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">poe-pai = mas tulen ; roso = gosok</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19" />Ladhe dhèu pasue Ja'a tao sala, Ja'a kai aa huku si, sèna ka ra j'aj'i be'a. De miu hud'i pamola d'ara mi, ho madhutu Ja'a dènge d'ara kateme.<bt>If people whom I love do wrong, I scold/rebuke and punish them, so that they become good. So you must straighten your insides, so that you follow/obey Me wholeheartedly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zeéleue: the opposite of lukewarm --"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">zeéleue: the opposite of lukewarm -- get enthusiastic, charged up</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Hini 3:12, Ibrani 12:6</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="20" />Nanene paie-iie. Te Ja'a nuka titu ètu hèb'a èmu ne, aa Ja'a paroa taruu ho neo maso asa d'ara èmu. Ladhe dhèu cee dhu tadèngi lii Ja'a, ho na conge èmu, Ja'a dhiu asa d'ara, sèna ka madhèdi ta'a-tinu pa'èci.<bt>Listen well, cuz (elaboration) I have stood at the front of the door, and I keep calling wanting to enter. If there is a person who hears my voice, then he comes open the house, I will go inside, so that the we can eat together. [knock &gt; voice/call = symbolic action]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="conge ~ conga = buka"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">conge ~ conga = buka</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="deipneésoo: have a meal, regardless of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">deipneésoo: have a meal, regardless of the time of day kroúoo: knock, asking but not demanding to be let inside<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>anoíxeei: open and invite somebody inside the house</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Dhèu cee dhu taha madhutu Ja'a toke madhe, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a pangèd'u ne hak, ho nèd'u paredha bera-bera dènge Ja'a. Te Ja'a taha le madhutu Ama Ku kahèi, nèti èèna ka limuri ne Ja'a kèd'u paredha sama-sama dènge Ne.<bt>The person/whoever endures following My way of life to the point of death, later I will give him the right/authority, to rule together with Me. Cuz (elaboration) I also have endured following My Father, that's why now I sit ruling together with Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="22" />Nanene paie-iie, ngaa dhu Roh Lamatua peka mi juma'at Na sèra.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So! Listen well to what the Lord's Spirit is telling His congregations.”&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rèngu pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua ètu sorga<bt>They worship Father God in heaven</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, peka nare lii moa Na mi pidhu juma'at sèra, hèia Lamatua bhoke pad'elo dènge ja'a, ngaa-ngaa dhu leo hari. Ètu d'ara ciki oo'e èèna kahèi, ja'a kèdhi babèdho èci dhu bhoke le tangare la'e asa sorga. Ka ja'a tadèngi hari lii dhu mèdhu nèti dhèu deo na, nuka sèmi lii tiu tèbhe, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai ku! Ca'e asa ne'e, sèna ka Ja'a pad'elo dènge èu ngaa-ngaa dhu j'aj'i bèli-camèd'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>That Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man) finished speaking his requests to those seven congregations, then the Lord revealed yet other things to me. Suddenly, I saw a door opening facing heaven. Then I heard again that person's whose voice was loud like a trumpet, saying, “Come on! Come up here, so that I can show you things that will happen later.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="voice like a trumpet Rev. 1:10."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">voice like a trumpet Rev. 1:10. "Trumpet" OK; "horn" would be like a car horn. éidon: I saw, referring to a vision as in 1:12. Like a dream, but seen when the person is awake<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>deíxoo: "goin show" sounds like a more distant future than "like show"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Lod'o èèna kahèi, Roh Lamatua ded'e nèti ja'a asa sorga. Cag'ag'a laa, ja'a kèdhi kadera paredha èci, aa abhu dhu madhèdi ètu dedha.<bt>At that time then the Lord's Spirit lifted took me to heaven. Suddenly I saw a ruling chair which had someone sitting on it.</bt><v n="3" />Dhu madhèdi ètu kadera èèna heo mangèru dènge mea, èci èèna ka dènge hadhu kale'e dhu kab'ua, dhu ra peka na, <span class="Italic">yaspis</span> dènge <span class="Italic">sardius.</span> Abhu kahèi saroo èci dhu reo nare kadera paredha Na. Saroo ne heo na mangèru sama sèmi hadhu kale'e <span class="Italic">samrud.</span><bt>He radiated blue-green and reddish-brown, like jewel stones that are expensive which they refer to as <span class="Italic">jaspis</span> and <span class="Italic">sardius.</span> There was also a rainbow surrounding that ruling chair. It's radiance, was a blue-green colour like the <span class="Italic">samrud</span> jewel. [NOTE: colours, etc. relating to precious stones from Loewen, TH, Martins article.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saroo = pelangi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">saroo = pelangi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="homoios horasie: had a visual effect"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">homoios horasie: had a visual effect like that of a ... (two times)</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:2-3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 1:26-28, 10:1</note><v n="4" />Ètu èèna kahèi, abhu 24 (dua nguru èpa) kadera paredha iiki, dhu reo rare kadera paredha dhu ètu talora aae èèna. Ètu dedha kadera paredha iiki se'e, madhèdi katua 24 (dua nguru èpa) dhèu. Aa'i-aa'i ra pake mèdha-papake pudhi, dènge solo paredha dhu tao nèti hualaa.<bt>There there were also 24 other ruling chairs surrounding that ruling chair in the middle. There were 24 elders/leaders who sat in those chairs. They all wore white clothes, and wore ruling hats made from gold.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katua = kepala dari satu kumpulan,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">katua = kepala dari satu kumpulan, ketua organisasi ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="presbytérous: though tradition adds up the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">presbytérous: though tradition adds up the twelve apostles and the twelve tribe leaders to get 24, these act more like heavenly citizens than like people with an earthly connection, or like ordinary church "elders" leukóis: white may suggest purity, or victory, or immortality<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>crown made from gold, not solid gold</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Nèti kadera paredha ètu talora aae èèna, abhu bela dhu kacèb'a, dènge d'oro dhu lii mèdhu patuu ma'èta boe. Abhu kahèi ob'o pidhu bua dhu heo ètu madha kadera paredha èèna. Rèngu se, nuka sèmi Roh Ama Lamatua dhu pidhu rupa.<bt>There was lightning that struck out from the midst of those ruling chairs, and thunder that rumbled on loudly. There were also seven torches that burned/shone in front of that ruling chair. Those were like God's Spirit which seven faces/facets/ manifestations. [EXEG: see discussion and ftn at 1:4. Make parallel with 3:1.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patuu = 1) bersambung, 2) kasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">patuu = 1) bersambung, 2) kasi berlabuh ; obo = obor</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pneúmata: not ghosts, but unseen beings"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">pneúmata: not ghosts, but unseen beings with personalities that can influence people. It may be a symbolic way of talking about the Holy Spirit. Attach "good", because people are acquainted with other spirits that are not good. [But P&amp;S say only good spirits would come from God, so do not need to say 'good'.] lampádes pyròs: fixed torches that burn with a visible flame. Not lamps that burn oil, but torches that themselves burn on top.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="4:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 19:16, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 1:4, 8:5, 11:19, 16:18, Yeskial 1:13, Sakaria 4:2</note><v n="6" />Ètu madha kadera paredha ne, ja'a kèdhi èi, oe sèmi dhasi dhu mèu aadha-aadha nuka sèmi tèru.<bt>In front of that ruling chair, I saw as if there was a sea that was clear like glass.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèu aadha-aadha = bersih sekali, jernih"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mèu aadha-aadha = bersih sekali, jernih ; tèru = 1) cermin ; tèru huhu = ambil ikan (dalam bubuk)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="A pool like the reflecting pool"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">A pool like the reflecting pool in front of the State Capitol building, part of the architecture. King Solomon had one at his palace.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ja'a kèdhi badha èpa ngi'u dhu dhae kèdhi mèka ciki sa rai-reo kadera èèna. Ngi'u ra nèti madha toke kabodho, pènu dènge musi madha. Badha se'e ka dhu lalau-lalo'o Lamatua.<bt>Then I saw there were four extra-ordinary animals around that chair. Their bodies front-back were full of eyes. These animals were the ones who served/attended the Lord. [EXEG: “in the midst” made implicit; although vs. 6 isn't clear, the info in vs. 8 gives fuller info allowing us to say here that the eyes are on their bodies, not just on their heads. “Served” from higher level context (vs.8-11, etc) signals that these fearsome creatures were not a threat. Required here as part of background intro to them.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Re cabèka kadera paredha dhu ètu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Re cabèka kadera paredha dhu ètu talora aae.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kyklóoi: next to the throne, one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">kyklóoi: next to the throne, one on each of its four sides</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 1:22</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Badha ka èci, rèhu na sèmi singa. Ka dua, rèhu na sèmi sapi mone. Ka tèlu, rèhu na sèmi dhèu. Aa ka èpa, rèhu na nuka sèmi manea luji dhu lela.<bt>That first animal's face, was like a lion. The second's face, was like a bull. The third's face, was like a human. And the fourth's face, was like a white-bellied sea eagle that was flying. [NOTE: this is the one type of eagle they see on their small island of Dhao.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manea luji = elang puti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">manea luji = elang puti</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moschóoi: young bull, calf"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">moschóoi: young bull, calf</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:7" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu dhèu d'èlu-mèu Sasuri Mola-Mèci, ra peka na, èpa badha se nuka: Singa ka dhu koasa risi eele. Sapi ka dhu èra risi eele. Dhèu ka dhu d'èlu-mèu risi eele. Aa manea luji ka dhu mèri risi eele.<bt>According to experts on the Bible, they say these four animals meaning is: The lion, is the one who is most powerful. The cow, is the one who is the strongest. Humans, are the ones who are the smartest. And the eagle, is the one who is the fastest.</bt></note><note reference="4:6-7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 1:5-10, 10:14</note><v n="8" />Badha èpa ngi'u se, ci'u-ci'u ka dhu dènge èla ra, èna. Re li'u dènge re d'ara èla se, pènu dènge musi madha kahèi. Mèu-mèda, badha se loe boe sod'a, peka na,<bt>Those four animals, each one had six wings. On those wings inside part and outside part, were also full of eyes. Day-night they sang without stopping, saying, [EXEG: NLT has wings covered with eyes; CEV has bodies covered with eyes; NRSV is vague. Gk “they are full of eyes” could refer grammatically to the wings or the creatures as a whole. KM has both covered, saying ‘bodies’ in vs. 6 and ‘wings’ in vs. 8.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ji'i koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua!<bt>“We keep praising God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Lamatua!<bt>We lift up high God's name/reputation!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua èèna, dhu mola-mèci risi eele!<bt>God is the one, who is most holy/clean!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Koasa Lamatua dhu kapai risi eele.<bt>God is the one, whose power/authority is greatest.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua èèna karèi nèti uru ka mai.<bt>That God existed from long ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua dhu deo ne'e ne.<bt>God is who exists now.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa Lamatua dhu taa-taa toke d'ai mia-mia la'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>God is who will continue forever!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="légontes: the Greek word is nonspecific"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">légontes: the Greek word is nonspecific about the mode of utterance, but it isn't conversation. Chanting is a part of all ethnic Hawaiian rituals, which other people are familiar with from television, and it is also part of the Buddhist heritage Rev. 1:4, 1:8.<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="4:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 1:18, 10:12, Yesaya 6:2-3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Dènge ra sod'a sèmi èèna, rèngu koa-kio dènge pakab'ua Ama Lamatua, aa ra manèngi makasi mi Nèngu kahèi, lula Nèngu ka dhu madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha èèna, aa Nèngu ka dhu taa-taa toke d'ai mia-mia. Ropa rèngu sod'a,<bt>By singing like that, they praised and gave respect/honour to God, and also requested/reciprocated thankyou to Him, because He was the one who sat on that ruling chair, and who is forever. When they were singing,</bt><v n="10" />hèia 24 (dua nguru èpa) katua sèra pabèbha iisi ra, ka patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha Ama Lamatua, dhu madhèdi ètu kadera paredha èèna. Katua se bhoke eele solo paredha ra, ka ra tèke mi madha kadera paredha èèna, ho pahaha iisi mi Nèngu dhu mamuri taa-taa dènge boe too-lane. Èle ka, ra koa-kio Ne, peka na,<bt>those 24 elders fell kneeling in front of God who was sitting in that ruling chair. They took off their ruling hats, then put them in front of that ruling chair of His, to worship Him who lives continually. They praised Him, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="balóusin: throw, implying that the honor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">balóusin: throw, implying that the honor they have is no big deal compared to God. But in Pidgin throwing them on the ground would imply that they are disgusted with God, so it sounds better to say that they place them there carefully, which allows for respect légontes: as in v 8, they aren't just talking. But 24 people together don't chant in this culture (four can, if it's antiphonal), so with the rhythm of the words it has to be taken to be more like singing<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />&lt;&lt;Ooo, Ama Lamatua!<bt>“O Lord God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i koa-kio kolongara Lamatua!<bt>We praise God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Lamatua.<bt>We lift up high God's name/reputation.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua ne, Kètu ji'i.<bt>This Lord, is our Head.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua ne, Ama Lamatua ji'i!<bt>This Lord, is our Father God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu nia sèmi more koa-kio ji'i.<bt>God is the one who is appropriate/worthy to receive our praise.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu pantas sèmi lii pakab'ua ji'i.<bt>God is the one who certainly must receive our respect/honour.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Lamatua ka dhu koasa kapai risi eele.<bt>Because God is who has the greatest power/authority.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Lamatua ka dhu dedha risi eele.<bt>And God is who is the highest (status, rank, position).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu paj'aj'i aa'i-aa'i.<bt>God is who created everything.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu hia mamuri aa'i-aa'i.<bt>God is who gives life to everything.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa'i-aa'i dhu tesa,<bt>Everything that exists,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">j'aj'i, lula Lamatua ka dhu ad'u-ue.<bt>has happened because it's God who created it (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri,<bt>Everything that lives,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dènge a'ae, lula Lamatua ka dhu hia.&gt;&gt;<bt>has breath because it's God who gave it.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="to receive glory, and honor, and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">to receive glory, and honor, and power: people giving God these things Exist: This needs to include both living and inanimate things. In Acts 17:28: "live and move and have our being": "...stay an move an do everyting."<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lalulu sasuri dhu segel madhe<bt>The rolled writing that is sealed up</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a ladhe hari Nèngu dhu madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha èèna. Na kèpe dènge sasuri ca lulu ètu ai g'ana Na. Ètu lalulu sasuri ne, dhu suri le re li'u dènge d'ara. Ra segel le ètu pidhu era.<bt>After that, I saw again at He who sat in that ruling chair. He held a *scroll (Lit: rolled up writing) in His right hand. That scroll was full of writing outside and inside. And they (non-referential) had sealed it shut in seven places.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalulu = gulungan ; pakadite ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">lalulu = gulungan ; pakadite = lem (getah pohon) stick from inside, kadite = lem getah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katesphragisménon: it had wax seals along"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">katesphragisménon: it had wax seals along the edge and on the strings so that the only way to see what it said would be to break the seals. But the seals were not broken yet. Still, no need to mention the string, which isn't in the text.</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 2:9-10, Yesaya 29:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Hèia ja'a kèdhi ana pajuu nèti sorga ca dhèu dhu kapai aae. Dènge lii aae, na karèi, &lt;&lt;Dhèu cee ka dhu dènge hak ho bisa bhoke segel aa baca sasuri ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I saw an angel from heaven who was very great. He asked in a loud voice, saying, “Who has the right/authority to open those seals and read that writing?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="iskhyròn: not just physically strong, but"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">iskhyròn: not just physically strong, but having a lot of clout, an important angel áxios: qualified, has the right, he deserves to get it<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Na karèi sèmi èèna ka, te ngaa ra abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu dènge hak, ho bisa bhoke dènge baca isi sasuri ne. Masi ka ètu sorga, do ètu rai-haha ne, abhu boe èci sa hèi dhu dènge hak. Ètu era dhèu madhe, aad'o kahèi.<bt>He asked like that, but they did not find even one person who had the right/authority to open that writing and read its contents. Not in heaven, nor on earth, there was no one who had the right. In the dead people's place, there was not anyone either.</bt><v n="4" />Ropa kèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia ja'a tangi d'ara pèd'a, lula abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu dènge hak ho bisa bhoke sasuri aa baca isi na.<bt>Seeing like that, then I wept bitterly, because there was not even one who had the right to open that writing and read its contents.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heuréthee: does not imply a search,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">heuréthee: does not imply a search, but just that there was nobody qualified</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Èle ka, ca dhèu nèti dua nguru èpa katua se'e, lii dènge ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku tangi, we. Te ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud ca dhèu dhu kapai risi eele, dhu ra haji ngara Na, &lt;Singa nèti udhu-rasa Yahuda&gt;. Nèngu ka dhu ab'o palaho le aa'i-aa'i dhu bhelu-katub'a. De Nèngu ka dhu dènge hak, sèna ka bisa bhoke segel aa baca isi sasuri ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then one of those 24 elders, spoke with me, saying, “Don't cry. Cuz (elaboration) king Daud has a descendant who is great/amazing, whom they give a symbolic name/title, saying, ‘Lion (loan) from Yahuda clan/tribe&gt;. He has smashed destroyed all that is evil. So (consequently), He has the right to open that seal and read that writing's contents.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haji ngara = kasi symbol nama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">haji ngara = kasi symbol nama ~ ama Ben (Bentama) ~ ina Ben</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 49:9, Yesaya 11:1, 10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa tadèngi kore lii ne'e, ja'a kèdhi Ana Kahib'i-Kalèbho dhu titu ètu talora aae badha èpa ngi'u sèra, dènge 24 (dua nguru èpa) katua dhu madhèdi reo rare kadera paredha èèna. Ana Kahib'i-Kalèbho ne, oe sèmi dhu ra pamadhe le. Nèngu ne dènge tadhu pidhu, aa musi madha Na pidhu kahèi. Musi madha pidhu sèra, nuka sèmi Roh Na dhu dènge pidhu rupa, dhu Na papuru mai palème rai-haha ne.<bt>Hearing like that, then I saw a Sheep Offspring standing in the middle of those four animals, and those 24 elders who sat around that ruling chair. That Sheep Offspring there, it was as if it had once been murdered/killed. His horns were seven, and his eyes were seven. Those seven eyes of his, were like His Spirit which has seven faces/facets/manifestations, whom He had sent to the whole world. [NOTE to daughter translations: review note at 1:4; follow solution consistent with 1:4, 3:1 &amp; 4:6 re: 7 spirits, but remember here they are sent to 7 locations, so has to make sense.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tadhu = tanduk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">tadhu = tanduk</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 53:7, Sakaria 4:10</note><v n="7" />Hèia ja'a ladhe kèdhi Ana Kalèbho ne, kako la'e asa madha Nèngu dhu madhèdi ètu kadera paredha èèna, sèna ka sèmi nare lalulu sasuri nèti ai g'ana Na.<bt>Then I saw that Sheep Offspring go to the One who was sitting in that ruling chair, and take/receive that rolled writing from His right hand.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eíleephen: he took it -- not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">eíleephen: he took it -- not snatching it away, but receiving it because he was qualified to take it</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ropa Ana Kalèbho ne sèmi nare sasuri, cag'ag'a laa badha èpa ngi'u, dènge 24 (dua nguru èpa) katua sèra, pabèbha iisi ra, ka ra patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha Na. Rèngu se èci-èci ka kèpe mèdha lii sod'a oe sèmi sasadhu sa, dènge mago hualaa dhu isi dènge raa aj'u hèu mèngi, sèna ka ra pasèbu ho pahèu mèngi. Raa aj'u hèu mèngi se'e ka, nuka lii manèngi-mangaj'i nèti dhèu unu Lamatua.<bt>When He received it, suddenly those four aforementioned animals there, and those 24 elders there, fell kneeling in front of Him. They each one held a musical instrument similar to a sasando, and a golden bowl, which was filled with resin which they burned to make sweet smelling smoke. That sweet smelling resin there, it was like the Lord's people's prayers. [EXEG: Is it incense = prayers? or bowls = prayers? Ex. Summ. #2 grammatical agreement favours “bowls” here. But NIGTC points out 8:3-4 equates prayers = incense, and Ex.Summ #1 goes there for this verse. None of the sources discuss the possibility of the higher level “golden bowls full of incense” = prayers (but then they rarely get above the microscopic level); I think (CEG) the incense is burning by implication, and the smoke is symbolically the prayers -- evoking other passages of scripture, but without explicit textual support here.]</bt><note reference="5:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 141:2</note><v n="9" />Ka rèngu aa'i-aa'i sod'a lii sod'a hiu èci, peka na:<bt>Then they all sang a new song, saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ana Kalèbho ne'e ka dhu nia sèmi nare sasuri ne.<bt>“The Sheep Offspring here, is who is appropriate/worthy to receive this writing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ana Kalèbho ne'e ka dhu dènge hak ho bisa bhoke segel sèra.<bt>The Sheep Offspring here, is who has the right to open its seals.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te Nèngu ne'e ka dhu ra pamadhe le.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He has been killed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Hèia Ama Lamatua pake raa Na,<bt>Then God used His blood,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho sui nare dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne,<bt>to redeem people from every tribe on earth,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ho pamèu sasala-sasigo dhèu nèti suku"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ho pamèu sasala-sasigo dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka dhèu cahag'e bisa j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua.<bt>so that some of them can become God2's people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dènge sèmi èèna, dhèu rai-haha nèti lii aa'i-aa'i dènge rai aa'i-aa'i,<bt>Because of that, humans from every language and country,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bisa j'aj'i ana-ana Lamatua.<bt>can become the Lord's family.</bt><note reference="5:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 33:3, 98:1, Yesaya 42:10</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Ana Kalèbho ne'e ka, oru nare si aa'i-aa'i,<bt>The Sheep Offspring here, has gathered them all together,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">j'aj'i mi ca rae-ca nadha.<bt>to become a nation/kingdom (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca rae-ca nadha = satu kampung-satu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ca rae-ca nadha = satu kampung-satu tempat perayaan adat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ana Kalèbho ne'e ka, hag'e nare si,<bt>The Sheep Offspring here, has chosen them/set them apart,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">j'aj'i dhèu sab'a Lamatua.<bt>to become the Lord's workers.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Bèli-camèd'a rèngu se'e ka dhu rèd'u paredha ètu rai-haha.<bt>Later2 they will rule in the world.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe rèngu sab'a hia Lamatua ètu rai-haha.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later they will serve God on the earth.”</bt><note reference="5:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 19:6, 1 Petrus 2:5,9, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 1:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle ka, ja'a boti kètu, hèia tadèngi lii mèdhu aae èci. Hèia ja'a ladhe badha aae èpa ngi'u, dènge 24 (dua nguru èpa) katua se, tabha hari dènge ana pajuu nèti sorga ae titu kèna. Ana pajuu se d'ai juta-kehi.<bt>After that, I lifted by face and I heard a loud voice. And I saw those four extra-ordinary animals there, and those 24 elders there, added together with a great many of God's angels from heaven. Those angel's amount there, was up to millions and millions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="juta-kehi ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">juta-kehi =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="myriádes myriádoon, kaì khiliádes khiliádoon: ten"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">myriádes myriádoon, kaì khiliádes khiliádoon: ten thousands of ten thousands, and thousands of thousands -- super big number, too many to even try to count</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:10</note><v n="12" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra sod'a dènge lii mèdhu, peka na,<bt>They all sang with a loud voice, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ji'i ded'e padedha-dedha Ana Kalèbho dhu ra pamadhe le,<bt>“We lift up high that Sheep Offspring who was killed,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lula Nèngu ka dhu nia sèmi nare lii koa-kio ji'i!<bt>Because He is appropriate to receive our praises (doublet)!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Koasa Na, kapai risi eele.<bt>That power/authority of His, is exceedingly big/great.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Kakaja Na, lale-kabèle.<bt>That wealth of His, is abundant (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ngangee lii padhai Na, lèke mola-mola.<bt>That thinking of His, extremely hits the mark.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">A'èra Na, èci sa risi boe.<bt>That strength of his, is truly amazing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Na.<bt>We lift up high His name/reputation.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i pakab'ua Ne.<bt>We give honor to Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i koa-kio Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>We praise Him.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a tadèngi hari lii sod'a dhu leo èci. Lii sod'a ne, mai nèti aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri ètu: sorga, dedha-liru, rai-haha, dènge d'ara dhasi. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra sod'a. Nèti era dhèu madhe kahèi, ra madhutu sod'a. Aa'i-aa'i ra sod'a, peka na,<bt>After that, I heard yet another song. Everything that lives, in heaven, in the sky, on the earth, and in the sea, they all festively sang. From the dead people's place also, they followed along/participated in singing. They all sang (implied by grammatical construction: with great enthusiasm), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua dhu madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha.<bt>“We praise (doublet) God who sits on this ruling chair.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i nedhe padedha-dedha kahèi Ana Kalèbho ne.<bt>We also lift up high this Sheep Offspring here.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nedhe = angkat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">nedhe = angkat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i pakab'ua Rèngu.<bt>We give respect/honour to Them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i pahaha iisi mi Rèngu.<bt>We worship Them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Rèngu ka dhu rèd'u paredha taa-taa!<bt>Because They are the Ones who rule forever!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa koasa Ra dhu dènge boe too-lane!&gt;&gt;<bt>And Their power/authority is unbounded!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tà en autóis pánta: all the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">tà en autóis pánta: all the things in all these places</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Hèia èpa badha aae se, loe boe dènge lii dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a-re'a! Lèke kèna!&gt;&gt; Ka 24 (dua nguru èpa) katua se'e pabèbha hari iisi ra, hèia ra patitu kètu urutuu, ho ra pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua, dènge Ana Kalèbho èèna.<bt>Then those four extra-ordinary animals there, responded over and over, saying, “That's true! That's right!” And those 24 elders fell kneeling again to worship God and that Sheep Offspring.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana Kalèbho bhoke eele segel se èci-èci [\s2] Segel ka èci -- Kapala pamusu kalua mai<bt>The Sheep Offspring opens each of those seals [\bts2] Seal number one -- a war leader comes out</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Èle ka, ja'a ladhe kèdhi Ana Kalèbho bhoke segel ka èci nèti lalulu sasuri èèna. Hèia ja'a tadèngi, na, èci nèti èpa badha aae sèra parodha dènge lii mèdhu, nuka sèmi lii d'oro. Na paredha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamu dènge ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, I saw that Sheep Offspring open that rolled writing's first seal. Then I heard one of those four extra-ordinary animals there yell with a loud voice like thunder. He commanded saying, “Go now!” [EXEG: Trans Handbook: the ‘go’ is to the horseman. See note on Gk /érkhou/ not “come up to the sky” but “come on the scene”, “start to do your thing”, “get going”, “Go”, which in the Timor region is best expressed as “go!”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="érkhou: not &quot;come up to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">érkhou: not "come up to the sky" but "come on the scene", "start to do your thing", "get going", "Go".</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Cag'ag'a laa, ja'a kèdhi jara pudhi ci'u. Dhèu èci dhu manya'e pake dènge solo kapala musu, lula nèngu ka dhu segi taruu ètu d'ara pamusu. Limuri ne na kèpe le kataki-hahusu, la'e ho segi hari musu na ètu rai-haha.<bt>Suddenly/unexpectedly I saw a white horse. There was a person sitting on top wearing a war captain's hat, because He continually conquered in war. Now He was holding a bow (doublet), and going out to go defeat again his enemies on earth. [EXEG: none of the sources discuss “going out (from where)?” It is assumed to be a generic “going forth to battle”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kataki-hahusu = busur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kataki-hahusu = busur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nikoon: not &quot;fighta&quot;, because that's a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">nikoon: not "fighta", because that's a boxer. "Military person" conveys a better image.</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 1:8, 6:3, 6</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Segel ka dua -- patao-palaha ètu rai-haha [\s2]<bt>Seal number two -- chaos on earth [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Hèia Ana Kalèbho ne bhoke segel ka dua. Ka ja'a tadèngi badha aae ka dua paredha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamu dènge ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Afterwards, that Sheep Offspring opened seal number two. And I heard the number two extra-ordinary animal command, saying, “Go!”</bt><v n="4" />Ka jara ci'u dhu mea gèu-gèu kalua mai. Dhèu dhu manya'e jara ne sèmi nare samala aae èci. Ra hia ne koasa ho la'e pamaruru ètu rai-haha, sèna ka dhèu rai-haha èci pamadhe èci.<bt>And then a flaming red horse came out. The person who sat on top accepted a big fighting sword. They gave him power/authority to go make chaos/disruption/destruction on earth, so that humans would kill each other.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pajuku = adu-domba"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pajuku = adu-domba</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="exéelthen: doesn't imply that the horses"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">exéelthen: doesn't imply that the horses were inside some enclosure and then came outside, but more like they each sallied forth to do their thing pyrrós: flame red, fiery red<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="6:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 1:8, 6:2</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Segel ka tèlu -- tèu manganga-mad'èu [\s2]<bt>Seal number three -- an extreme famine (doublet) season/year [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka Ana Kalèbho bhoke segel ka tèlu. Hèia ja'a tadèngi lii paredha nèti badha aae ka tèlu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamu dènge ka!&gt;&gt; Kaca'a laa, ja'a kèdhi jara mèdhi ci'u. Dhèu dhu manya'e jara ne nèd'u dènge kabatai cue, sèna ka tai nganga'a dhu oe kura kèna.<bt>Next, that Sheep Offspring opened seal number three. And I heard the extra-ordinary animal number three command, saying, “Go!” Suddenly/unexpectedly I saw a black horse. The person who was sitting on/riding that horse, was holding a scale in his hand, to weigh food which had started to be lacking.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabatai = dacing ; tai ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kabatai = dacing ; tai = timbang</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 6:2, 6</note><v n="6" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi hari, nuka sèmi lii èci mai nèti talora aae badha èpa ngi'u se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Bèli-camèd'a, abhu manganga-mad'èu dhu kapai titu kèna ètu rai-haha. Gaji dhèu ca lod'o nia dhoka hèli laludhu tèlu moo di; te ngaa neo laludhu be'a, abhu dhoka ca moo di. Masi ka sèmi èèna, dhèu bisa boe pa'ele iie aj'u saitun dènge aj'u anggor ètu d'ara oka ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>And then I heard as if there was a voice that came from the middle of those four animals, saying, “Later there will be an intense hunger/famine (doublet) on earth. A person's one day wage, will only be enough to buy three measuring tins of rice; but as for good rice, only enough for just one measuring tin. But later when that famine arrives, people are not allowed to destroy the olive trees and the grape trees/bushes in the gardens.” [EXEG: how do oil &amp; wine become olive trees and vines? Ex.Summ. has fairly widespread agreement that it is metonymy for the source here.] @@ ADDED FTN</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khóinix: a quart of flour, about"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">khóinix: a quart of flour, about two pounds. This is is ten times the ordinary price deenaríou: a Roman coin that was the regular pay for working all day at field labor. Like a dollar a day in the cane field<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>meè adikeéseeis: don't wrong the oil and the wine, don't ruin the supply of oil or wine; don't adulterate the oil or the wine (less probable in the money context - it sounds more like famine conditions for supply and demand at outrageous prices)</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu rai nèi, dhèu sèra mamuri nèti aj'u dua se. De masi ka ra abhu manganga-mad'èu dhu kapai titu kèna, te ngaa sad'i aj'u dua se era ètu nèi, rèngu bisa mamuri taruu.<bt>In that region people live(d) from those two types of trees [=important part of life and culture, like lontar tree for Rote and Sabu people; similar phrasing used to talk about it]. So (consequently), even if the famine is severe, as long as they still have those two trees, people can still continue to live.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Segel ka èpa -- dhèu ae madhe [\s2]<bt>Seal number four -- many people die [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Èle èèna ka, Ana Kalèbho ne bhoke segel ka èpa. Hèia ja'a tadèngi lii nèti badha aae ka èpa hia paredha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamu dènge ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that Sheep Offspring opened seal number four. And I heard extra-ordinary animal number four command, saying, “Go!”</bt><v n="8" />Kaca'a laa, ja'a ladhe kèdhi jara ci'u dhu rèu na sanama karara. Dhèu dhu manya'e jara ne, ngara na &lt;Mamadhe&gt;. Aa abhu dhu madhutu ne re limuri, ngara na &lt;Era pea Samanga Dhèu Madhe&gt;. Rèngu dua ra abhu koasa ho lasi pamadhe dhèu ètu rai-haha pake samala, tèu manganga-madèu, papèd'a-tarègu, dènge pasoku badha hui dhu bhelu. Ladhe ige aa'i dhèu dhu madhe, aa'i-aa'i ra ca kaboko nèti èpa kaboko nèti dhèu dhu pea ètu rai-haha.<bt>Suddenly, I saw a pale yellow horse. The person sitting on top of that horse, his name was &lt;Death&gt;. There was also one who went behind him, his name &lt;Place of Dead People's Souls/Spirits&gt;. Then the two of them were given power/authority to go kill people on earth using swords, famine (doublet) seasons, sicknesses (doublet), and evil wild animals. If we count all those who died, the sum is the same as one part from four parts of all the people on earth. [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk here tends toward ‘light green’ ‘pale greenish gray’, so do your colour research, not just blindly going with an equivalent of /kuning pucat/. Colour systems in the Timor region vary widely.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sanama karara = kuning pucat ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">sanama karara = kuning pucat ; pasoku = foo, shooing, suru</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aa'i-aa'i ra ae nèngu bagi èpa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">aa'i-aa'i ra ae nèngu bagi èpa nèti dhèu dhu pea ètu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khloorós: ghastly greenish, like the mummy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">khloorós: ghastly greenish, like the mummy in the monster movie. Sickly pale, corpse color. Careful that "no mo color" doesn't get confused with "no mo kala!" R</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 14:21</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Segel ka lèmi -- dhèu unu Lamatua tatae toke Na pama'ète lii langu si [\s2]<bt>Seal number five -- God's people wait until He decides their cases [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia Ana Kalèbho ne bhoke segel ka lèmi. Ka ja'a kèdhi samanga dhèu dhu ra pamadhe uru sèra ètu ro'a mei korban. Ra pamadhe rèngu lula parcaya Ama Lamatua, aa aj'a-nori dhèu taruu lula-nèti Lii Holo-Nori Na.<bt>Then, that Sheep Offspring opened seal number five. And I saw the the spirits/souls of people who had previously been murdered, under the sacrificing table (=altar). They were murdered because they believed God, and people continually about His Words.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hypokátoo: underneath, or at the base"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">hypokátoo: underneath, or at the base in this case psychàs: souls or spirits of the departed. Not ghosts or obake spirits; this is positive -- the living personalities of many Christians who had been killed for their faith, and now are with God, but without the new body God plans to give them yet<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ra pa'oo-parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Oo Lamatua, Ama dhu kapai risi! Ama dhu mola-mèci! Ji'i parcaya ngaa dhu Lamatua peka-padhai. Te ngaa ji'i hud'i tatae d'ai pèri lod'o hari, heka Lamatua pama'ète lii langu, sèna ka huku dhèu dhu pamadhe ji'i ètu rai-haha nèi?&gt;&gt;<bt>They yelled out saying, “O Lord! Great Father! Holy Father! What ever the Lord (=you) say, we believe. But how long must we wait, before the Lord decides the litigation in order to punish those people who murdered us on earth?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ho despótees: slave owner, master, in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">ho despótees: slave owner, master, in this case very much like Almighty God héoos póte: not a request for a timetable, but a demand for action - "Please don't wait any longer!"<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ekdikéis: get even, settle accounts, right the wrong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa rèngu karèi rare sèmi èèna, hèia rèngu èci-èci ka abhu kodho pudhi robho d'ai rai. Abhu dhu peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Tatae hari ku ciki oo'e, toke miu tesa aa'i. Te abhu anga miu era dhu ra pamadhe sèmi miu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they finished asking like that, then they each one received a white robe/dress/shirt to the ground. There was someone who told them, “Wait a bit longer, until your total is complete. Cuz (elaboration) there are still your siblings who will later be murdered the same as you.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="leukeé: white clothes (Rev 3:4-5 &quot;dat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">leukeé: white clothes (Rev 3:4-5 "dat no ack pilau, jalike dey get clean clotheses. Dey da guys dat goin walk wit me an wear white kine clotheses, cuz dey get da right fo do dat. Everybody dat fight an win ova da bad kine stuff, dey goin wear white kine clotheses lidat.") to show purity and victory</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Segel ka èna -- mamadhe-mamopo ètu dedha-liru dènge rai-haha [\s2]<bt>Seal number six -- disaster in the sky and on earth [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka Ana Kalèbho ne bhoke segel ka èna. Kaca'a laa, ja'a ladhe kèdhi rai-haha ne opo kapai titu kèna. Hèia madha lod'o maroga kiu-kiu, nuka sèmi bèla mèdhi, aa hèru mea sama sèmi raa.<bt>Then, that Sheep Offspring opened seal number six. Suddenly, I saw a big earthquake. And the sun became dark like a black cloth and the moon became red like blood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sákkos tríkhinos: sacking cloth made from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">sákkos tríkhinos: sacking cloth made from black goat hair, worn to show extreme grief or dismay, similar to knocking out one's own teeth or cutting off one's own finger joints in parts of the Pacific. But the goats here are brown, and mourning is shown in some of the ethnic groups by white, and is not symbolized in others. Change the figure to something sinister.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="6:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 11:13, 16:18, Yesaya 13:10, Yoel 2:10, 31, 3:15, Mateos 24:29, Markus 13:24-25, Lukas 21:25</note><v n="13" />Hua hètu-hua hètu nèti dedha-liru bèbhe mai asa rai-haha, nuka sèmi hua aj'u hoa dhu kabhui, lula lèke ngèlu aae.<bt>The stars in the sky fell down to the earth, like ripe fruit that falls from a tree because of a great wind.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabhui = gugur ; hoa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kabhui = gugur ; hoa = jato sebelum ada isi ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="anémou megálou: this would be about"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">anémou megálou: this would be about a gale force wind, not quite a hurricane but plenty dangerous on land or sea. Not a local wind like a whistling wind or Lahainaluna wind or one of the others that have special names</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Hèia ja'a ladhe, na, liru mae bagi mi dua, ka lulu nuka sèmi dhèpi, toke ele. Aa ledhe-ledhe dènge pulu aa'i-aa'i ra gaged'o, toke ele nèti era ra.<bt>And I saw the sky split divide in two, to roll up like a mat until it disappeared. And the mountains and the islands all shook until they disappeared completely from their place.</bt><note reference="6:13-14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 34:4; Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 16:20</note><v n="15" />Ropa j'ara se j'aj'i, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha, mulai nèti dhèu aae-dhèu kapai, komedhaa sordad'u, dhèu kaja-su'i, toke d'ai ènu sèra, aa'i-aa'i ra madha'u titu kèna. Ka rai lasi lu'u ètu ro'a-ro'a loe, dènge sasanga-sasanga hadhu ètu ledhe.<bt>When that happened, then all the people on earth from the kings and leaders (doublet), military commanders, rich people (doublet), until even slaves, they all become afraid. Then they all ran to hide in holes in caves and in gaps in the rocks in the mountains.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasanga hadhu = fissure ; masèke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">sasanga hadhu = fissure ; masèke = terbelah ; lu'u = sembunyi</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 2:19, 21</note><v n="16" />Dhèu sèra pua ledhe-ledhe aa hadhu aae sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Saguru mere ka ji'i laa! Pahuni ji'i sèna ka Nèngu dhu madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha aae èèna, baku nèdhi ji'i. Aa Ana Kalèbho èèna huku ia ka ji'i.<bt>They commanded the mountains and the big rocks, saying, “Cover over us! Hide us so that He who sits on that big ruling chair there, can't see us anymore. And that Sheep Offspring can't judge/punish us anymore. [EXEG: they are so terrified of God's wrath that they would prefer to be crushed. See Ex. Summ.]</bt><note reference="6:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Hosea 10:8, Lukas 23:30</note><v n="17" />Ira ii! Ji'i laho mae-mae le, te lod'o d'ai mamadhe-mamopo kèna! Ama Lamatua dènge Ana Kalèbho èèna, neo dutu nanasa Rèngu mi dedha ji'i. Te ngaa èci sa bisa boe sili rare, hèia tatu madhe aa'i mèu-mèu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Waa! (remorse/regret) We-exc are in big trouble here, cuz (elaboration) the calamity day(s) has arrived! God and that Sheep Offspring are wanting to pour out their anger on us. And surely there is no one who can avoid/survive it anymore.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sadutu = sabhori = po'a ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">sadutu = sabhori = po'a ; sili = lehe = avoid ; sili (2) = lombok ; dutu = bhori</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yoel 2:11, Meliaki 3:2</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua tao cap mi 144.000 (cangasu èpa nguru èpa riho) dhèu<bt>God puts brand/stamp on 144.000 people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ja'a ladhe kèdhi ana pajuu Lamatua dhèu èpa puru mai nèti sorga, titu ètu èpa madha ngèlu ètu rai-haha ne, ho taha ngèlu. Ka ngèlu bisa boe tiu asa d'ara dhasi, rai-dedha, dènge aj'u-aj'u.<bt>After that, I saw four angels of the Lord from heaven standing on the earth's four sources of wind in.order.to constrain the wind. And so the wind could not blow on the sea, the land, and the trees.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meta touto: after that episode. This"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">meta touto: after that episode. This is a different vision</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 49:36, Daniel 7:2, Sakaria 6:5</note><v n="2" />Lamatua hia si koasa, ho ra pa'ele iie rai-dedha dènge d'ara dhasi. Ka ja'a kèdhi hari ana pajuu dhu leo ca dhèu nèti sorga, mai nèti dhimu. Na mai nèti dènge cap Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri taa-taa. Hèia na rodhe mi ana pajuu dhèu èpa sèra, peka na,<bt>God have given power to them to destroy the land and sea. Then I saw another angel from heaven, come from the east. He was bringing the brand/stamp/seal from God who lives continually. Then he called out telling those four angels, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sphragíida: not a seal on a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">sphragíida: not a seal on a document, as in the preceding chapter. This was a signet ring or chop, used to put an identifying mark on God's people. Nowadays they stamp your hand at Aloha Stadium or Waikiki Shell. A carved stone was usually used in those days to make an impression on a blob of wax, or in this case, to put ink on somebody's skin ékraxen phoonéei megáleei: he shouted with a loud voice<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>thálassan: any large body of water, salt or fresh</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />&lt;&lt;Mate ku! Baku pa'ele iie ku rai-dedha, do d'ara dhasi, do aj'u sèra. Mate toke ji'i tao ngare ku cap mi katangarèi dhèu unu Lamatua sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>“Wait! Don't destroy the land or sea or trees. Wait until we (exc) have put a stamp on God's peoples' foreheads.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katangarèi = testa ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">katangarèi = testa ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sphragísoomen: the angel who is talking"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">sphragísoomen: the angel who is talking and his associates, but not the four angels in charge of controlling the winds</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 9:4, 6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Èle èèna ka, rèngu peka dènge ja'a, na, ana pajuu ne tao le tadha mi dhèu unu Lamatua sèra. Dhèu sèra aa'i-aa'i ra 144.000 (cangasu èpa nguru èpa riho) dhèu, dhu mai nèti suku Isra'el. Nuka:<bt>Then they told me that angel had put a sign on God's people. Their amount/total were 144.000 people, who came from all the clans of Israel. They were:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="5" />nèti suku Yahuda, 12.000 (canguru dua riho) dhèu;<bt>from clan Yahuda, there were 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">suku Ruben, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Ruben, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">suku Gad, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Gad, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="6" />suku Aser, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Aser, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">suku Naftali, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Naftali, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">suku Manase, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Manase, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="7" />suku Simeon, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Simeon, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">suku Lewi, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Lewi, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">suku Isaskar, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Isaskar, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="8" />suku Sebulon, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Sebulon, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">suku Yusuf, 12.000 dhèu;<bt>clan Yusuf, 12.000 people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa nèti suku Benyamin, 12.000 dhèu.<bt>and from clan Benyamin, 12,000 people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu mola-mèci koa-kio Ama Lamatua dènge Ana Kalèbho<bt>The holy/clean people praise (doublet) God and the Sheep Offspring</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a kèdhi dhèu ae titu kèna, dhu ige kore boe. Rèngu mai nèti suku aa'i-aa'i, nèti udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i, nèti kabarai aa'i-aa'i, aa nèti lii aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha. Rèngu pakaboko tangara asa kadera paredha, aa asa Ana Kalèbho kahèi. Dhèu sèra pake kodho pudhi, aa ra kèpe dènge rèu palam.<bt>After that, I saw many people, to the point that they could not be counted. They came from every clan/tribe, every ethnic group/race, every country/nation, and every language/speech community on earth. They all gathered facing that ruling chair and that Sheep Offspring. They all wore white clothes and were holding palm leaves in their hands.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="éidon: another separate vision phoínikes: palm"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">éidon: another separate vision phoínikes: palm branches. A sign of celebration and happiness, like when Jesus went into Jerusalem. Sounds like a victory parade<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ka aa'i-aa'i ra koa-kio, aku rèngu na,<bt>Then they all enthusiastically praised, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua ji'i,<bt>“We praise (doublet) our God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu madhèdi ètu kadera paredha Na.<bt>who is sitting on this ruling chair here.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i ded'e padedha-dedha Ana Kalèbho ne kahèi!<bt>We also lift up high this Sheep Offspring here!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rèngu se'e ka dhu pala mamuri hia ji'i.<bt>They here, are who give salvation to us.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hee sooteería tóoi theóoi: victory? salvation?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">hee sooteería tóoi theóoi: victory? salvation? but why the dative case? "associated with"? Check B-D grammar. Nothing in Blass-Debrunner under Dative, unless it is "Salvation has to do with our God" as a loose associative, but there are no good parallels. Might it be a calque on "hosanna"?<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rèngu se'e ka dhu bhoke j'ara mamuri hia ji'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>They here, are who open the path of life for us.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hee sooteería tóoi theóoi: victory? salvation?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">hee sooteería tóoi theóoi: victory? salvation? but why the dative case? "associated with"? Check B-D grammar. Nothing in Blass-Debrunner under Dative, unless it is "Salvation has to do with our God" as a loose associative, but there are no good parallels. Might it be a calque on "hosanna"?<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa padhai lii rare sèmi èèna, ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga dhu rai-reo rare kadera paredha ne, patitu kètu urutuu ra, toke rèhu d'ai rai, tangare asa kadera paredha aae ne. Katua-katua dènge èpa badha aae sèra, tao madhutu sèmi èèna kahèi. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua,<bt>When they finished speaking like that, the angels of the Lord who stood around those ruling chairs, knelt with their faces to the ground in front of that big/main ruling chair. Those elders, and those four extra-ordinary animals, also did like that. They all worshipped God</bt><v n="12" />aa ra peka na,<bt>and they said,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Tare'a! Èèna tare'a-re'a!<bt>“Correct! That's correct!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua kahèi!<bt>We also praise (doublet) the Lord God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Lamatua kahèi!<bt>We also lift up high the Lord's name/reputation!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ngangee dènge lii padhai Lamatua, dhu lèke mola-mola.<bt>The thoughts and words of God's, hit the mark/ are extremely perceptive.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Koasa Lamatua dhu kapai risi eele.<bt>That power/authority of God's, is very big/great.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">A'èra Lamatua seli eele.<bt>That strength of God's, is exceeding amazing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i loe boe manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>We do not cease giving thankyou to God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i loe boe pakab'ua Lamatua.<bt>We give honour to God without ever ending.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lèke! Tare'a sèmi èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>That's right! That's how it is!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="datives: again, this appears to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">datives: again, this appears to be something people are giving to God, not a statement about his attributes. OR, they are recognizing his attributes, like "bless God" is recognizing and thanking him for the blessings he gives.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa rèngu koa-kio rare sèmi èèna, hèia nèti 24 (dua nguru èpa) katua se, èci karèi ja'a, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ae-ae dhu pake kodho pudhi se, èu tadha si, do? Rèngu se mai nèti mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>They finished praising like that, then from those 24 elders there was one who asked me saying, “These many people here who are wearing white clothes, you know them, [tag question, expecting yes answer]? Where are they from?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa ja'a dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, ama. Ja'a tadhe boe rèngu se, cee. Ama ka dhu tadhe risi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I replied saying, “No, father/Mr. I don't know/recognise who they are. Father is the one who knows better.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na peka dènge ja'a, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Rèngu se, dhèu dhu bhodho nèti d'ara j'aj'èra aae.<bt>Then he told me saying, “They there, are the people who have come out of/survived the big suffering.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rèngu se, dhèu dhu pake le raa Ana Kalèbho ne,<bt>They there, are the people who used that Sheep Offspring's blood,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka rase mèdha-papake ra,<bt>to wash their clothes,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa tao papudhi kodho ra.<bt>to make clean white their shirts/robes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="thlípseoos: they lived through a time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">thlípseoos: they lived through a time of extraordinary distress; they are the survivors. Probably not just any big trouble, but the Tribulation or, the whole church age.</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 12:1, Mateos 24:21, Markus 13:19</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />Nèti èèna ka, rèngu titu ètu madha kadera paredha Ama Lamatua.<bt>Because of that, they stand in front of God's ruling chair.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Mèu-mèda rèngu lalau-lalo'o Lamatua ètu d'ara Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i Na.<bt>They serve God day-night in His Worship House. [NLT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua dènge si taa-taa.<bt>God is continually with them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua madhenge si taa-taa.<bt>God continually protects them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="skeenoósei: spread his tent over them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">skeenoósei: spread his tent over them [and protect them], shelter them with his presence</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />Pe rèngu re'a heka manganga.<bt>In the future they will not feel hungry anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe rèngu koko-kamango heka.<bt>In the future they will not feel thirsty anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pe madha lod'o pakèpu heka si.<bt>In the future they will not be burnt by the sun anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakèpu = kasi angus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pakèpu = kasi angus</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pe ka'uri rèngu carici heka lèke lod'o pana.<bt>In the future their skin will not peel being adversely affected by heat anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="carici = takupas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">carici = takupas</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 49:10</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />Ana Kalèbho dhu padètu dènge kadera paredha èèna,<bt>That Sheep Offspring who is close to that ruling chair there,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe Nèngu ka j'aj'i dhèu bata-magee kètu rèngu.<bt>In the future He will become their shepherd (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu (bata)-magee kètu = orang (usir)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">dhèu (bata)-magee kètu = orang (usir) halangi kepala = gembala</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èèna na Nèngu ka eo nèti si,<bt>In the future He will herd lead them,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eo nèti = foo bawa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">eo nèti = foo bawa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lasi rinu asa madha èi dhu nèti mamuri hia dhèu.<bt>to go drink at the source of water that bring life/salvation to people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe Lamatua saku eele sasusa ra,<bt>In the future God will also wipe away their difficulties,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka ra tangi ia ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>so that they do not cry anymore.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poimanéi: used of the shepherd; but"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">poimanéi: used of the shepherd; but here the Lamb is the shepherd</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 23:1-2, Yeskial 34:23, Yesaya 49:10, Yesaya 25:8</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Segel ka pidhu -- ana pajuu Lamatua sèmi rare tèbhe pidhu bua<bt>Seal number seven -- angels receive seven trumpets</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Ana Kalèbho ne bhoke segel ka pidhu. Kabèdhi laa, aa'i-aa'i ètu sorga kalau-karèto boe. Abhu boe lii èci sa, pe d'ai catenga jam sa.<bt>Then, that Sheep Offspring opened seal number seven. Suddenly, everything in heaven was dead quiet (became completely motionless/quiet). There was nothing that voiced/made.a.noise for approximately half an hour.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalau-karèto boe = sonde bagarak sadiki"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kalau-karèto boe = sonde bagarak sadiki ju ; kalau = bergerak ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="seventh seal: the last seal. silence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">seventh seal: the last seal. silence for half hour: emphasizes the importance of what was happening.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ka ja'a ladhe kèdhi ana pajuu dhèu pidhu nèti sorga, titu taruu ètu madha Ama Lamatua, dhu pa'èra lalau Ne. Rèngu èci-èci ka sèmi rare tèbhe ra.<bt>Then I saw seven angels continually standing in front of God so that they are ready to serve Him. They each one receive a trumpet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="horn or trumpet: The Biblical trumpet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">horn or trumpet: The Biblical trumpet could be a ram's horn. Modern trumpets are brass wind instruments. There is no way to know which the writer meant. But "horn" nowadays is "car horn," so they'd better be trumpets.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka ana pajuu dhu leo ca dhèu, titu ètu madha mei era tunu raa aj'u hèu mèngi. Nèngu dhu nèd'u dènge mago hualaa cue, era isi raa aj'u hèu mèngi. Hèia ra hia ne raa aj'u hèu mèngi ae-ae, sèna ka na pab'ali dènge lii manèngi-mangaj'i nèti dhèu unu Ama Lamatua. Ka na nèti mago hualaa, ho tao sèmi korban dhu hèu mèngi, sèna ka la'e tèke asa dedha mei hualaa ètu madha kadera paredha aae.<bt>Then one of the other angels went to stand in front of that table which they use to burn resin. He was holding a golden bowl, which they usually used to put resin. They gave him lots of resin, to mix with God's people's prayers. Then he took that golden bowl as a sacrifice which smelled fragrant to place it on top of the gold table in front of that ruling chair.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="censer: small golden bowl or pan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">censer: small golden bowl or pan in which incense was burned. It had a handle so the priest could hold it and carry it to the altar (1 Kings 7:50). He was given much incense: God, an angel, or somebody gave him, or he received.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="8:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Amos 9:1, Kalua nèti Masir 30:1, 3</note><v n="4" />Ka na tunu raa aj'u hèu mèngi ne. Hèia hèu mèngi na ca'e asa madha Ama Lamatua, palere-lere dènge lii manèngi-mangaj'i nèti dhèu unu Lamatua.<bt>Next he burned that resin. And it's fragrant smell went up in front of God, together with all of the prayers from God's people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Èle èèna ka, ana pajuu ne nare ai nèti dedha mei ne, la'e tao asa d'ara mago hualaa èèna. Hèia na pèci mago ne asa rai-haha. Kaca'a laa, ja'a ladhe kèdhi bela kacèb'a lolo aae nèti g'ana-kariu ètu rai-haha. Ka lii tea ma'ète boe, aa rai opo kapai titu kèna.<bt>Then, that angel took fire from that table, put it in that gold bowl. Next he threw that bowl away on to the earth. Unexpectedly/immediately, I saw lightening striking out left-right on the earth. And loud crack of thunder followed, and there was a big earthquake.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii tea = bunyi guntur yg"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">lii tea = bunyi guntur yg dasat, crack</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 16:12, Yeskial 10:2, Kalua nèti Masir 19:16, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 11:19, 16:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Èle ka, ana pajuu dhèu pidhu nèti sorga sèra, pa'èra ho tiu tèbhe ra.<bt>Then, those seven angels got ready to blow their trumpets.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tiu tèbhe ka èci -- ana aaj'u kèpu-ladhu ai [\s2]<bt>Trumpet number one -- plants are burned [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa ana pajuu ka èci tiu tèbhe na, hèia èj'i es aa ai pab'ali dènge raa, sabhori mai asa rai-haha. J'u'u aa'i-aa'i ètu mia-mia kèpu-ladhu ai. Ca era nèti tèlu era ètu rai-haha ne, kèpu-ladhu ai. Aa ca kaboko nèti tèlu kaboko ana aaj'u ètu rai-haha ne, dhu kèpu-ladhu ai kahèi.<bt>When the first angel blew his trumpet, then ice rain and fire mixed with blood, fell pouring down on the earth. All the green grass was burned up everywhere. One place of three places on the earth burned up. One group of three groups of trees on this earth also burned up. [DISCOURSE: reordered for info flow: all grass, 1/3 of earth, 1/3 of trees/plants.] @@ Restructure with team. DELETE BT below.When the first angel blew his trumpet, then ice rain and fire mixed with blood, fell pouring/spewed down on the earth, until all the plants were burned (doublet). If we(inc) divide all the plants on earth into three parts, those that burned up, were one part. [NOTE to revise: @@ Because the term for ‘plants’ is the same as ‘tree’, and includes ‘grass’ within it, the ‘third of the trees burned’ and ‘all the green grass was burned’ got undertranslated (=missing) here. Because of the different semantic range, I see why the team diverged from the Kupang here. Sorry I didn't catch it on an earlier pass.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ladhu ai = hangus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ladhu ai = hangus</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Aj'u dènge ana aaj'u dhu kèpu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Aj'u dènge ana aaj'u dhu kèpu sèra, ladhe bagi mi tèlu nèti aj'u dènge ana aaj'u dhu muri ètu rai-haha ne. // Ropa ana pajuu ka èci tiu tèbhe na, hèia èj'i es aa ai pabali dènge raa, sabhori mai asa rai-haha, ka pakèpu-ladhu ai aj'u dènge ana aaj'u aa'i-aa'i ra. Ca kaboko nèti tèlu kaboko aj'u dènge ana aaj'u ètu rai-haha ne, dhu kèpu-ladhu ai.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hail: extremely rare in Hawaii; most"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">hail: extremely rare in Hawaii; most people have never seen it. Ice is common, sold by the bag triteen: "one third" is homophonous with an expression that would be unacceptable in church. It has to be "thirty-three percent" in order to not offend or amuse or be totally misunderstood. Percentages and round numbers are a fact of life in a society where people pay taxes and look for discounts.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="8:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 9:23-25, Yeskial 38:22</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tiu tèbhe ka dua -- ngaa-ngaa ètu d'ara dhasi madhe [\s2]<bt>Trumpet number two -- everything in the sea dies [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ropa ana pajuu ka dua tiu tèbhe na, ka mèdha èci sama sèmi ledhe aae cue dhu heo robhe-robhe, pèci la'e asa d'ara dhasi, toke ca era nèti tèlu era ètu d'ara dhasi j'aj'i raa.<bt>When angel number two blew his trumpet, then a thing like a big mountain that was burning, was thrown into the sea, until one of three parts in the sea became blood. [NOTE: versification in NRSV off from Gk here.]</bt><v n="9" />Hèia ca kaboko nèti tèlu kaboko badha ètu d'ara dhasi, madhe aa'i mèu-mèu. Ca kaboko nèti tèlu kaboko kapa aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara dhasi, laho eele aa'i si.<bt>Then one of three parts of all the animals in the sea, died off. And one of three parts of all the ships in the sea also were completely destroyed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="POSSIBLY -- bagi tèlu nèti kapa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">POSSIBLY -- bagi tèlu nèti kapa aa'i-aa'i ètu dara dhasi...</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tiu tèbhe ka tèlu -- èi j'aj'i pèd'u [\s2]<bt>Trumpet number three -- water becomes bitter [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10-11" />Ropa ana pajuu ka tèlu tiu tèbhe na, hèia nèti dedha-liru hua-hètu aae cue bèbhe mai, nuka sèmi ob'o kapai aae èci dhu heo. Hua-hètu ne, ngara na &lt;Pèd'u&gt;. Ropa na bèbhe mai, èi loko dènge madha èi, j'aj'i pèd'u. Hèia nèti dhèu dhu rinu, ae ka dhu madhe. Ladhe sèmi loko dènge èi madha ètu rai-haha ne hag'e mi tèlu, na, ca hag'e j'aj'i pèd'u.<bt>When angel number three blew his trumpet, then a big star fell from the sky, like a big torch that was burning. That star's name was "Bitter". When it fell then, rivers and springs became bitter. Then of the people who drank, there were many who died. If we divide all the rivers and springs in the world into three parts, well, those who became bitter, were one part.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èd'u = empedu ; pèd'u ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">èd'u = empedu ; pèd'u = pahit</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Wormwood: named after a bitter drug"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Wormwood: named after a bitter drug made from a plant with a certain smell. The drug is not poisonous, but it was considered poisonous. Harsh tasting.</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:10-11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 14:12, Yermia 9:15</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tiu tèbhe ka èpa -- madha lod'o, hèru dènge hua-hètu maroga [\s2]<bt>Trumpet number four -- sun, moon, and stars become dark [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia ana pajuu ka èpa tiu tèbhe na. Kaca'a laa, madha lod'o, hèru dènge hua-hètu lèke hake, hèia maroga. Ladhe re mèu, maroga èpa jam, lula madha lod'o heo iia heka. Aa ladhe re mèda, maroga kiu-kiu èpa jam kahèi, lula hèru dènge hua-hètu heo iia heka kahèi.<bt>Then, that angel number four blew his trumpet. Unexpectedly the sun and moon and stars were stricken, and they become dark. So, in the daytime, there was dark for 4 hours, because the sun was not shining correctly/fully anymore. And at nighttime, it became pitch dark for 4 hours, because the moon and the stars did not shine correctly/fully anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèia ca era nèti tèlu era"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hèia ca era nèti tèlu era j'aj'i maroga. De ladhe re mèu, na maroga èpa jam. Aa ladhe re mèda, maroga kiu-kiu èpa jam kahèi. // Ladhe re mèu, ca era nèti tèlu era j'aj'i maroga, lula madha lod'o heo be'a heka.</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 13:10, Yeskial 32:7, Yoel 2:10, 31, 3:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Èle ka, ja'a doa kètu, ka ladhe kèdhi manea luji ci'u dhu lela dedha titu kèna. Na parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Kasian! Kasian! Bèli-camèd'a j'aj'èra kapai lèke dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri ètu rai-haha. Te ana pajuu dhèu tèlu era, dhu tiu mèka tèbhe ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I lifted up my head, and I saw an eagle flying high in the sky. He yelled out, saying, “Mercy/Pity! Mercy/Pity!! A big catastrophe will happen to all the people who live on earth. Cuz (elaboration) there are still three angels who have not yet blown their trumpets.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tiu tèbhe ka lèmi -- kabara paj'èra dhèu rai-haha [\s2]<bt>Trumpet number five -- grasshoppers cause humans to suffer [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, ana pajuu ka lèmi tiu tèbhe na. Hèia ja'a kèdhi hua-hètu cue bèbhe asa rai-haha. Ra pangèd'u hua-hètu ne gagoe èci, ho na bhoke babèdho ro'a j'aj'èra dhu marèma na dènge boe too.<bt>After that, the angel number five blew his trumpet. And I saw a star fall to the earth. They gave a key to that star in.order.that s/he open the door to the hole of torment/suffering which has no foundation/bottom/limit/boundary. [EXEG: implicature: CEV note and Ex. Summ (unanimous) in anceint world, stars were thought to be personal beings of some kind. Consider FTN, if necessary, if the star being given the key doesn't make sense.]</bt><v n="2" />Lod'o na bhoke nare babèdho ro'a ne, kaca'a laa sèb'u dhu mèdhi guru-guru kalua mai, nuka sèmi sèb'u ai na'e j'ami. Sèb'u ne kalua mai dhu kahore-kahore, ca'e la'e asa dedha, ka dedha-liru dènge madha lod'o maroga.<bt>When s/he opened that hole's door, thick black smoke came out like the smoke of burning forest. That smoke came out went up in clumps (=billowing), until the sky and the sun were black/dark.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kahore = gumpal, kaboak ; kahore-d'ad'a-d'ad'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kahore = gumpal, kaboak ; kahore-d'ad'a-d'ad'a =</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 19:28</note><v n="3" />Hèia kabara ae titu kèna, lela nèti d'ara sèb'u ai ne, ka bèbhe asa rai-haha. Ama Lamatua dhu pangèd'u le koasa mi rèngu, sama sèmi karakarai.<bt>Next an incredible large number of grasshoppers flew out of that smoke, to come down/swoop down to the earth. God had given them power like scorpions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karakarai = kalajengkeng, (lit. kepiting tanah)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">karakarai = kalajengkeng, (lit. kepiting tanah)</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 10:12-15</note><v n="4" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua peka dènge si, ho baku pa'ele iie j'u'u, aj'u-aj'u, dènge ana aaj'u ètu rai-haha. Te ngaa ra hud'i paj'èra ku dhèu dhu dènge boe tadha Lamatua ètu katangarèi ra.<bt>But He ordered them to not destroy the earth's grass, and trees, and other plants. But they were to cause torment to all the people who did not have God's sign on their forehead.</bt><note reference="9:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 9:4</note><v n="5" />Lamatua soro tèke kabara se paj'èra dhèu sèra toke d'ai lèmi hèru, te ngaa bisa boe pamadhe si. Dhodhoka tao papèd'a di, sama sèmi karakarai tèpu.<bt>God allowed those grasshoppers to cause torment to those people for five months, but they could not kill them. Only cause them pain like a scorpion sting.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèpu = dedek, sting, sengat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">tèpu = dedek, sting, sengat</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ètu d'ara lèmi hèru èèna, rarii aa j'èra titu kèna, toke ra manèngi madhe. Masi ka sèmi èèna, ra madhe boe.<bt>During those five months, the suffering people would not be able to stand it anymore, to the point that they just request to die. Even that being the case, nevertheless they do not die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rarii = rasa sakit ; rii"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">rarii = rasa sakit ; rii = arus</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ayub 3:21, Yermia 8:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ja'a ladhe rupa kabara se sama sèmi jara pamusu. Rèngu pake solo kapala musu dhu tao nèti hualaa. Rèhu ra sama sèmi rèhu dhèu.<bt>I saw those grasshoppers' faces, like war horses. They were wearing war chief hats which were made out of gold. Their faces were like humans.</bt><note reference="9:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yoel 2:4</note><v n="8" />Rèu kètu ra madhera èci èèna ka dènge rèu kètu dhèu bhèni. Ngutu ra mariu sèmi ngutu singa.<bt>Their hair was long like a woman's hair. And their teeth were sharp like lion's teeth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mariu = tajam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mariu = tajam</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yoel 1:6</note><v n="9" />Rèngu se oe sèmi pake kodho bèsi ètu sangasa ra. Lii kahaku èla ra mèdhu sama sèmi jara sordad'u ae titu kèna dhu ère kareta pamusu ra.<bt>It was as if they were wearing iron shirts on their chests. Their wings sounded loudly, like an army batalion's horses running pulling war carts. [NOTE to daughter translation: compare phrasing for “breastplate” in 1 Thess. 5:8 &amp; Eph. 6:14]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sangasa = dada = kakara ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">sangasa = dada = kakara ; lii kahaku = sound of wings</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Miriam prefers &quot;chariots&quot;. In Exodus we"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Miriam prefers "chariots". In Exodus we have used "wagons fo war" and "war wagons", so we need to see how generally "chariots" is understood.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yoel 2:5</note><v n="10" />Rèu lai ra èra titu kèna, aa dhu dènge raco nuka sèmi raco karakarai. Rèngu se abhu koasa, ho paj'èra dhèu pake raco ra, toke d'ai lèmi hèru.<bt>Their tails were truly amazing with poison like scorpion poison. They were given power to torment people with that poison of theirs, for five months.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèu lai = ekor (bulu layar)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">rèu lai = ekor (bulu layar)</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Dhèu aae kabara se, nuka kètu nèti rèngu aa'i-aa'i dhu ra babège si nèti d'ara ro'a j'aj'èra dhu dènge boe too-lane. Ngara na ètu d'ara lii Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Abadon,</span> aa madhutu lii Yunani, <span class="Italic">Apolion.</span> Sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Dhu d'èi pa'ele iie&gt;&gt;.<bt>Those grasshopper's king, was the leader of all the underlings who had come out of that suffering hole which did not have a foundation. His name in Hebrew language, <span class="Italic">Abadon,</span> and in Yunani (Greek) language, <span class="Italic">Apolion.</span> It's meaning says, “The Habitual Destroyer.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, seli le j'aj'èra ka èci. Te ngaa baku pamud'e! Te dua j'aj'èra dhu leo era, dhu bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i hari.<bt>In that way, that first catastrophe, had passed. But don't get lazy! Cuz (elaboration) there are still two more catastrophes to come later.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tiu tèbhe ka èna -- tèlu rupa j'aj'èra ètu rai-haha [\s2]<bt>Trumpet number six -- three kinds of suffering on earth [\s2]</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\HK00260C.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Èpa tadhu ètu kabicu mei hualaa<bt>Four horns at the corners of the gold table</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka ana pajuu ka èna tiu tèbhe na. Hèia ja'a kèdhi mei hualaa, era dhu pake tunu raa aj'u hèu mèngi, dhu patangara dènge Lamatua. Ka lii èci kalua nèti èpa tadhu ètu kabicu mei èèna,<bt>Then, the number six angel blew his trumpet. And I saw that gold table which they used to burn resin, which was facing God. There was a voice coming out of that table's four corners, [CEV] @@ PIX caption</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabicu = sudut, pojok"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kabicu = sudut, pojok</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 30:1-3</note><v n="14" />ho peka dènge ana pajuu dhu heka tiu nare tèbhe na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ana pajuu dhèu èpa, dhu nèbhu nare sange ne'e lèke èki ètu d'ara loko aae èci, dhu ngara na Efrat. Lamu patabuli eele si!&gt;&gt;<bt>telling the angel who had just blown that trumpet, saying, “There are four underlings who have been tied up for a long time at a big river, named Efrat river. Go free them!”</bt><v n="15" />Hèia la'e patabuli si, sèna ka ana pajuu èpa se lasi pamadhe dhèu, dhu lèke dènge tèu na, hèru na, lod'o na, dènge jam na, dhu Lamatua pama'ète nare le. Ladhe èdhi bagi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne mi tèlu kaboko, na, dhu madhe, ca kaboko.<bt>Then he went to free them, in order for the four of them to go kill people exactly at the year, on the month, on the day, and on the hour which God had decided ahead of time. If we divide all the humans on earth into three parts, well, those who died, were one part.</bt><v n="16" />Rèngu peka dènge ja'a, na, sordad'u ana pajuu dhu ca'e jara pamusu sèra aa'i-aa'i ra, dua ngasu juta dhèu.<bt>They told me saying those underling's soldiers which rode war horses, were two hundred million people.</bt><v n="17" />Hèia ja'a ladhe kèdhi sordad'u dènge jara ra. Sordad'u se dhu pake kodho bèsi pa'abhe sangasa ra. Kodho se nuka, dhu mea gèu-gèu, mangèru kale'e, dènge karara oe sèmi èi nasu. Rupa kètu jara se, sama sèmi kètu singa. Nèti hèb'a jara se, kalua ai, sèb'u, aa èi nasu,<bt>Then I saw those soldiers and their horses. Those soldiers wore iron shirt chest protectors, Those shirts were shiny red, flashing blue, and sulfur yellow. Those horses' heads were like lions' heads. There was also smoke and sulfur that sprayed/spit out of those horses mouths,</bt><v n="18" />ho hia j'aj'èra tèlu rupa asa rai-haha, toke dhèu ètu rai-haha ne madhe aa'i ca kaboko nèti tèlu kaboko.<bt>in.order.to give three kinds of suffering on earth, to the point that one of three parts of all the humans who are on the earth died.</bt><v n="19" />Èle èèna, hèia jara se lasi paj'èra dhèu pake hèb'a dènge rèu lai ra. Ètu rèu lai ra, abhu kètu sèmi kètu mege.<bt>Then, those horses went to cause suffering to humans using their mouths and their tails. On those tails of theirs, there was a head like a snake head.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa abhu dhèu cahag'e ètu rai-haha, dhu ra pamadhe boe nèti j'aj'èra se'e. Masi ka sèmi èèna, rèngu neo boe tèke eele bhabhelu-katub'a ra. Rèngu sogo-tagu taruu nidhu aa mèdha-panyau dhu ra tao nèti hualaa, doi pudhi, tabaga, hadhu, dènge aj'u. Masi ka mèdha se bisa boe rèdhi ngaa-ngaa, bisa boe tadèngi ngaa-ngaa, aa bisa boe kako, te ngaa ra loe boe sogo-tagu si.<bt>But there were still other people on earth, who were not killed from those sufferings. Even that being the case, nevertheless they did not want to abandon their evil. They continued (traditional) worshipping evil spirits and worship things which they made from gold, silver, copper/bronze, stone and wood. Even though those things could not see anything, could not hear anything, and could not walk, nevertheless they just kept on worshipping them.</bt><note reference="9:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 115:4-7, 135:15-17, Daniel 5:23</note><v n="21" />Dhèu se'e ro'o boe loe kahèi nèti sasala dhu leo, nuka sèmi pamadhe dhèu, pake na'i nidhu, tao j'ara karehe dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali ra, aa mana'u pagogo-pagero.<bt>They also did not want to stop from their others sins, such as killing people, using black magic, (sexual) transgression with someone who is not their spouse, and stealing (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mana'u pagogo-pagero = mancuri (all types)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mana'u pagogo-pagero = mancuri (all types) ; pagogo = raba sembarang ; pagero = bongkar sembarang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana pajuu nèti sorga dhu nèd'u dènge lalulu sasuri iiki<bt>The angel holding the small *scroll (rolled up writing)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ja'a ladhe kèdhi ana pajuu Lamatua dhu kapai èci puru mai nèti sorga. Ra'i-liru sarimu nare ngi'u na. Kètu na dhu poi dènge saroo. Rèhu na heo sama sèmi madha lod'o, aa haga na heo èci èèna ka dènge heo ai.<bt>Then I saw a great/amazing angel of the Lord coming down from heaven. His body was wrapped/enveloped with cloud. There was also a rainbow surrounding his head (like a head-cloth). His face shone like the sun, and his leg/feet blazed like fire.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poi = wear head-dress, destar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">poi = wear head-dress, destar</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Nèngu ne kèpe dènge lalulu sasuri iiki, dhu bhoke tèke. Na titu, haga g'ana na ètu d'ara dhasi, haga kariu na ètu dedha-rai.<bt>He was holding a small scroll which was opened. He stood right foot in the sea, left foot on the land.</bt><v n="3" />Hèia na pa'oo-parodha, sèmi lii taraa singa. Ropa na pa'oo-parodha nare, hèia d'oro lii pagod'o-god'o pidhu hari.<bt>Then he yelled out (doublet), like a lion roaring. He finished yelling, then thunder kept sounding rumbling seven times.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Seven: indicates completion in the Bible."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Seven: indicates completion in the Bible. Thunder: sometimes indicates God's judgment, or people think God is speaking.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ropa d'oro lii, ka ja'a neo suri lii padhai ra. Te ngaa ja'a tadèngi lii èci nèti sorga, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu baku lolo dènge dhèu lii padhai lula-nèti pidhu d'oro se'e! Mage mu suri ngaa-ngaa kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>When the thunders had sounded/spoken, then I was wanting to write what they said. But I heard a voice from heaven saying, “You don't tell anyone the talking of those seven thunders. Don't write anything.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka ana pajuu dhu titu haga calaa ètu dedha-rai, aa haga calaa ètu d'ara dhasi èèna, j'oka ai g'ana na asa dedha-liru,<bt>Then, that angel there who stood with one foot in the sea, one foot on the land, lifted up his right hand to the sky,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The gesture of one who makes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">The gesture of one who makes a promise to God</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />hèia na subha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lii dhu ja'a peka ne, lèke tare'a! Ja'a subha dènge kolongara Ama Lamatua, lula Nèngu ka dhu taa-taa! Nèngu ka dhu paj'aj'i liru dènge rai-haha, aa isi ra aa'i-aa'i. Nanene paie-iie! Lod'o dhu èdhi tatae èèna, mamai na oe dètu le.<bt>to swear (oath), saying, “This speaking of mine, is true! I swear with God's name/reputation, because it is He, who continues on forever! It is he who has made the sky and land, and all their contents. So, listen well! That day which we all have waited for, it is nearly here. [EXEG: lgs in this region don't tend to have a lexical item that matches “delay”; Sense of “wait no longer” from NLT, CEV; immediately, without delay, see Ex. Summ.]</bt><v n="7" />Te ladhe ana pajuu Lamatua ka pidhu èèna neo tiu tèbhe na, pe Lamatua tao madhutu ngaa dhu uru èèna dhèu dhae re'a mèka. Te ngaa, ngaa dhu Na neo tao ne, Na peka le dènge dhèu rèti lii padhai Na dhu lalau-lalo'o Ne. De nanene paie-iie, te lii padhai Ja'a ne lèke tare'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if/when God's number seven angel is about to blow his trumpet, then God will carry out his plan which long ago people did not know. But that plan, He has told using His spokespersons who serve Him. So (consequently), listen well, cuz (elaboration) this speaking of mine here, is certainly true.” [EXEG: TAM “is to blow” NRSV, “is about to sound trumpet” AGNT] [DISCOURSE: last sentence closing off oath.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tiu ka CHANGED to neo tiu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">tiu ka CHANGED to neo tiu</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2012-01-25 01:50:30Z" /></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: &quot;Serious promise&quot; or &quot;strong promise&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">TERM: "Serious promise" or "strong promise" elsewhere too - check for 'oath'.</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:5-7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:11, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 32:40, Daniel 12:7, Amos 3:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ka lii dhu ja'a tadèngi nèti dedha-liru èèna, peka hari dènge ja'a, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis, lamu ka asa ana pajuu nèti sorga nèi, dhu titu haga na calaa ètu rai-dedha, aa calaa ètu d'ara dhasi. More nèti kacui-aai na, lalulu sasuri iiki dhu bhoke tèke èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, that voice which I heard earlier from the sky, it spoke again with me, saying, “Yohanis, you go to that angel from heaven there, who is standing with one foot in the sea, one foot on the land. Take from his hand that small scroll which is open.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia ja'a laku dènge ka asa ana pajuu ne, manèngi kore sasuri iiki èèna. Ka na lii dènge ja'a, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;More ho mu'a ka! Èèna na d'ara hèb'a èu, rasa kee nuka sèmi dhua nasu oni, te ngaa ètu d'ara kabake èu, rasa pèd'u.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I went to that angel, to request that aforementioned small writing. Then he told me, saying, “Take it to eat it (imp)! In your mouth it will taste sweet like honey, but later it will make your stomach feel bitter.” [EXEG: reverse order for chronology: mouth, then stomach. Compare vs. 10.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa na padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, ka ja'a sèmi kore sasuri iiki èèna nèti kacui-aai na. Hèia ja'a ku'e dènge ka. Ètu d'ara hèb'a ja'a ne kee sèmi dhua nasu oni. Te ngaa ropa ja'a dhèle, ja'a rasa na ètu d'ara kabake ja'a pèd'u.<bt>When he finished speaking like that, then I accepted that small writing from his hand. Next I ate it. In my mouth it tasted sweet like honey. But when I swallowed it, I felt bitter in my stomach.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèle = telan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">dhèle = telan</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:8-10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 2:8--3:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka abhu dhu pua ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu hud'i lamu hari ku, ho peka dènge ka ngaa dhu bèli-camèd'a Lamatua neo tao ètu rai-haha. Peka j'ara-j'ara dhu bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i mi dhèu aae aa'i-aa'i, mi dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i, nèti udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i, aa dènge nèti lii aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then there was (one) who ordered me saying, “You must go again to tell ahead of time that which God wants to/is about to do on earth. Tell about what will latter happen with all the kings, and the people from every nation, every clan, and every language on earth.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhèu dua dhu kapai risi<bt>Two great/amazing people bring the word/message of God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ra j'ole hia ja'a aj'u a'uku calaa dhu madhera nuka sèmi tatea. Ka Ama Lamatua paredha ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis, lamu ho uku Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ja'a dènge mei sogo-tagu na ètu kota Yerusalem. Aa ige dhèu-dhèu dhu sabaj'a ètu d'ara Èmu èèna.<bt>They they handed me a measuring stick that was long like a staff. And God commanded me saying, “Yohanis, go measure My Main Worship House with it's sacrifice table in Yerusalem city. And count all the people who are worshiping/praying there. [EXEG: ‘My’ from TH]</bt><note reference="11:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 40:3, Sakaria 2:1-2</note><v n="2" />Te ngaa madha Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i èèna, mage mu uku, te era èèna dhu hag'e eele le hia suku-suku leo dhu tadhe boe Ja'a. Èèna na rèngu mai j'aj'èli leli ho pakaj'alu kota Ja'a ne, d'ai tèlu tèu dènge cabèka (nuka, 1.260 [ca riho dua ngasu èna nguru] lod'o).<bt>But it's not necessary to measure the Worship House's yard, cuz (elaboration) that place already has been set aside for the other nations who do not know Me. Later they will come step all over making dirty/defile that city of Mine, for three and a half years (that is 1260 days). [EXEG: Yakan BT for ‘my city’]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èpa nguru dua hèru,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">èpa nguru dua hèru,</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 21:24</note><v n="3" />Pe Ja'a pua dhèu Ja'a dhèu dua lasi asa era èèna, sèna ka rèti lii padhai Ja'a. Dhèu dua se pake mèdha sasusa, aa ra lole lii moa nèti Ja'a, toke èle 1.260 (ca riho dua ngasu èna nguru) lod'o èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later I will commission two of My people there so that they become My spokesperson. The two of them will wear mourning clothes and tell messages/instructions from Me until those 1260 days are finished.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèdha balu = pakaian duka (implies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mèdha balu = pakaian duka (implies female);</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Sakaria, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua, dhu suri mema le nèti uru ka, lula-nèti dhèu dua se. Na pakasame sèmi aj'u saitun dua kapua, aa era tatèke labhu dua, dhu patitu tangare asa Ama Lamatua, dhu j'aj'i Kètu mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha.<bt>God's spokesperson Sakaria wrote ahead of time from before, about these two aforementioned spokespersons. He likened them to two olive trees and two lamps that stand facing God, that is, the Head of all people in the world.</bt><note reference="11:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 4:3, 11-14</note><v n="5" />Ladhe dhèu neo paj'èra dhèu dua dhu rèti lii padhai Lamatua, èèna na ai bhodho nèti d'ara hèb'a ra, ho pakèpu aa'i musu ra. Dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e, dhèu dhu neo paj'èra si, tatu madhe.<bt>If there is/are a person/people who wants to cause torment to these two spokespersons of God, later fire will come out of their mouths to burn up all their enemies. In that way, all people who want to cause them difficulty, will surely die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhodho = kaluar = cèu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bhodho = kaluar = cèu</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Lod'o dua ra j'aj'i dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua ètu rai-haha ne, Lamatua pangèd'u ra koasa ho ra bisa taha èj'i, koasa sèna ka tao madha èi j'aj'i raa, aa koasa ho ad'u-ue rupa-rupa mamadhe-mamopo ètu rai-haha, madhutu dad'èi ra.<bt>When the two of them become God's spokespersons on earth, the Lord will give power/authority to them to restrain the rain (make it not rain). He will also give power to make water springs become blood, and power to bring all kinds of catastrophies (doublet) on this earth, according to whatever they want.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasoe = rugi, tidak berhasil, paling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">sasoe = rugi, tidak berhasil, paling sial,</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 17:1, Kalua nèti Masir 7:17-19, 1 Samuel 4:8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Lod'o d'ai èle sasab'a-la'a ra, èèna na badha bhelu ci'u bhodho mai nèti ro'a j'aj'èra dhu dènge boe too-lane. Badha ne'e lab'a rèngu dua ra, toke na segi si, aa na pamadhe dua ra.<bt>When their time of work (doublet) is over, later a vicious animal will come out of that torment hole that does not have a foundation/limit. He will war against the two of them, until he defeats them and kills them.</bt><note reference="11:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:7, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 13:5-7, 17:8, Daniel 7:21</note><v n="8-9" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, dua ra madhe ètu kota kapai, dhu uru èèna era dhèu paku pamadhe Lamatua rèngu ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Te kota ne'e j'aj'i le kota bhelu, sèmi kota Sodom dènge rai Masir uru èèna. Èèna na, dhèu core eele ngi'u aae dua ra, toke d'ai tèlu lod'o dènge ca èta. Ka dhèu-dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i, nèti udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i, aa dènge nèti kabarai aa'i-aa'i ra, mai lingu. Dhèu se ro'o boe hia ijin ho padhane si,<bt>In that way, they two will die in that big city in which previously people killed their Lord on a cross. Cuz (elaboration) that city has become an evil city like the city of Sodom and land of Masir (=Egypt) in previous times. Later people will throw away those spokesperson's corpses in the street, for three and half days. Then people from every tribe, every clan, every language, and every country/nation will come gather around to view/watch. They also will not give permission to bury them,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lingu = keliling, (nonton)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">lingu = keliling, (nonton)</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 1:9-10</note><v n="10" />lula ra karej'e laladhe ngi'u aae dhèu dua se, dhu mai lalai ngangee dhèu ae ètu rai-haha ne. Ka dhèu se aa'i-aa'i ra tao pesta, aa ra pa'adhu hadia èci dènge èci.<bt>because they are happy seeing those two people have died, who came disturbing the thoughts of all people on earth. So they will enthusiastically make a feast, and send presents to each other. [NOTE to daughter translations: what the prophets say upsets everybody's consciences, so avoid the impression of wreaking physical havoc.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Te ngaa ropa èle tèlu lod'o dènge ca èta, hèia Ama Lamatua hia si a'ae, ka dua ra mamuri hari. Hèia dhèu-dhèu dhu ladhe rèdhi si, madha'u toke isi ra rèbha-rèbha.<bt>But after three and half days then God will give breath to them, so that they live again. Then all people who see them, will be so afraid they tremble.</bt><note reference="11:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 37:10</note><v n="12" />Ka dhèu dua se tadèngi lii dhu mèdhu èci nèti dedha-liru pua ra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dua mi ca'e ka asa ne'e mai!&gt;&gt; Hèia dua ra ca'e asa dedha-liru lasi dènge ra'i-liru dhu sarimu nare si. Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, ka musu ra malaa ko'a-ko'a sène.<bt>Then, those two people will hear a loud voice from heaven, ordering them, saying, “Hey! You two come up here!” Then they two will be taken up to the sky with a cloud covering wrapping them. When they see that, then their enemies will be stunned (open mouth speechless).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malaa ko'a-ko'a sène"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">malaa ko'a-ko'a sène</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Dhèu Aae sèra 2:11</note><v n="13" />Kaca'a laa, rai opo dhu kapai titu kèna. Ladhe ige èmu aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara kota, nèti canguru èmu, dhu guri, cue. Aa dhèu dhu madhe, pidhu riho dhèu. Dhu madhe boe, ra madha'u bia. Te ngaa rèngu èèna na pakab'ua kahèi kolongara Ama Lamatua, lula Nèngu ka dhu nèd'u paredha ètu sorga.<bt>Suddenly there will be a big earthquake. If we count all the houses in the city, from ten houses, there will be one that falls. And there will be seven thousand people who die. The other people who don't die, will become exceedingly afraid, But they will also give honour to God, because He is the one who holds rule/governs in heaven.</bt><note reference="11:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 6:12, 16:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Dènge sèmi ne'e, j'aj'èra ka dua seli le. Te ngaa baku pamud'e! Te calaka ka tèlu oe mai kèna.<bt>In that way, suffering/disaster number two will pass. But don't let up (your guard)! Cuz (elaboration) catastrophe number there is about to come.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tiu tèbhe ka pidhu -- Ama Lamatua dènge Yesus Kristus rèd'u paredha ètu rai-haha [\s2]<bt>Blowing trumpet number seven -- God and Yesus Kristus rule on earth [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia ana pajuu Lamatua ka pidhu tiu tèbhe na. Kaca'a laa, ja'a tadèngi lii ae-ae nèti sorga, dhu peka na,<bt>After that, angel number seven blew his trumpet. Unexpectedly/suddenly, I heard many voices from heaven, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Limuri ne, dhu rèd'u paredha ètu rai-haha,<bt>“Now the ones who rule on earth,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhodhoka Ama Lamatua dènge Kristus,<bt>are only God and Kristus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">nuka Dhèu dhu Lamatua hag'e nare karèi nèti uru ka mai.<bt>that Person whom He has chosen/set aside from long ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èèna na Lamatua nèd'u paredha taa-taa, sama sèmi Dhèu Aae.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later God will rule like a King forever.”</bt><note reference="11:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 15:18, Daniel 2:44, 7:14, 27</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka 24 (dua nguru èpa) katua dhu madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha ètu madha Ama Lamatua, tadèngi lii èèna kahèi. Hèia ra patitu kètu urutuu, toke rèhu ra d'ai rai, ka ra koa-kio Ama Lamatua,<bt>Those 24 elders who were sitting on those aforementioned ruling chairs in front of God, they also heard those voices. Then they fell kneeling with face to the ground, to praise (doublet) God,</bt><v n="17" />aa sod'a, peka na,<bt>and sing, saying, [NRSV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Oo Ama Lamatua!<bt>“O Lord God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Kètu ji'i!<bt>Our Lord/Master!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama Lamatua ji'i!<bt>Our Father God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua ka dhu paredha aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Lord (=you) is the one who rules everything</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua ka dhu koasa nare aa'i.<bt>Lord (=you) is the one who has power/authority over everything</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu karèi nèti uru ka mai.<bt>Lord (=you) is the one who is from long ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu deo ne'e ne.<bt>Lord (=you) is the one who is now.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i manèngi makasi mi Lamatua,<bt>We give thanks to the Lord (=you),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Ama pake le koasa Mu dhu kapai risi,<bt>because the Father (=you) has used the Your power which is big/great,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka mèd'u paredha ètu rai-haha.<bt>to rule on earth.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa dhèu nèti suku-suku nasa titu kèna,<bt>But the other nations are furious,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula rèngu ro'o boe madhutu Lamatua.<bt>because they don't want to follow/obey the Lord.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa limuri ne, Lamatua nasa kahèi,<bt>And now the Lord is also angry,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula rèngu ro'o boe tadhe Ne.<bt>because they don't want to know Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Limuri ne, d'ai le lod'o na,<bt>Now the time has come for</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka Lamatua huku dhèu dhu pusi-pahae boe Ne.<bt>the Lord to punish people who don't want to know anything about Him. (=have anything to do with)</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Limuri ne, d'ai le lod'o na,<bt>Now the time has come for</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho Lamatua palaho dhèu dhu palaho dhèu leo.<bt>the Lord to destroy people who destroy other people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Limuri ne, d'ai le lod'o na,<bt>Now the time has come for</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho Lamatua parisa lii langu dhèu madhe.<bt>the Lord to examine the dead people's affairs/cases.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Limuri ne, d'ai le lod'o na,<bt>Now the time has come for</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho Lamatua b'ae-baj'a èi kabhèsu dhèu sab'a Na.<bt>the Lord to reciprocate the Lord's servant's sweat (=effort):</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nuka: dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua,<bt>That is the Lord's spokespersons,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge dhèu unu Lamatua,<bt>and the Lord's people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Ana iiki-dhèu kapai, dhèu ngèru-dhèu heka.<bt>Small big, old young.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua b'ae rui-j'aj'èra mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra,<bt>The Lord compensates/rewards the efforts all people</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu pakab'ua kolongara Na.&gt;&gt;<bt>who give honour to His name/reputation.”</bt><note reference="11:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:5, 110:5, 115:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a ladhe kèdhi babèdho Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i Lamatua ètu sorga, dhu conge tèke. Ka ja'a kèdhi boaraka dhu uru èèna era tèke lii paredha Ama Lamatua dhu suri ètu lei hadhu. Hèia bela kacèb'a lolo aae nèti haa, nèti dhimu, d'oro lii pagod'o-god'o, rai-haha ne karedha, dènge èj'i es hadhu dhu bia, kabhui mai nèti dedha-liru.<bt>After that, I saw in heaven the Lord's Worship House's door was open. Next I saw that box which previously they used to store God's commands that were written on the writing stone. Then lightning struck from west from east, loud sounding thunder followed, the earth shook, and rock ice rain that was heavy fell down from the sky.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karedha = tagoyang-goyang ; kabhui ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">karedha = tagoyang-goyang ; kabhui = jato datang ; lei = batu tulis ; conge = buka</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 8:5, 16:18, 16:21</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mege naga pamusu dènge dhèu bhèni aa dènge ana na<bt>The dragon snake wars against the woman with her child</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />Ka cag'ag'a laa, ja'a kèdhi tadha èci dhu kapai titu kèna cèu ètu dedha-liru, dhu dhèu dhae rèdhi mèka ca tèka sa. Tadha ne, nuka sèmi: bhèni ca dhèu dhu ngi'u na pahutu dènge madha lod'o. Hèru j'aj'i mi era pacapa haga na. Nèngu pake solo dhèu aae, dhu dènge hua-hètu canguru dua bua.<bt>After that, unexpectedly/suddenly I saw an extra-ordinary sign which appeared in the sky, which humans have not yet ever seen. The sign was like this: there was a woman whose body was wrapped with the sun. She rested her feet on top of the moon. She wore a king's hat that had 12 stars.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pacapa = muat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pacapa = muat</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Bhèni ne dènge babia, ka dhu tangi, te abhu le tadha ho nara iisi.<bt>She was pregnant, and was crying, cuz (elaboration) she was having birth pains.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Kaca'a laa, ja'a kèdhi hari tadha èci dhu kapai aae, dhu cèu ètu dedha-liru kahèi. Tadha ne, nuka mege naga mea ci'u dhu kapai. Kètu na pidhu, aa tadhu na canguru bua. Ètu kètu na sèra, dhu pake solo dhèu aae.<bt>Unexpectedly, I saw again another extra-ordinary sign which appeared in the sky. There was a red dragon snake that was big. It's heads were seven, and it's horns were ten. It wore seven king hats on its heads.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="diadeemata: fillet, blue band trimmed with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">diadeemata: fillet, blue band trimmed with white, from Persia</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:7</note><v n="4" />Na pake rèu lai na, ho saku eele hua-hètu ca kaboko nèti tèlu kaboko ètu dedha-liru. Hèia na core hua-hètu se asa rai-haha. Ka la'e titu ètu madha bhèni ne, na tatae toke bhèni ne nara iisi. Te na neo dhèle dènge ka ana nèti bhèni ne.<bt>It used its tail to sweep clean one part of the stars out of three parts in the sky. Then it threw those stars to the earth. Next it went ot stand before that woman, to wait until she gave birth. Cuz (elaboration) it wanted to right away swallow that child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèle = telan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">dhèle = telan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="triteen: one third, one out of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">triteen: one third, one out of every three stars. Alternate, more appropriate in some contexts, "30%". The English term "third" is known and used, but it is also homophonous with a coprology.</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 8:10</note><v n="5" />Hèia bhèni ne nara iisi Ana Mone ca dhèu. Te ngaa ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ca dhèu nèti sorga, mai parame nare Ana ne, ka rai nèti asa Lamatua, sèna ka nèd'u paredha sama-sama dènge Ama Lamatua ètu sorga. Te bèli-camèd'a Ana ne paredha suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha dènge koasa dhu kapai risi eele.<bt>Then, that woman gave birth to a Male Child. But an angel of God from heaven came and snatched that Child, and brought him to the Lord so that that child ruled together with God in heaven. Cuz (elaboration) that aforementioned Child, later would rule all the tribes/nations on earth with extremely amazing authority/power.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poimainei: firmness, not force"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">poimainei: firmness, not force</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 66:7, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:9</note><v n="6" />Te ngaa bhèni ne rai la'e asa d'ara mamoo èci dhu Lamatua tao tèke hia ne. Pe ra ladhe-leru ne, toke tèlu tèu dènge ca èta, (nuka, 1.260 [ca riho dua ngasu èna nguru] lod'o).<bt>But that woman ran to a quiet/desolate place which the Lord had prepared for her. Later they took care of her there for three and half years (that is 1260 days).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mikael pamusu dènge mege naga ètu sorga [\s2]<bt>Mikael wars against the dragon (loan) snake in heaven [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Èle èèna ka, j'aj'i pamusu aae ètu sorga. Ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga, dènge kapala musu ra Mikael, lab'a mege naga dènge ana pajuu na.<bt>After that then there was a big war in heaven. The angels with their commander-in-chief Mikael warred against that snake dragon and its underlings.</bt><note reference="12:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 10:13, 21, 12:1, Yudas 9</note><v n="8" />Ka Mikael si segi mege naga ne dènge ana pajuu na sèra. Èle ka, ra kai mege naga ne dènge ana pajuu na sèra, ho pea ia ka ètu sorga.<bt>And Mikael (collective) defeated that snake dragon and its underlings. Then they forbade that snake dragon and its underlings, so that they could not stay in heaven anymore.</bt><v n="9" />Nèti èèna ka, ra bhabhoo eele si nèti sorga, hèia core si asa rai-haha. Mege naga ne, nuka dhèu aae nidhu, dhu ngara na &lt;Lamatua nidhu&gt;. Karèi nèti uru ka, nèngu ne'e ka dhu leko-monya dhèu ho ad'u-ue sasala.<bt>Because of that, they expelled threw them out of heaven, then threw them to earth. That aforementioned dragon snake, that is the evil.spirit's king, whom they call &lt;Lord/Master of evil spirits&gt;. From long ago, he habitually lied to/deceived people so that they would do wrong.</bt><note reference="12:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 3:1, Lukas 10:18</note><v n="10" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi hari lii dhu mèdhu èci nèti dedha-liru, peka na,<bt>Then I heard again a loud voice from the sky, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Uru èèna, mege naga ne'e ka dhu titu dhii-dhii ètu madha Ama Lamatua.<bt>“Previously that dragon snake kept standing (refusing to give up place) in front of God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhii-dhii = tidak mau ondor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">dhii-dhii = tidak mau ondor</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasab'a nèngu, nuka pèci sasala asa a'ari èdhi, dhèu parcaya sèra.<bt>His is the one whose work is to throwing wrongs (= blame/accusing) at our siblings who believe.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Na loe boe galaa si mèu-mèda.<bt>He keeps accusing them daytime-nighttime.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa limuri ne, ra bhabhoo eele ne nèti sorga.<bt>But now he/it is thrown out of heaven.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhabhoo = usir"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bhabhoo = usir</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De limuri ne aa'i-aa'i tesa le.<bt>So (consequently) everything is complete. [EXEG: Teams queried theology implying “salvation” etc. hadn't happened before. NLT gives sense of completeness or final step for everything to be complete. More support in Ex.Summ. and LN of Gk on /arti egeneto/.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te d'ai lod'o na kèna, sèna ka Lamatua hia mamuri mi dhèu rai-haha.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) now the time has come for God to save/give life to humans.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Limuri ne Lamatua nèd'u le paredha dènge koasa Na dhu kapai.<bt>Now God rules with His great/amazing power/authority.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Na ded'e le Kristus,<bt>And He has raised up Kristus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Dhèu dhu hag'e nare ho j'aj'i Dhèu Aae dhu paredha suku aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>that Person whom He chose to become King who governs/rules all tribes/nations.</bt><note reference="12:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ayub 1:9-11, Sakaria 3:1</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />A'ari èdhi sèra ka dhu segi mege naga èèna, dhu uru èèna pèci sasala mi rèngu,<bt>Our siblings have defeated that snake dragon who previously kept accusing them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula raa Ana Kalèbho dhu suti sèna ka saku eele sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>because the Sheep Offspring's blood has spilled to erase their wrongs.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">A'ari èdhi segi ne kahèi,<bt>They also defeated him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula rèngu bani lole Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua.<bt>because they dared to tell the Lord's Words.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Masi ka dhèu nasa ho neo pamadhe si,<bt>Even though people got angry and wanted to kill them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa ra bege boe.<bt>nevertheless they did not retreat/withdraw/shrink back.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bege = taku = madha'u"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bege = taku = madha'u</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />De aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri ètu sorga hud'i karej'e-karae ku!<bt>So (consequently), all who live in heaven, [you] must be happy!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri ètu rai-haha hud'i bori pa'èra ku,<bt>But all who live on earth must watch out,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula mamadhe-mamopo oe bèbhe mai lèke miu.<bt>because misfortune/calamity is about to befall you-pl.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu aae nidhu puru mai le ètu talora aae miu.<bt>The evil spirit's king has come down among you(pl).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu nasa titu kèna,<bt>He is very angry,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula ne'a, na, lod'o ho nèngu tao bhabhelu, oe èle kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>because he knows, that time of this for doing evil, is about to finish!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eufrainete: more than &quot;be happy&quot; or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">eufrainete: more than "be happy" or "feel good" hoi ... skeenountes: those who live temporarily<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mege naga patangi-tenge bhèni èèna ètu rai-haha [\s2]<bt>The snake dragon keeps looking for the woman on earth [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa mege naga ne'a, na, nèngu dhu ra core le asa rai-haha, ka la'e dènge tenge bhèni dhu nara iisi Ana èèna, ho neo paj'èra ne.<bt>When that snake dragon knew that he was cast off to the earth, then he went to find that woman who had given birth to that Child, to cause difficulty to her. [EXEG: troubled/pursued the woman, or the Child (who was already taken to heaven)? vs. 14 and all versions imply it is the woman. Referent needs to be clear. CHECK. OK]</bt><v n="14" />Te ngaa ra hia bhèni ne èla dua, nuka sèmi èla manea luji, sèna ka na lela la'e lu'u asa d'ara mamoo dhu pakaj'èu nèti mege naga. Ètu era nèi, ra ladhe-leru ne, toke tèlu tèu dènge ca èta.<bt>But they gave that woman two wings, like eagle wings, so that she could fly go hide in that desolate place that was far from that snake dragon. There they took care of her for three and half years. [EXEG: TH, HCE, Uma, Mounce, Hughes]</bt><note reference="12:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani uru tèka, suri peka na, &lt;&lt;ca lod'o, dua lod'o, dènge ca'èta lod'o&gt;&gt;. Lii se'e, sama sèmi ètu sasuri <span class="Italic">Daniel</span> 7:25, 12:7. Lod'o èèna, nuka 42 (èpa nguru dua) hèru, do, 1.260 (ca riho dua ngasu èna nguru) lod'o ètu fasal 11:2-3.<bt>The original Yunani language Bible writes, saying, “one time, two times, and half (a) time”. Those words are the same as what is in <span class="Italic">Daniel</span> 7:25, 12:7. The time is the same as 42 months, or, 1,260 days in chapter 11:2-3 above.</bt></note><v n="15" />Ropa nèdhi nare sèmi èèna, hèia mege naga ne sabhuu èi, nuka sèmi èi aae lala, ho neo hae nèti bhèni ne.<bt>When he saw that, that snake dragon spit out water like a flood, to sweep take away that woman.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hae = mengalir"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hae = mengalir</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Te ngaa rai-haha bara bhèni ne, dènge j'ara pacangange rai, ho dhèla aa'i mèu-mèu èi ne, dhu kalua nèti d'ara hèb'a mege naga, sèna ka baku d'ai bhèni ne.<bt>But the earth helped that woman by opening its land to swallow up that water that flowed coming out of that snake dragon's mouth, so that that water didn't get to that woman.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pacangange ~ pacanganga = buka lebar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pacangange ~ pacanganga = buka lebar (mulut)</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ka mege naga ne nasa titu kèna dènge bhèni ne. Hèia la'e pamusu dènge ana-ana leo nèti bhèni ne, nuka dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu lii paredha Ama Lamatua, aa dhu loe boe nèti peka-padhai Lii Lolo Be'a lula-nèti Yesus.<bt>Then that snake dragon was extremely angry with that woman. So it went out to fight against that woman's other children, that is the people who live following/obeying God's commands, and who continually spread around Yesus' Good News.</bt><v n="18" />Èle èèna ka, mege naga ne la'e titu ka ètu sebhe dhasi, dènge kadhi ngutu kèru-kèru.<bt>After that the snake dragon went to stand on the edge of the sea, and ground his teeth (in frustration/anger). [NOTE: last clause added (context: implicit &gt; explicit) Sept 2005 M. Crofts]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèru-kèru ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kèru-kèru =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Badha bhelu dhu kalua nèti d'ara dhasi<bt>The ferocious animal that comes out of the sea</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ja'a kèdhi badha bhelu ci'u dhu kalua nèti d'ara dhasi. Badha ne, kètu na pidhu, aa tadhu na canguru. Ètu kolo tadhu na sèra, dhu pake solo dhèu aae. Ètu kètu na sèra, dhu suri lii-lii pakarehe Ama Lamatua.<bt>After that, I saw a ferocious animal come out of the sea. He had seven heads, and ten horns. He wore king hats on top of each of his horns. On those heads were written words which are offensive to/blaspheming/slandering God.</bt><note reference="13:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:3, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 17:3, 7-12</note><v n="2" />Ngi'u na, sama sèmi meo aasu. Haga na, èci èèna ka dènge haga kiu aau. Hèb'a na sèmi hèb'a singa. Mege naga èèna pangèd'u koasa na mi badha bhelu ne, ho madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha, aa pake koasa na aa'i-aa'i.<bt>His body, was like a tiger. His feet/legs, were like bear's feet. And his mouth, like lion's mouth (loan). That snake dragon handed over his authority to that wild animal, so that he sat on that ruling chair, and he used all of his power/authority. [CHECK animals if known.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meo aasu = harimau ; kiu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">meo aasu = harimau ; kiu aau = beruang,</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:4-6</note><v n="3" />Ètu kètu èci nèti badha bhelu ne, abhu era hisu aae èci, nuka sèmi dhu ra pare ne ka oe madhe, te ngaa madhe boe. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne malaa, ropa ladhe rèdhi a'èra na, ka dhèu se madhutu ne.<bt>On one of the wild animal's heads was a big former wound, as if he had once been cut until he almost died, but he didn't die. All the people on earth were amazed looking at that wild animal's strength, and people followed/obeyed it/him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaba kètu = tempurung kepala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kaba kètu = tempurung kepala</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dhèu se pahaha iisi ra mi mege naga ne, dènge ded'e padedha-dedha ne nuka sèmi Lamatua, lula mege ne ka dhu pangèd'u koasa na mi badha bhelu èèna. Dhèu sèra koa-kio kahèi badha bhelu ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne kapai titu kèna! Abhu boe èci sa dhu bisa segi ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Those people worshipped that dragon snake and lifted him up high like God, because that snake had handed over power/authority to that ferocious animal. Those people also kept praising that ferocious animal, saying, “He there, is incredibly amazing/great! There is no one who can defeat him!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ama Lamatua soro tèke badha bhelu ne, sèna ka na padedha iisi na, aa padhai lii pakarehe Lamatua. Hia ne ijin kahèi, ho nèd'u paredha toke d'ai tèlu tèu dènge ca èta (nuka 42 [èpa nguru dua] hèru).<bt>God permitted that ferocious animal to speak arrogantly and speak offensively to/blaspheme/slander God. He was given permission to hold ruling authority for three and a half years (that is) 42 months. [EXEG: “was permitted” by whom? TH (followed by Uma) says by God, but in vs. 2 and 4 it is the dragon who is giving authority of different kinds to the beast. Mounce says John's readers would have understood the 4 occurrences in 5-7 to be “by divine permission” of God.]</bt><v n="6" />Nèti èèna ka, na padhai lii pamanahu kolongara Ama Lamatua, dènge pakarehe kolongara dhèu-dhèu unu Lamatua dhu pea ètu sorga.<bt>That's why he spoke making fall (slander2) God's name/reputation. And he also slandered/defiled all of God's people who live in heaven.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="skeeneen: the portability is not in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">skeeneen: the portability is not in focus; it's the Old Testament allusion</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:5-6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:8, 25, 11:36</note><v n="7" />Ama Lamatua soro tèke ne kahèi, ho pamusu lab'a dhèu-dhèu unu Lamatua, toke na segi. Na abhu koasa kahèi, sèna ka paredha suku aa'i-aa'i, udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i, lii aa'i-aa'i, aa kabarai aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>God also gave permission to him, to war against God's people, until he defeated them. He also was given authority/power to rule people of all the clans, all the tribes, all the languages, and all the nations/countries on earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ètu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ètu</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:21</note><v n="8" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne, sogo-tagu badha bhelu èèna, nuka rèngu aa'i-aa'i dhu ngara ra suri boe ètu d'ara Sasuri Ana Kalèbho. Uru èèna dhèu pamadhe Ana Kalèbho èèna, te ngaa Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne. Lod'o Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i mèka rai-haha ne, Nèngu dhu suri nare le ngara-ngara nèti dhèu parcaya aa'i-aa'i ra ètu d'ara sasuri Na. Dhu peka na, pe rèngu sèra ka dhu unu mamuri taa-taa, toke d'ai mia-mia dènge Nèngu.<bt>Because of that, all the people on earth (traditional/non-Christian) worshipped that aforementioned ferocious animal. They were all the people who names were not written in that Book of the Sheep Offspring. Previously people had killed that Sheep Offspring, but God made him live again. When God had still not yet made this world, He had already written ahead of time all the believer's names in that writing. It said, they are the ones who would later get true/real life with Him that never ends.</bt><note reference="13:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:29</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />&lt;&lt;Nanene paie-iie!<bt>“Listen well!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Ladhe Lamatua pama'ète nare le, dhèu cee ka dhu hud'i lèke kèpe,<bt>If God decides that there is someone who must be captured/arrested,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pe ra kèpe rare ne.<bt>later he will be captured.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa ladhe Lamatua pama'ète nare le, dhèu cee ka dhu hud'i madhe ku dènge samala,<bt>If God decides that there is someone who must die with/by a fighting sword,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pe ra pamadhe nèngu pake samala kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>later he will be killed by a fighting sword.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Nèti èèna ka, dhèu-dhèu unu Lamatua baku hari kabodho, te èèna hia ra tebho ho madhutu taruu dènge parcaya Na taa-taa!<bt>Because of that, God's people shouldn't retreat/pull back, cuz (elaboration) that is an opportunity to endure following and believing in Him continually!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lula nèti èèna ka, dhèu-dhèu unu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Lula nèti èèna ka, dhèu-dhèu unu Lamatua hud'i pa'èra-èra ku madhutu Na taa-taa, te Nèngu ka dhu tao tèke le se'e aa'i-aa'i.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 14:2."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 14:2.</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 15:2, 43:11</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Badha bhelu dhu bhodho nèti rai-haha<bt>The ferocious animal that comes out of the earth</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle, hèia ja'a kèdhi badha bhelu dhu leo ci'u, bhodho nèti rai-haha. Tadhu na dua, nuka sèmi tadhu kahib'i-kalèbho. Lii na nuka sèmi lii mege naga.<bt>After that, I saw another ferocious animal come up out of the earth. He had two horns, like a sheep's horn/s. And his voice, was like the dragon snake's voice.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhodo = muncul (dari bawah)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bhodo = muncul (dari bawah)</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Nèngu nèti lii padhai lamatua na, nuka badha bhelu dhu uru èèna, dhu lèke pare ka oe madhe. Na abhu koasa nèti lamatua na, sèna ka na laka-seti dhèu rai-haha aa'i-aa'i ho sogo-tagu lamatua na.<bt>He became a spokesperson for his lord/master, who was that aforementioned first ferocious animal, who previously was inflicted with a cut almost dying. He received power/authority from that lord/master of his, in order to force all people on earth to [trad.] worship his lord/master.</bt><v n="13" />Nèngu tao tadha-tadha malaa dhu kapai kahèi, toke na bisa papuru ai nèti dedha-liru, ètu madha dhèu ae-ae.<bt>He also did amazing signs that were incredible, to the point that he could bring down fire from heaven in front of many people. [EXEG: Gk just says “before (the) men/people”, so don't get caught up in noise from translations that say “all” or “everyone”, since it is contextually driven, not driven by the Gk text.]</bt><v n="14" />Dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e, ka badha bhelu ka dua ne, pake koasa nèti lamatua na, ho kapod'e-kabèli dhèu rai-haha. Na paredha dhèu ho tao mèdha sogo-tagu cue, rupa na nuka sèmi lamatua na, sèna ka ra pakab'ua lamatua na, dhu uru èèna dhèu pare ne, ka oe madhe.<bt>In that way, that ferocious animal number two, used his boss' power to deceive people on earth. He also ordered people to make an object of worship, like his boss' appearance/shape/form, so they could honour his boss who previously was inflicted with a cut almost dying. [EXEG: “with a sword” explicit - implicit, since “cut” here evokes the earlier reference. Forcing it would be heavy info load.]</bt><v n="15" />Ama Lamatua soro tèke kahèi, badha dhu kapod'e-kabèli ne, ho na hia a'ae, sèna ka pamamuri mèdha sogo-tagu ne. Nèti èèna ka, mèdha sogo-tagu ne bisa padhai lii, ho pua pamadhe dhèu dhu ro'o boe pahaha iisi mi nèngu.<bt>Father God also allowed that aforementioned animal deceiver, to give breath making that object of traditional worship live. Because of that, that object of traditional worship could talk, and give orders to kill people who did not want to worship him. [EXEG: see note at vs. 5 on God as agent.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Badha dhu kapod'e-kabèli ne laka-seti dhèu kahèi, sèna ka tao tadha mi ai g'ana ra, do mi katangarèi ra. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i, nuka ana iiki-dhèu kapai, dhèu kaja-dhèu unu aad'o, dhèu ènu, do dhèu mardeka, rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra hud'i abhu ku cap èèna.<bt>That animal deceiver also forced people to receive a sign on their right hands, or on their foreheads. All people, small-big, rich-poor, freed or slave, they all must receive that stamp/brand.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 11:18; 3:17; 6:15."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 11:18; 3:17; 6:15.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Te ladhe aad'o, dhèu sèra bisa boe pahia do pahèli ngaa-ngaa. Ètu d'ara cap ne, dhu suri ngara badha bhelu ka èci, dènge nomer na.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if they didn't, they could not sell or buy anything. On that stamp was written that first wild animal's name and his number.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />De hud'i pangee paie-iie! Dhèu dhu d'èlu-mèu bisa re'a sasoa nèti nomer èèna. Nuka &lt;&lt;666&gt;&gt; (èna ngasu èna nguru èna), dhu paj'uj'u mi dhèu rai-haha.<bt>So you need to think carefully! The person/ whoever is smart can understand that number's meaning. That number which designates human/s is “666”.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 13:10."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 13:10.</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu dhèu d'èlu-mèu Alkitab, uru èèna ètu nèi, nomer &lt;&lt;èna&gt;&gt;, sasoa na, ca j'ara dhu be'a boe, dhu tesa boe, dhu mèci boe, aa dhu bhelu-katub'a. De nomer &lt;&lt;èna ngasu èna nguru èna&gt;&gt;, sasoa na, &lt;&lt;dhu bhelu risi eele&gt;&gt;.<bt>According to people who are knowledgable about the Bible, long ago in that place, the number “6” meant something that was not good, not complete, or evil. So (consequently), this number “666” here means “most evil”. [UBS Study Notes.]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana Kalèbho dènge dhèu Na 144.000 (cangasu èpa nguru èpa riho) dhèu<bt>The Sheep Offspring with His 144.000 people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="14" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a boti kètu, kaca'a laa, ja'a ladhe kèdhi Ana Kalèbho dhu titu ètu kolo ledhe iiki èci. Ngara na ledhe Sion. Na titu dènge dhèu Na 144.000 (cangasu èpa nguru èpa riho) dhèu. Ètu katangarèi dhèu se'e, dhu suri ngara Ana Kalèbho, dènge ngara Ama Na.<bt>After that I lifted my head, and unexpectedly I saw that Sheep Offspring standing on top of a small mountain. The mountain was named Sion. He stood together with 144.000 people. On their foreheads, were written that Sheep Offspring name and His Father's name.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Mt. Zion: here represents the seat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Mt. Zion: here represents the seat of the Messianic Kingdom on earth The Lamb: Rev. 5:6.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>144,000: Rev. 7:4.</Message></Annotation><note reference="14:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 9:4, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 7:3</note><v n="2" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi lii èci nèti dedha-liru. Lii ne kadèru sèmi lii bèbhe naha dhasi kapai, aa dou sèmi lii d'oro. Te ngaa lii ne culi be'a titu kèna, nuka sèmi dhèu ae dhu karihu sasadhu.<bt>Then I heard a voice/sound from the sky. The voice was roaring like large waves breaking (in the west monsoon), and loud like the sound of thunder. But that aforementioned voice/sound, was also very sharp/clear like there were many people playing sasandos [traditional Rotinese/Timorese stringed instrument].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="culi = suara halus, nada tinggi,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">culi = suara halus, nada tinggi, tajam ; @@</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lii ne kapai sèmi lii èi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Lii ne kapai sèmi lii èi hae nèti kolo ledhe, dou sèmi lii d'oro.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="I hear a voice: see Rev."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">I hear a voice: see Rev. 10:4. Like the sound of many waters: see Rev. 1:15.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>Loud thunder: see Rev. 6:1.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ka ja'a kèdhi 144.000 (cangasu èpa nguru èpa riho) dhèu se, dhu titu tangare asa madha Ama Lamatua, dènge badha aae èpa ngi'u dhu reo rare kadera paredha Lamatua, aa dènge katua-katua sèra. Dhèu ae-ae se sod'a lii sod'a hiu èci. Lii sod'a ne, dhodhoka rèngu di dhu re'a, dhèu leo aad'o. Te rèngu dhu pabe'a le dènge Lamatua, lula Lamatua pake raa Ana Na, ho sui si nèti sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>And I saw those 144.000 people were standing facing God, and those four extra-ordinary animals who surround that chair of God's, and those elders. Those many people were singing a new song. Only they themselves knew that song, but other people didn't know it. Cuz (elaboration) it was they who were in a reciprocally good relationship with God, because God had used His Child's blood to *redeem them from their wrongs (doublet). [NOTE: “from the earth” undertranslated so as not to skew the information load.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="They sing: Rev 13:12. Before the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">They sing: Rev 13:12. Before the throne...four living creatures...elders: Rev. 4.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>TERM: eegorasmenoi 'redeemed' 5:9 fo buy back peopo fo bring um to God</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Mamuri rèngu mola-mèci le, nuka sèmi mone kalora iisi dhu pa'èci nèdhi mèka dènge dhèu bhèni. Rèngu parai eele boe dènge Ana Kalèbho èèna, sad'i asa era mia èèna ka, lula Ama Lamatua sui le rèngu pake raa Ana Na, sèna ka rèngu j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua. Rèngu èci èèna ka dènge hua hela dhu uru tèka nèti d'ara oka hia mi Lamatua dènge Ana Kalèbho.<bt>Their lives were clean/holy, like bachelors who have never played around with women. They followed that Sheep Offspring, wherever it went, because God had redeemed/paid for them using His Child's blood, so that they would become His people/possession. They here were like the first harvest which people bring from the garden to give to God and the Sheep Offspring. [CHECK term for bachelor]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mone kalora iisi = bujang (check)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mone kalora iisi = bujang (check)</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Rèngu dhu re'a boe padhai lii leko-monya, lula d'ara ra mola.<bt>They also did not speak deceptively, because their insides were straight/clean/holy.</bt><note reference="14:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sefanya 3:13</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tèlu ana pajuu nèti sorga rèti lii<bt>Three angels from heaven bring news</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka ja'a kèdhi ana pajuu Lamatua ca dhèu hari mai nèti sorga. Ana pajuu ne dhu lela dedha titu kèna, ho rodhe palème Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua, dhu ma'ète boe ciki sa. Na lela palème era, ho peka dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha, nèti suku aa'i-aa'i, nèti udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i, nèti lii aa'i-aa'i, dènge negara aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Then I saw another angel from heaven. He was flying high in the sky, in.order.to call out spread/scatter the Lord's Good News that never ends. He flew around places telling all the people on the earth, from every tribe, every clan, every language, and every country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Another angel: angels have appeared already"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Another angel: angels have appeared already in Rev. 5:2, 10:1. Flying in midair: see Rev. 8:13.<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>TERM: Nation, tribe, language, people: see Rev. 5:9 "ohana, an language, an peopo, an country". The order differs from place to place, but probably could be regularized; it is the terms themselves that should be regularized more than their order. Check especially "language," which as inanimate does not need to be pluralized to be plural.</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Na pa'oo-parodha, peka na,<bt>He shouting out (doublet), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Miu hud'i pakab'ua ku Ama Lamatua!<bt>“You(pl) must give honour to God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Miu hud'i j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Na dhu dedha risi eele!<bt>You must lift up high His name which is most high!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula lod'o na d'ai le,<bt>Because the time has come for</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho Lamatua parisa lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i madhutu tatao ra.<bt>God to examine all people's cases according to their deeds.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Koa-kio Ne!<bt>Praise (doublet) Him!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Na!<bt>Lift up high His name!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Nèngu ka paj'aj'i liru dènge rai-haha.<bt>Because He is the one who made the sky and the land.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa nèti paredha Na, ka dhasi dènge madha èi j'aj'i aa'i mèu-mèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He is the one who commanded that all the seas and the water springs come into being.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èi madha = 1) tears, 2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">èi madha = 1) tears, 2) natural, springs; madha èi = dug wells</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ropa padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, hèia ja'a kèdhi hari ana pajuu dhu leo ca dhèu nèti sorga, dhu mai madhutu ana pajuu dhu mai uru èèna. Na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Laho eele le! Laho mae-mae le! Kota Babel dhu kapai na, laho le! Kota dhu bhelu èèna, guri eele le pamera dènge rai. Uru èèna, kota ne, nuka sèmi bhèni kajeo dhu laka-seti suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne ho rinu mahu, aa madhutu dad'èi na, ka ad'u-ue j'ara makae. Te ngaa limuri ne kota ne, pasae nare le pala na nèti nanasa Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he finished speaking like that, next I saw another angel, who came with the first angel. He spoke saying, “It's destroyed! It's completely destroyed! The great city of Babel is destroyed! That evil city, has fallen down to the ground. Previously that city was like a prostitute who forced all tribes to drink until drunk and to follow her will and do shameful things (implied sexual). But now that city has experienced God's anger!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="abhu le pala = su dapat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">abhu le pala = su dapat bagian</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Babylon is fallen: see Rev. 18:2-3."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Babylon is fallen: see Rev. 18:2-3.</Message></Annotation><note reference="14:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 21:9, Yermia 51:8, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 18:2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia ja'a kèdhi hari ana pajuu dhu leo ca dhèu nèti sorga, mai madhutu ana pajuu ka dua deo na. Na pa'oo-parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mata unu mi! Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu sogo-tagu badha bhelu dènge mèdha sogo-tagu na, do abhu cap ètu katangarèi, do ètu kacui-aai, pe rèngu pasae rare nanasa Lamatua!<bt>Then I saw yet another angel, who came following that number two angel. He shouted (doublet), saying, “Be careful! All people who [traditional/non-Christian] worship that ferocious animal and his object of traditional worship, or receive his stamp on their forehead, or hand, later they will also taste/feel God's anger!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The First Beast: Rev. 13:1, 14-15."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">The First Beast: Rev. 13:1, 14-15. Mark: Rev. 13:16.<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Bèli-camèd'a Lamatua mesa Na sabhori mai nanasa Na mi dedha rèngu, nuka sèmi Na panginu si èi uuru nèti èi anggor pèd'u. Èèna Na core si asa d'ara èi nasu dhu heo robhe-robhe dhu loe boe ciki sa. Ana pajuu Na nèti sorga sèra, aa Ana Kalèbho èèna kahèi ladhe rèdhi j'ara ne'e.<bt>Later God himself will pour out His anger on them, as if He is making them drink full strength wine that is bitter. Later He will throw expel them into the sulfur fire that burns without ending. His angels, and that Sheep Offspring also see that matter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: the wine = wrath metaphor,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">TERM: the wine = wrath metaphor, this time</Message></Annotation><note reference="14:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 51:17, Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 19:24, Yeskial 38:22</note><v n="11" />Peka ka laa, dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu sogo-tagu badha bhelu dènge mèdha sogo-tagu na, do rèngu dhu lèke le cap na, pe dui rare j'aj'èra taa-taa. Sèb'u nèti j'aj'èra rèngu bhodho mai loe boe mèu-mèda.&gt;&gt;<bt>The important thing is, all people who traditionally worships that animal and his object of traditional worship, or, accepts his stamp/brand/ identifying mark, later they will be endlessly tortured like that. And smoke from their suffering/torment rises day-night unceasingly.</bt><note reference="14:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 34:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12-13" />De se'e se, sasoa na, dhèu unu Ama Lamatua, hud'i nanene ku paie-iie lii paredha Na, aa parcaya taruu mi Yesus, aa baku hari kabodho.<bt>So (consequently), all that means, God's people must listen well to His commands, and continually believe in Yesus. [EXEG: LN and Ex. Summ. #1 Gk “endure” here is about persevering in persecution and difficulties (part c below), not just about faithfulness (part a above)]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ja'a tadèngi lii èci nèti dedha-liru, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis! Èu hud'i suri ku sèmi ne'e: karèi nèti deo ne'e, dhèu dhu parcaya Lamatua Yesus, ladhe ra madhe, rèngu abhu oto.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I heard a voice from the sky that told me, saying, “Yohanis! You must write like this: From now on, if/when people who believe in the Lord Yesus die, they will obtain an advantage/benefit.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a! Bèli-camèd'a rèngu sèra oto tare'a-re'a! Lula rèngu j'èra le ètu rai-haha, te ngaa ra taha ho madhutu taruu Lamatua. De èèna na, Lamatua b'ala j'aj'èra rèngu, ka rèngu mamuri j'èra heka ètu sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then God's Holy Spirit replied saying, “True! Later they will be truly advantaged! Because they have suffered difficulty on earth, but they endured following/obeying God. So (consequently), later God will reciprocate their suffering and they live with out any more suffering in heaven.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta erga autoon akolouthei met' autoon:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">ta erga autoon akolouthei met' autoon: information only, or skills? Erga probably includes the latter.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Hahuku Ama Lamatua ètu rai-haha nuka sèmi puu-g'ètu dhu pake hela pare j'u'u<bt>God's punishment on earth is like using a sickle to harvest</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a padoa kètu. Kaca'a laa, kèdhi ra'i-liru dhu pudhi lao-lao, aa ca dhèu dhu madhèdi ètu dedha na. Dhèu ne, oe sèmi Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Na pake dènge solo juara dhu tao nèti hualaa, aa nèd'u dènge hela pare j'u'u madèka èci.<bt>After that, I lifted my head. Unexpectedly, I saw a shiny white cloud, and there was a person who sat on it. That person, was like the Ideal/Original Human (*Son of Man). He was wearing a champion hat from gold, and holding a sharp sickle.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hela pare j'u'u = known by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hela pare j'u'u = known by young UNS's ; pudhi ha'a-ha'a</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Son of Man: Rev. 1:13."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Son of Man: Rev. 1:13.</Message></Annotation><note reference="14:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia ja'a kèdhi ana pajuu dhèu èci hari nèti sorga, kalua nèti d'ara Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Na rodhe dhèu dhu madhèdi ètu dedha ra'i-liru èèna, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pake hela èu èèna ho lamu puu-g'ètu ka! Te d'ai le hèru pakaboko isi rai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I saw again an angel, come out from God's Worship House. He called out to the person on the cloud saying, “Use your sickle to go harvest (imp)! Cuz (elaboration) the time to gather the earth's harvests, has come.”</bt><note reference="14:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yoel 3:13</note><v n="16" />Ka Dhèu dhu madhèdi ètu dedha ra'i-liru ne, kèpe nare hela na, ka na la'e puu-g'ètu. Hèia na oru kaboko isi rai nèti rai-haha.<bt>Then that Person who sat on that cloud, wielded his sickle and went to harvest (doublet), and gathered up the earth's harvests.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka ana pajuu dhu leo hari ca dhèu kalua nèti d'ara Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i ètu sorga. Nèngu nèd'u dènge hela pare j'u'u madèka èci, ho neo g'ètu hua aj'u.<bt>Then there was another angel came out of the Worship House in heaven. He was holding a sharp sickle to go pick fruit.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia ana pajuu dhu leo hari èci kalua nèti era tunu raa aj'u hèu mèngi ètu d'ara Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i ètu sorga. Sasab'a ana pajuu ne, nuka j'aga ai ètu era tunu raa aj'u hèu mèngi. Na pa'oo pua ana pajuu dhu nèd'u hela pare j'u'u deo na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pake ka hela èu èèna, ho lamu ka g'ètu hua aj'u ètu rai-haha! Te ètu nèi, hua anggor dhu madhasa aa'i le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then there was another angel came out from that place of burning resin in the Worship House in heaven. This angel's job, was to guard that place of burning fragrant resin. He yelled ordering that angel who held that sickle, saying, “Use that sickle of yours, to go pick fruit on the earth (imp)! Cuz (elaboration) the grape trees/bushes' fruits there are ripe.”</bt><v n="19" />Ka ana pajuu ne kèpe nare ka hela pare j'u'u na la'e asa rai-haha, ho na g'ètu hua anggor, j'ue dènge ii kateme. Hèia na pamaso hua anggor se asa d'ara bak pacèli anggor. Ka ra j'èli marèu anggor se, sèna ka rare èi. J'èli marèu hua anggor ètu d'ara bak pacèli ne, sasoa na, nanasa Lamatua.<bt>Then that angel holding his sickle went to the earth, to cut those grapes' bunches. And He put those grapes into a pressing/squeezing tank. Next they stepped all over the grapes to get their liquid/juice. Stepping on grapes in that pressing tanks, its meaning is God's anger.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ii = rangke ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ii = rangke ;</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Bak pacèli ne ètu li'u kota. Ropa ra j'èli marèu anggor se, hèia raa kalua ae-ae. Raa ne hae sama sèmi loko cue, dhu madhera na 300 (tèlu ngasu) kilo, aa marèma na d'ai ca meter ca èta.<bt>That pressing tank was outside the city. When they stepped on those grapes, then lots of blood flowed out. That blood flowed like a river, it's length 300 kilometers, and it's depth one and half meters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Edha = Rote"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Edha = Rote</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Carolyn Dyk illustrations?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Carolyn Dyk illustrations?</Message></Annotation><note reference="14:20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani suri madhera loko ne, &lt;&lt;1.600 (ca riho èna ngasu) <span class="Italic">stadia</span>&gt;&gt;, sama sèmi 296 (dua ngasu ceo nguru èna) toke 300 (tèlu ngasu) kilometer. Aa marèma loko ne, ra suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;katitu na, sèmi madhera dhari rarapa jara&gt;&gt;, nuka ca meter dènge ca'èta. Jara ra kapai risi nèti jara Edha.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes that river's length, saying, “1,600 <span class="Italic">stadia</span>”, that is 296-300 kilometers. And that river's depth they write, saying, “as high as a horse bit”, that is one and a half metres. Their horses are taller than Rote horses.</bt></note><note reference="14:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 63:3, Lii Roma Iisi 1:15, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 19:15</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana pajuu dhèu pidhu nèti sorga rèti pidhu calaka kapai asa rai-haha<bt>Seven angels from heaven bring seven great calamities to earth [NOTE to daughter translations: NRSV, NIV; every English translation seems to have a different title for this section, so just go with what's here -- it's as good/bad as any]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Yohanis ladhe nèdhi isi sorga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Yohanis ladhe nèdhi isi sorga</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="15" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ja'a ladhe kèdhi tadha èci ètu dedha-liru, dhu kapai titu kèna, toke ja'a malaa bia. Abhu ana pajuu dhèu pidhu nèti sorga, èci-èci ka dènge koasa ra, ho hia calaka kapai asa rai-haha. Pidhu calaka se, nuka j'aj'èra dhu limuri tèka. Ladhe j'ara se aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i ka, d'ara Ama Lamatua pacuhi, ka nasa heka dènge dhèu rai-haha.<bt>After that, I saw extra-ordinary sign in the sky to the point that I was totally amazed. There were seven angels, whom each one had the authority to send big catastrophes to earth. These seven catastrophes, were the final catastrophes. If they all had happened, na, it meant that God's insides was cool to the point that He was no longer angry with humans.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="plague: Rev. 9:18, great disaster that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">plague: Rev. 9:18, great disaster that injures and kills, often seen as God's punishment; a blow, calamity, terrible trouble</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ka ja'a kèdhi dhasi dhu ha'a-ha'a, nuka sèmi tèru dhu pab'ali dènge ai. Ja'a kèdhi kahèi dhèu ae dhu titu ètu sebhe dhasi èèna. Dhèu se'e ka dhu madhutu boe badha bhelu èèna, aa ra sogo-tagu boe mèdha sogo-tagu na, aa dhu sèmi boe cap na hèi. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i dhu kèpe dènge mèdha lii sod'a èci nuka sèmi sasadhu, dhu ra abhu nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>Then I saw a sea that shone/burned like glass which was mixed with fire. I also saw many people who were standing at that sea's edge. They were the ones, the people who did not follow that ferocious animal, did not worship his object of traditional worship, and did not accept his stamp either. They all held musical instruments like sasandos which they had received from God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Pool of glass: See Rev. 4:6"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Pool of glass: See Rev. 4:6 same Conquered: Rev. 2:7, 6:2.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>Beast: Rev. 13:1, 14-15, 16-17. Harps: Rev. 5:8.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ka ra sod'a lii sod'a èci dhu Musa suri. Musa ne, ana pua-paleha Ama Lamatua uru-uru sèra. Dhèu se'e se sod'a kahèi lii sod'a èci dhu koa-kio Yesus. Te uru èèna, dhèu pamadhe Ne, sama sèmi dhèu roro pamadhe ana kalèbho ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua, sèna ka pamaringi d'ara Na. Dhèu se sod'a, peka na,<bt>Then they sang a song from Musa, that is God's servant long ago. Those people also sang a song to praise Yesus. Cuz (elaboration) previously people had killed Him, like people kill a sheep offspring in the *temple to cool His insides. (=ask forgiveness; make things right with God). They sang saying, [NOTE to daughter translations: UNS's couldn't connect the dots about the Lamb without this explication.]</bt><note reference="15:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Musa tao lii sod'a ne, lod'o Lamatua lere nèti dhèu Isra'el sèra nèti Mesir, era j'aj'èra rèngu.<bt>Musa composed that song when God took the Isra'el people out of Masir, that suffering place of theirs.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua!<bt>“We praise (doublet) God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ji'i j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Na!<bt>We lift up high His name!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula koasa Lamatua kapai risi eele.<bt>Because God's power/authority is extra-ordinary.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dènge a'èra Na kapai titu kèna.<bt>And God's strength/greatness, is sooo amazing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu nèd'u le paredha mi suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha.<bt>God rules all the tribes on earth.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu j'aj'i Dhèu Aae mi udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha.<bt>God has become King for all the clans in the world.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tatao Lamatua mola sèmi isi pupu.<bt>God's deeds, are straight/honest/righteous as a blowgun arrow (idiom).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mola sèmi isi pupu = lurus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mola sèmi isi pupu = lurus seperti isi sumpit (straight as an [blowgun] arrow) &gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasab'a Lamatua be'a seli eele!<bt>God's work, is truly good!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">J'ara Lamatua mèu rèd'e-rèd'e.<bt>God's road/path, is very, very clean/pure (=righteous)!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèu rèd'e-rèd'e = bersih sekali, jernih"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">mèu rèd'e-rèd'e = bersih sekali, jernih</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mamuri Lamatua lèke mola-mola!<bt>God's life, is very correct/true/straight!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Moses song: Exodus 15:1-18, Deuteronomy 32:1-44,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Moses song: Exodus 15:1-18, Deuteronomy 32:1-44, the song Moses sang or composed.</Message></Annotation><note reference="15:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 15:1-18</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Lamatua,<bt>All the people lift up high God's name/reputation,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra koa-kio babe'a Lamatua.<bt>all the people praise God's goodness.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Lamatua mesa Na dhu mola-mèci.<bt>Because only God himself is who is clean/holy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Lamatua mesa Na di, dènge boe sasala.<bt>Only God himself is the one who doesn't have sin.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe suku aa'i-aa'i mai pahaha iisi mi Lamatua.<bt>Later all people/tribes will come to worship God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i mai manèngi makasi mi Lamatua.<bt>Later all clans will come to give thankyou to God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a rèdhi le tatao Lamatua dhu be'a.<bt>Because all people have seen God's deeds which are good.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a le mamola d'ara Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>And all people have known God's liver which is straight/righteous.” [EXEG: Gk. /dikaiwmata/ for last two lines as “righteous acts/deeds” (NLT, LN) rather than “judgements” (NRSV) -- fits context better.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Respeck your name: Rev. 11:18. Glorify"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Respeck your name: Rev. 11:18. Glorify your name: Rev. 11:13, 4:7.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>Holy: Rev. 16:5. Separate, God, different from people.</Message></Annotation><note reference="15:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 10:7, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 86:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ropa dhèu se èle sod'a, ja'a kèdhi Kama Luri Mola-Mèci ètu d'ara Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i Lamatua ètu sorga, dènge bhèla bhabhiri dhu bhoke pataleo tèke.<bt>When those people finished singing, then I saw that Room that is Very Holy/Taboo in God's Worship House in heaven, with it's blocking cloth was wide open. [NOTE: many lgs/UNS cannot have an open room (NLT actually sounds funny in English), but the cloth is wide open.] [EXEG: for “tent of witness” see summary discussion in TH. We follow their recommended solution, which seems to make the best sense in context.]</bt><note reference="15:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 38:21</note><v n="6" />Ka ja'a kèdhi ana pajuu dhèu pidhu nèti sorga dhu rèti dènge pidhu calaka sèra. Rèngu kalua mai nèti Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Rèngu pake mèdha-papake dhu kale'e pudhi mèu, aa pake salalu dhu tao nèti poe dènge pai.<bt>Then I saw those seven angels who brought those seven disasters. They were coming out of God's Worship House. They wore clothes that were shiny clean white, and they wore sashes made of original/pure gold.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Gold bands: Rev. 1:13."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Gold bands: Rev. 1:13.</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Hèia ja'a ladhe kèdhi badha aae èci nèti èpa ngi'u sèra ètu sebhe kadera paredha Lamatua, dhu papala pidhu bokor hualaa mi ana pajuu dhèu pidhu sèra. Pidhu bokor se, èci-èci ka dhu isi ra hahuku nèti Ama Lamatua dhu taa-taa toke d'ai mia-mia. Te Na pa'èra le, ho sabhori nanasa Na asa rai-haha.<bt>Then2 I saw those four extra-ordinary animals who were at the side of God's ruling chair, divide out seven (wide rimmed) gold bowls/basins to those seven angels. Each one of those seven bowls were filled with judgements/punishments from God who exists continually forever. He was ready to pour out His anger on the world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bokor = baskom air, wash basin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bokor = baskom air, wash basin</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Nèbhu boe, hèia Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne pènu dènge sèb'u dhu bodho mai nèti dadedha dènge koasa Ama Lamatua. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa maso asa era èèna. Ana pajuu dhèu pidhu se hud'i sabhori pa'èle ku pidhu calaka asa rai-haha ne, heka dhèu bisa maso asa era èèna kèna.<bt>Not much longer (=soon), then that Worship House was full of smoke, which came out of God's greatness/majesty and His power/authority. There was not a single person who could enter in there. Those seven angels had to finish pouring out those seven catastrophes on the earth, before a person could go in there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dadedha = ketinggian"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">dadedha = ketinggian</Message></Annotation><note reference="15:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 40:34, 1 Dhèu Aae sèra 8:10-11, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 5:13-14, Yesaya 6:4</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nanasa Ama Lamatua bhori mai asa rai-haha<bt>God's anger poured out on the earth</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="16" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi lii parodha èci kalua nèti d'ara Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ho peka dènge ana pajuu dhèu pidhu se, na, &lt;&lt;Lami ka! Nedhe mèti ka bokor se'e, ho bhori ka nanasa Lamatua asa rai-haha.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I heard a loud voice come out of the Worship House to order those seven angels saying, “Go! Pick up and take those bowls/basins to pour out God's anger on the earth (imp).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ropa tadèngi rare, hèia ana pajuu ka èci la'e bhori isi bokor na asa rai-haha. Kaca'a laa, papèd'a-tarègu lèke dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu uru sèra abhu cap nèti badha bhelu, dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu sogo-tagu mèdha sogo-tagu na. Rèngu se lèke èi papèd'a hisu huu dhu rarii titu kèna.<bt>When I heard that, then the first angel poured out his bowl's contents on the earth. Suddenly, calamity (doublet) struck all the people who had ever received that wild animal's stamp, and the people who worshipped that object of traditional worship of his. They were afflicted with rotten sores (like large boils) that were terribly painful.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hisu huu = luka bisul yg"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hisu huu = luka bisul yg besar</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 9:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Èle èèna ka, ana pajuu ka dua la'e bhori isi bokor na asa d'ara dhasi. Kaca'a laa, èi ètu d'ara dhasi j'aj'i raa dhu hèu mau, cakaraa hèu raa dhèu madhe. Ka aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri ètu d'ara dhasi madhe aa'i si.<bt>Then angel number two poured out his bowl's content into the sea. Suddenly, the water in the sea became rotten smelling blood, like a dead person's blood. And everything that lived in the sea, completely died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèu mau = bau busuk dari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hèu mau = bau busuk dari darah manusia</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Exodus 7:20-21."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Exodus 7:20-21.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia ana pajuu ka tèlu la'e bhori isi bokor na asa d'ara loko dènge madha èi. Ka èi aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i raa.<bt>Then angel number three poured out his bowl's contents into the rivers and water springs. And all those waters became blood.</bt><note reference="16:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 7:17-21, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 78:44</note><v n="5" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi ana pajuu ca dhèu nèti sorga, dhu uri èi aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne. Na koa-kio Ama Lamatua, peka na,<bt>Then I heard an angel, who was (in charge of) ruling/governing/managing all the water on earth. He praised God saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Oo Lamatua!<bt>“O Lord!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua dhu mola-mèci!<bt>Lord (=you) is the one who is holy!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua dhu sala nèdhi boe!<bt>Lord (=you) is the one who is never wrong/sinful!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua mema-mema karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>Lord (=you) really are from the beginning,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Lamatua taa-taa toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>And the Lord (=you) later will be forever.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua pama'ète lii langu dhu mola isi pupu.<bt>Lord (=you) have judged/decided cases/disputes straight/correctly (idiom).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua hia le huku dhu kasii-kasore boe.<bt>Lord (=you) has given judgements/punishments that are appropriate (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasii-kasore = babengko"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kasii-kasore = babengko</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Dhèu-dhèu pasuti le,<bt>People have spilled</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">raa nèti dhèu unu Lamatua.<bt>the Lord's people's blood.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu-dhèu pamadhe le,<bt>People have killed</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua.<bt>the Lord's spokespeople.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua laka-seti si, ho rinu raa kahèi.<bt>That's why, the Lord (=you) has forced them to also drink blood ( = suffer).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua b'ala si, dènge huku dhu lèke.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's why, the Lord (=you) has reciprocated with a correct punishment.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Èle ka, ja'a tadèngi lii èci kalua nèti mei sogo-tagu, peka na,<bt>After that, I heard a voice come out from the sacrifice table which replied saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Tare'a! Ama Lamatua dhu koasa kapai risi eele.<bt>“True! God is the one who is most powerful.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Tare'a! Ama Lamatua dhu èra risi aa'i.<bt>True! God is the one who is most great/influential.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua dhu pama'ète lii langu dhu koe boe kapengo boe.<bt>God is the one who judges fairly/without prejudice.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua dhu pamanahu huku dhu lèke mola-mola.&gt;&gt;<bt>God is the one who hands down punishments that are appropriate.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia ana pajuu ka èpa la'e bhori isi bokor na asa madha lod'o. Kaca'a laa, lod'o pana titu kèna, ka dhèu ètu rai-haha ne kèpu-ladhu ai.<bt>Then angel number four poured out the contents of his bowl on the sun. Unexpectedly/suddenly the sun became exceedingly hot, to the point that humans were burned (doublet).</bt><v n="9" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu lèke tunu se, dhoo kolongara Ama Lamatua, lula Nèngu ka dhu papuru calaka ne hia mai asa rèngu. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu ele-ho'a, ka lèpa asa Lamatua ho koa-kio kolongara Na.<bt>All those humans who were burned, they cursed God's name, because He was the one who ordered that calamity (loan) to be sent to them. Even that being the case, nevertheless there was not a single person who *repented, then returned to God to praised His name.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka ana pajuu ka lèmi la'e bhori isi bokor na asa kadera paredha badha bhelu se. Kaca'a laa, maroga kiu-kiu saguru nare dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu sogo-tagu ne, toke j'èra titu kèna hèia ra gègu-ria.<bt>Then, that angel number five poured out his bowl's contents on that wild animal's ruling chair. Suddenly, then pitch darkness covered all the people who worshipped him, to the point that the suffering was so great they ground their teeth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gègu-ria = grinding sound of molars"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">gègu-ria = grinding sound of molars ; ria = (gigi) geraham ; can makan gigi from 1) anger, 2) to withstand pain (UNS's)</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 10:21</note><v n="11" />Dhèu se'e kahèi dhoo Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, lula hisu ra rarii titu kèna. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu ae eele nèti bhabhelu ra, ka lèpa asa Ama Lamatua.<bt>They also cursed God in heaven because those sores of theirs, were extremely painful. Even though it was like that, nevertheless there was not even one who stopped doing evil, and returned to God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia ana pajuu ka èna bhori isi bokor na asa loko aae, dhu ngara na Efrat. Ka loko ne mango-meto dènge ka. Hèia ra tao j'ara ètu d'ara loko ne, hia dhèu aae-dhèu aae dènge sordad'u-sordad'u dhu bèli-camèd'a mai nèti cabèka dhimu.<bt>Then angel number six poured out his bowl's contents on that big river, named Efrat. Then that river dried up (doublet) right away. Then they made a road in the riverbed there for kings and armies that would later come from the east. [EXEG: Gk only mentions kings here, but context is major battle (e.g. vs.14). NLT mentions armies in this verse. Regional lg patterns for background-foreground info require it to be placed here.]</bt><note reference="16:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 11:15</note><v n="13" />Ka ja'a ladhe kèdhi nidhu bhelu tèlu. Rupa ra sama sèmi ana gaged'e. Ci'u bhodho nèti d'ara hèb'a mege naga. Ci'u kalua nèti d'ara hèb'a badha bhelu. Aa ci'u hari bhodho nèti hèb'a dhèu kapod'e-kabèli, dhu nèti lii padhai mege naga èèna.<bt>Then I saw three evil spirits. Their shape/forms were like frogs. One came out of that dragon snake's mouth. One came out of that wild animal's mouth. And one more came out of that dragon snake's deceptive spokesperson's mouth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana gaged'e = katak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ana gaged'e = katak</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Nidhu tèlu se dènge koasa ho tao rupa-rupa tadha malaa. Ra kalua, lasi paraga dènge dhèu aae aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha, ka ra pajaji ho ètu d'ara ca lod'o sa lasi pamusu, lab'a Ama Lamatua dhu koasa kapai risi eele èèna. Te ngaa lod'o dhu ra pajaji èèna, lèke dènge lod'o dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le, ho Na segi musu Na aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Those three evil spirits had power/authority to do all sorts of miracles. They came out to go meet all the kings in the world, then they promised each other a time to go war against God who is most powerful. But that time which they promised then, matched God's time which He had already chosen to defeat all his enemies.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Great Day of God Almighty: Rev."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Great Day of God Almighty: Rev. 19:11-15.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15-16" />Era dhu ra pakaboko ho pamusu èèna, lii Ibrani peka na, <span class="Italic">Armagedon.</span><bt>That place where they will gather to go to war, Hebrew language says <span class="Italic">Armagedon.</span> [NOTE: some MTT's want to know what ‘Armadegon’ means. The scholars have wide ranging views on what it means and where it is, and whether or not it is symbolic, cryptic, or geographical. Best discussion in Mounce (on TW4). Info not clear enough to make a coherent ftn.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yesus Kristus peka kahèi, na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e paie-iie! Te kaca'a laa, Ja'a mai nuka sèmi dhèu mana'u, dhu dhèu èci sa re'a boe. Dhèu dhu oto, nuka rèngu dhu beke dènge dhu bori mema dhari. Te ladhe Ja'a mai, nèngu na'e boe makae, lula dhèu rèdhi boe era makae na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus Kristus also speaks/spoke saying, “Remember well! Cuz (elaboration) suddenly I will come like a thief which people do not expect. The person who stays awake watches/guards with all his/her clothes on (idiom) are most fortunate. Cuz (elaboration:grounds) when I come, s/he will not be embarrassed/ashamed, because people will not see his/her nakedness (euphemism).”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'aga dènge bori mema dhari ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">j'aga dènge bori mema dhari = jaga deng ikat memang tali (siap-siap) ; kore madha ra = sampe di dong pung muka</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 24:43-44, Lukas 12:39-40, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 3:3</note><note reference="16:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Dhèu Aae Sèra 23:29, Sakaria 12:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia ana pajuu ka pidhu la'e bhori isi bokor na asa madha ngèlu. Ka Ama Lamatua padhai lii mèdhu nèti kadera paredha Na ètu d'ara Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èle le! Nanasa Ja'a bhori aa'i mèu-mèu le!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then angel number seven poured out his bowl's contents on the wind. And God spoke with a loud voice from His ruling chair in the Worship House saying, “It's finished! My anger is all poured out now!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="phoonee megalee ek tou naou apo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">phoonee megalee ek tou naou apo tou thronou legousa: What is the relationship between the sanctuary and the throne?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia bela heo ha'a-ha'a, dènge d'oro lii gasi-gasi. Aa rai opo dhu kapai titu kèna, dhu j'aj'i nèdhi mèka karèi nèti rai-haha ne j'aj'i.<bt>Next there was lightning that struck out and thunder that rumbled on and on. And a massive earthquake, which has never yet happened before on earth, also happened. [EXEG: “since people were on the earth” undertranslated so as not to skew the information load.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii dou pasèu-pasèu = baganti-baganti ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">lii dou pasèu-pasèu = baganti-baganti ; gasi-gasi = baganti-baganti ; lola-lola = basambung</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 8:5, 11:13, 19</note><v n="19" />Lod'o èèna, Ama Lamatua bhèlu boe bhabhelu dhèu ètu kota Babel. Ka Na pake rai opo dhu kapai aae, sèna ka tao kota kapai ne masèke mi tèlu. Ama Lamatua ad'u-ue sèmi èèna, sèna ka dhèu Babel re'a nanasa Na. Kota-kota leo ètu rai-haha ne, laho eele aa'i si kahèi.<bt>At that time, God did not forget Babel city people's evil. He used that extra-ordinary earthquake so that that great city was split/cracked up in three. God did like that, so that the Babel people would know/experience His anger. Other cities in the world also were destroyed. [EXEG: second use of wine-cup = anger/destruction. Since the image is confusing, we've just kept the grounds for comparison here to avoid over-translation.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="masèke = split up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">masèke = split up</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: Second use of the wine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">TERM: Second use of the wine = wrath metaphor "God come real huhu an no take da bad kine stuff dose peopo stay doing. He goin make dose peopo suffa real bad from da burning sulfur, in front da spesho angel guys an God's Baby Sheep. Dass jalike wen one guy make anodda guy drink too much real strong wine, fo make um come real drunk."</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 51:17</note><v n="20" />Lod'o èèna pulu-pulu cène aa'i si, aa ledhe-ledhe ela aa'i kahèi.<bt>At that time the islands submerged, and the mountains also disappeared.</bt><note reference="16:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 6:14</note><v n="21" />Abhu kahèi èj'i es hadhu dhu kapai, bèbhe nèti dedha-liru, kabhie nare dhèu-dhèu ètu rai-haha. Es hadhu se, babia ra abhu kahèi d'ai èpa nguru kilo.<bt>There were also big rain ice rocks falling from the sky to mash/press down on/crush humans. Those rocks' heaviness, there were those that were up to forty kilos.</bt><note reference="16:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;babia na sama dènge <span class="Italic">talenta</span> èci&gt;&gt;. Babia <span class="Italic">talenta</span> èci, nuka tèlu nguru èpa d'ai èpa nguru kilogram.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes, saying, “as heavy as one <span class="Italic">talenta</span>”. The weight of one <span class="Italic">talenta</span> is 34-40 kilograms. [EXEG: see NLT note and LN. TH is all over the map.]</bt></note>Lula èj'i es ne dhu paj'èra dhèu, ka ra dhoo Ama Lamatua.<bt>Because of that ice rain which made them suffer, that's why humans cursed God.</bt><note reference="16:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 9:23, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 11:19</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana pajuu Ama Lamatua pasoro kota Babel dènge bhèni kajeo<bt>God's angel compares the city of Babel with a whore/ prostitute</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoro = 1) banding, 2) baring-baring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pasoro = 1) banding, 2) baring-baring (istirahat), 3) kasi miring (benda) ; pakasoro = membandingkan (more specific)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="17" />
      <v n="1" />Èle ka, ana pajuu èci nèti rèngu dhèu pidhu dhu rèd'u bokor dhu dènge heka isi, mai peka dènge ja'a, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai ku sa ne'e! Ja'a neo pad'elo dènge èu, j'ara tasamia Ama Lamatua huku bhèni kajeo dhu bhelu aae èèna. Nèngu ne, nuka kota kapai èèna, dhu ra patitu padètu dènge èi ae-ae.<bt>After that one of those seven angels who held those empty bowls, came to speak with me, saying, “Come here! I want to show you God's way of punishing that prostitute who is exceedingly evil. She is that big city which they have build near many/much water. [EXEG: while English translations vary between “whore (promiscuous woman, no pay)” and “prostitute (promiscuous, for pay)”, the Gk seems to lean toward the latter (LN, BADG).]</bt><note reference="17:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 51:13</note><v n="2" />Uru èèna, dhèu aae-dhèu aae nèti mia-mia, mai ad'u-ue j'ara makae dènge ana kabarai d'ara kota ne. Dhèu leo kahèi mai rinu mahu, aa madhutu tatao j'ara makae ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Previously kings from all over came frequently to do shameful things (sexually) with that city's people. Other people also came drinking to the point of drunkeness and follow/participate in doing their shameful things (sexually). [NOTE to daughter translations: (high-level) The book-level themes, the Gk, and the Hebrew it evokes (e.g. Amos), are playing at two levels 1) sexual immorality, and 2) unfaithfulness to God [which is the primary point here at a high level]. Some terms (like maen basundal) are too restrictive to the first reading, even though they resonate nicely with prostitution. Other terms (like maen serong) can carry both senses. Try to find a broader term to carry through the remaining chapters.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This is not the wine ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">This is not the wine = wrath metaphor. It is related, but does not symbolize wrath.</Message></Annotation><note reference="17:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 23:17, Yermia 51:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Èle èèna ka, Roh Ama Lamatua maso asa ja'a, hèia ana pajuu nèti sorga ded'e nèti ja'a asa d'ara mamoo èci. D'ai nèi, ja'a ladhe kèdhi dhèu bhèni ca dhèu dhu madhèdi ètu dedha kabodho badha bhelu mea ci'u. Kètu badha ne pidhu, dènge tadhu na canguru. Palème ètu ngi'u na dhu suri lii-lii dhu pakarehe Ama Lamatua.<bt>Then God's Spirit entered/came upon me, and (that) angel lifted brought me to an deserted/desolate place. There I saw a woman sitting on a reddish-brown ferocious/evil animal. That animals heads were seven, and it's horns, ten. All over its body were written words which are offensive to/blaspheme/slander God. [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK that your team and UNS's can identify who “I” is in first sentence. If they can't, then /beta, andia Yohanis yang ada tulis ni,/ “me, that is Yohanis who is writing this”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kai eidon: introducing a new vision."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">kai eidon: introducing a new vision. Nestle has the paragraph break in the middle of the verse.</Message></Annotation><note reference="17:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 13:1</note><v n="4" />Bhèni ne pake bèla manii mea dènge mea sanama mangèru. Na pagaa ngi'u na dènge nèu mèdha hualaa, hadhu kale'e dhu kab'ua, dènge mutiara. Ètu ai g'ana na, nèd'u dènge cangkir hualaa èci dhu pènu dènge èi anggor. Anggor ne, sasoa na, j'ara makae, aa bhabhelu dènge tatao kaj'alu aa'i-aa'i dhu leo, dhu na ad'u-ue.<bt>That woman was wearing fine cloths that were red colour and purple colour. Her jewelry was from gold, expensive jewels, and from pearls (loan). She was holding a gold glass which was full of wine in her right hand. That wine, its meaning was her doing embarrasing/shameful (sexual) things, and all the evil and dirty/defiling other things which she had done.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pagaa = berhias ; nèu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pagaa = berhias ; nèu = 1) pake, 2) bahan bangunan, kayu dll,</Message></Annotation><note reference="17:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 51:7</note><v n="5" />Ètu katangarèi na, dhu suri ngara èci, dhu dhèu re'a boe. Lii dhu ra suri èèna, sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>On her forehead was written a name, whose meaning was still not known. That writing said like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a ne, Babel!<bt>I am Babel!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a ne, kota dhu kapai risi!<bt>I am the greatest city!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rupa-rupa bhabhelu ètu rai-haha,<bt>All the kinds of evil in the world,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">j'aj'aj'i ra nèti ja'a ka.<bt>originate from me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">J'ara makae aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i ètu rai-haha ne,<bt>All who do embarrassing/shameful (sexual) things on the earth,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">kapua ra nèti ja'a.<bt>have their roots/source in me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ja'a laladhe, na, bhèni ne dhu mahu bia, lula nèngu dhu ninu le raa dhèu unu Ama Lamatua sèra. Sasoa na, na pamadhe le dhèu unu Ama Lamatua, lula rèngu loe boe peka j'ara mamuri Yesus.<bt>Then I saw that woman was heavily drunk, because she had drunk God's people's blood. Meaning, she murdered God's people, because they did not stop talking about Yesus' life. [EXEG: see THandbook for seeing martyrs as part of God's people. NRSV, NLT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa ja'a kèdhi tatao bhèni ne sèmi èèna, hèia hèb'a ja'a nganga-nganga sène, lula malaa bia.<bt>When I saw the deeds of that woman, I was open-mouthed (=dumb founded) and extremely amazed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia ana pajuu ne karèi ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka èu naa-naa, aa malaa sèmi èèna? Mai ho ja'a peka dènge èu sasoa na nèti bhèni kajeo ne. Sèmi èèna kahèi, dènge sasoa nèti badha bhelu dhu nèngu manya'e èèna. Badha ne'e ka dhu kètu pidhu dènge tadhu canguru.<bt>But that angel asked me saying, “Why are you open-mouthed stupidly (=speechless) like that? Come, so that I can tell the meaning of that evil woman. Like that also with the meaning of that ferocious animal that she rode. This is the animal with seven heads and ten horns.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naa-naa = tanganga (berdiri tanpa suara)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">naa-naa = tanganga (berdiri tanpa suara)</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Uru èèna, badha bhelu ne dhu mamuri le ètu rai-haha, te ngaa limuri ne aad'o heka. Te ngaa nèbhu heka, na kalua hari mai nèti ro'a j'aj'èra dhu dènge boe too-lane èèna. Lod'o èèna, abhu dhèu dhu mamuri ètu rai-haha, dhu ngara ra dhae suri mèka ètu d'ara Sasuri Ana Kalèbho, dhu Ama Lamatua suri tèke le karèi uru ka, nèti Na paj'aj'i rai-haha ne. Bèli-camèd'a, dhèu se'e se malaa-maloha, lula rèdhi badha bhelu ne lèpa hari mai. Te ngaa ladhe na mai hari, pe Ama Lamatua pèci ne asa d'ara dhasi ai èi nasu dhu heo na taa-taa.<bt>Previously that ferocious animal lived on the earth, but now he is no longer there/no longer exists. But not much longer (=soon), he comes again from that hole of suffering which does not have a foundation/limit. At that time, there will be people who live in the world, whose names are not written in the Sheep Offspring's Writing, which God has written ahead of time from before He made/created this world. Later those people will be open-mouthed (doublet) seeing that ferocious animal, because they see he has returned. But if/when he has come, God will cast him out into the sea of fiery sulphur where the flames never stop. [DISCOURSE: don't put quote margin in here as it implies “change of speaker” in these languages.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: Book of Life"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">TERM: Book of Life</Message></Annotation><note reference="17:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:7, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 11:7, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:29</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Dhèu cee dhu d'èlu-mèu, na, nèngu bisa ne'a sasoa j'ara se'e. Badha bhelu dhu kètu pidhu, sasoa na, nuka ledhe pidhu bua. Bhèni kajeo èèna, dhu madhèdi ètu dedha ledhe sèra. Aa sasoa nèti kètu pidhu sèra, nuka dhèu aae dhèu pidhu.<bt>The person/whoever is truly smart/clever/wise can understand this matter. The meaning of that wild animal's seven heads, is seven mountains. That prostitute, is sitting on those mountains. And the meaning of those seven heads, is seven kings. [EXEG: Mounce notes “This calls for a mind with wisdom” may be a warning to interpret with care, or an aside to the effect that what follows “is the clue for those who can interpret it” (NEB).] [NOTE: versification of TB is off from the Gk here, putting last sentence of vs.9 in vs.10. So Advisors be careful lest your teams “correct” this to match the TB.]</bt><v n="10" />Lèmi nèti dhèu aae pidhu se, madhe le. Ca dhèu dhu nèd'u paredha limuri ne. Aa ca dhèu hari dhae mai mèka. Te ngaa ladhe mai, nèngu nèd'u paredha nèbhu boe.<bt>From those seven kings, five are dead. One is ruling now. The other one has not yet come. But when he comes, he will only rule for a little while.</bt><v n="11" />Ne'e ne ja'a lole dènge èu, nèti badha bhelu dhu uru èèna mamuri, te ngaa limuri ne madhe le. Lod'o èèna, nèngu ne ca dhèu nèti pidhu dhèu aae sèra, te ngaa èèna na mai hari nèd'u paredha, ho j'aj'i dhèu aae ka aru. Pe na laho mae-mae kahèi.<bt>Now I will tell about that aforementioned ferocious animal who previously alive, but now is dead. Previously he also was one of that seven kings, but later he will return to rule to become king number eight. Later he will be destroyed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Pe na abhu huku, ho j'aj'èra"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Pe na abhu huku, ho j'aj'èra na dhu loe boe ciki sa.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Canguru tadhu se, sasoa na, nuka canguru dhèu aae. Rèngu se dhae rèd'u mèka paredha. Bèli-camèd'a rèngu abhu koasa, ho rèd'u paredha sama-sama dènge badha bhelu ne, te ngaa dhoka ciki-diki di.<bt>The meaning of those ten horns, is ten kings. They have not yet ruled. Later they will receive authority to rule together with that ferocious animal, but only for a little while. [EXEG: NLT, CEV, LN]</bt><note reference="17:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani ètu ne'e, bisa abhu dua sasoa. Èci: dhoka ciki-diki di; dua: ca jam di.<bt>The Yunani language Bible here can have two meanings. That is: 1) just for a moment; or, 2) one hour.</bt></note><note reference="17:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:24</note><v n="13" />Te rare lii èci, ho pangèd'u koasa ra mi badha bhelu èèna.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) they all agreed to hand over their authority to that aforementioned ferocious animal.</bt><v n="14" />Dhèu aae sèra, bèli-camèd'a lasi pamusu, lab'a Ana Kalèbho. Te ngaa Ana Kalèbho dènge dhèu unu Na segi aa'i si. Dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu Ana Kalèbho ne, nuka rèngu dhu Na hag'e nare le, aa Na paroa si ho madhutu Ne taa-taa. Pe rèngu segi, lula Ana Kalèbho ne èra titu kèna. Dhodhoka Nèngu di dhu j'aj'i Dhèu Aae nèti dhèu aae aa'i-aa'i ra, aa Lamatua nèti lamatua aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Those kings later will go war again that Sheep Offspring. But that Sheep Offspring and His people will defeat them all. People who follow/obey that aforementioned Sheep Offspring, they are the people whom He chose and called to follow Him continually/forever. Later they will win, because that Sheep Offspring is very powerful/amazing/influential. Only just Him is King over all kings, and the Lord/Master over all lords/masters.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Aa èi ae-ae dhu padètu dènge bhèni kajeo ne, nuka dhèu-dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i, nèti udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i, aa dènge dhèu ae-ae nèti lii aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha.<bt>And that much/many water that is near that aforementioned prostitute, that is people from every tribe, every clan, and many-many people from every language on earth. [EXEG: Gk “multitudes/crowds” here (slightly different from other lists in REV).]</bt><v n="16" />Canguru dhèu aae dènge badha bhelu se, èèna na ra tèka d'ara dènge bhèni kajeo dhu ne'a boe makae ne. Èèna na parame rare mèdha-papake dènge mèdha-panyau na aa'i-aa'i, ka tèke eele ne dènge boe mèdha-papake ètu ua na. Èle èèna ka, ra'e sisi bhèni ne kahèi. Aa ngi'u na dhu ate, core asa d'ara ai.<bt>Those ten kings and that ferocious animal later will begin to hate that prostitute who doesn't know shame. Later they will loot her clothes and all her belongings, then leave her stark naked there. Then they will also eat her flesh. And the remains of her body, they will throw away in the fire.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sonde tahu malu ; ma'aa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">sonde tahu malu ; ma'aa = tebal</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu tao, toke canguru dhèu aae se rare lii èci, ho pangèd'u koasa ra mi badha bhelu ne, toke na palaho bhèni ne. Dènge j'ara ne'e, ngaa dhu Ama Lamatua neo ad'u-ue, bèli-camèd'a aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i.<bt>God himself is the one who has made it so that those ten kings are all in agreement, to hand over their power/authority to that ferocious animal, to the point that he will destroy that woman. In that way, God's plans will all happen.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Bhèni kajeo dhu èu mèdhi èèna, nuka dhèu aae-dhèu kapai nèti kota kapai dhu paredha dhèu aae aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha.&gt;&gt;<bt>That prostitute whom you see, is the leaders/prominent people (doublet) great city which rules all the kings on earth.” [DISCOURSE: don't add quote margin here.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana pajuu Ama Lamatua lole gaguri kota Babel<bt>An angel stories about Babel city's destruction</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="18" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ja'a ladhe kèdhi ana pajuu dhu leo ca dhèu, mai nèti sorga. Nèngu ne dhu dènge koasa aa saraa dhu kapai, ho pasaraa palème rai-haha.<bt>Then I saw another angel come (down) from heaven. He had power/authority and brightness that was great/amazing to the point that it gave light to all the earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Meta tauta eidon allon ...: like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Meta tauta eidon allon ...: like the parallel passages</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Dènge lii aae, na peka,<bt>He use a loud voice to tell, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Laho le! Laho le! Kota Babel laho mae-mae le!<bt>“It's destroyed! It's destroyed! Babel city is destroyed!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Guri le! Guri le! Kota kapai ne, guri dolu-dolu le!<bt>It's fallen! It's fallen! That great city, has fallen away!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dolu-dolu = roll away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">dolu-dolu = roll away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu j'aj'i le era pea nidhu.<bt>It has become evil spirits' {nidhu} living place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu j'aj'i le rai èta-èsu roh bhelu-katub'a aa'i-aa'i.<bt>It has become every evil spirits' {roh bhelu-katub'a} native land.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu j'aj'i le era pakaboko nèti manu-bhui aa'i-aa'i dhu ra'a sisi hèu.<bt>It has become every bird (scavenger) gathering place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu j'aj'i le oka nèti badha aa'i-aa'i dhu dhèu madenge.<bt>It has become the animal pen for all the yucky/gross animals (to be avoided).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 14:8. TEXT: [kai phylakee pantos"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 14:8. TEXT: [kai phylakee pantos pneumatos akathartou] [kai phylakee pantos orneou akathartou] [kai phylakee pantos theeriou akathartou] kai memiseemenou: weak attestation for the whole list, strongest for "beast" alone, next for "bird", weakest for "spirit" alone. Recommended "Now inside dea ony get pilau kine wild animals, da kine dat everybody hate." But best to go along with the more popular English editions. NIV has "spirit" and "bird".<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="18:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 21:9, Yermia 51:8, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 14:8, Yesaya 13:21, Yermia 50:39</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Nèngu guri le, lula suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne,<bt>She has fallen, because all tribes on earth</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">loe boe mai rinu mahu èi anggor na.<bt>habitually come drink to point of getting drunk from her wine.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu laho le, lula udhu-rasa aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne,<bt>She has fallen, because all clans in the world</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">loe boe mai ad'u-ue j'ara makae dènge ana kabarai kota ne.<bt>habitually come to do shameful things (sexual) with that city's inhabitants. [NOTE: metonymy explicated.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu aae-dhèu aae nèti negara aa'i-aa'i,<bt>Kings from all countries have come</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">mai j'unu pa'èci ètu èèna.<bt>have come to sleep together (sexual) there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu d'aga nèti kota aa'i-aa'i,<bt>Merchants from all the cities</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">mai pahia toke rèngu j'aj'i kaja.<bt>come sell to the point that they become rich.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Lula kota ne nuka sèmi dhèu bhèni dhu d'èi hèli mèdha dhu kab'ua aae.<bt>Because that city is like a woman who likes to buy every luxurious/expensive thing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Lula kota ne sama sèmi bhèni kajeo dhu d'èi dhoka tenge ngaa-ngaa dhu hua iia di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because that city is like a prostitute who likes to look for/find everything that is pleasing (to the senses/self).” [NOTE: “wine” in Gk here not wrath.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Wine of her adulteries -- again,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Wine of her adulteries -- again, not wrath: Rev. 14:8-10, 17:2. ek tees dynameoos: the wealth<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="18:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 23:17, Yermia 51:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi hari lii leo èci, paroa nèti dedha-liru, peka na,<bt>Then I heard again another voice call from the sky, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Wee! Dhèu Ja'a aa'i-aa'i!<bt>“Hoi! [+get attention] All of My people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rai eele ka era èèna!<bt>Run away from there!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Tèke eele ka kota èèna!<bt>Leave that city!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Baku tao madhutu bhabhelu ana kabarai kota ne,<bt>Don't follow/participate in the evil of the inhabitants of that city,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka baku lèke hahuku ra kahèi.<bt>so that [you] are not also afflicted with their punishment.</bt><note reference="18:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 48:20, Yermia 50:8, 51:6, 45</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Lula bhabhelu ra,<bt>Because their evil is</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ae seli eele.<bt>way too much.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa sasala ra,<bt>And their sins</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tanga-tanga d'ai dedha-liru.<bt>are layered up to the sky.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tanga-tanga = lapis-lapis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">tanga-tanga = lapis-lapis</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Limuri ne Ama Lamatua bhèlu heka,<bt>Now God has not forgotten anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">j'ara mamuri ra dhu bhelu-katub'a èèna.<bt>that way of life of theirs that is evil (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Limuri ne Ama Lamatua dhu pa'èra le,<bt>Now God is ready</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho neo huku si.<bt>to punish them.</bt><note reference="18:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 18:20-21, Yermia 51:9</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />De miu hud'i b'ala ku bhabhelu ra,<bt>So (consequently), you-pl must reciprocate/ avenge/pay back (for) their evil,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sama sèmi rèngu tao le bhabhelu mi dhèu leo.<bt>in the same way they did evil to other people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa miu hud'i b'ala si,<bt>But you must repay/reciprocate to them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">toke d'ai babia na dua-dua hari.<bt>to the point of two burdens/weight (=twice the amount).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Uru èèna, rèngu tipu le dhèu,<bt>Previously they deceived people,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ag'o = tipu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ag'o = tipu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho rinu nèti d'ara cangkir hualaa ra, dhu pènu dènge èi anggor j'aj'èra.<bt>to drink from their gold cup that was full of suffering wine (=wine that brings suffering).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa limuri ne rèngu mesa ra hud'i rinu ku<bt>But now it is they themselves who must drink</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">anggor j'aj'èra èèna, toke dua-dua hari.<bt>that suffering wine, until two fold.</bt><note reference="18:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 137:8, Yermia 50:29</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Rèngu se tao ngi'u ra kapai.<bt>They have made themselves out to be great.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa ra padedha-dedha ngi'u unu ra.<bt>And have lifted high (=self-praise/glorification) themselves.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rèngu d'èi dhoka mamuri karej'e-karae di.<bt>They want only to live luxuriously/happily (image associated with filthy rich who have no cares).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rèngu d'èi dhoka dhu be'a-be'a di.<bt>They like only what is (self-) pleasing/good.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèti èèna ka, rèngu hud'i abhu ku sasusa dhu bia.<bt>Because of that, they must get/experience heavy/severe difficulty.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De rèngu hud'i mamuri j'èra bia ku.<bt>So (consequently), they must live in suffering/strife.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te uru èèna, ra padhai lii padedha iisi sama sèmi bhèni kajeo, peka na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) previously they spoke arrogantly like a prostitute, saying</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Ja'a ne, ina bhèni aae!<bt>‘I am the queen!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a ne, èèna na j'aj'i boe bhèni balu!<bt>I am not going to be a widow!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a èèna na roma iisi boe.<bt>I am not going to cry wailing/mourning.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a èèna na silu boe mèdha balu dhèu madhe.&gt;<bt>I am not going to wear widow mourning clothes.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Ra padhai lii sèmi èèna, toke Ama Lamatua nasa le dènge ra.<bt>They spoke like that to the point that God is angry with them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ka Ama Lamatua neo huku si.<bt>And/so God wants to punish them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èèna na, d'ara ca lod'o di,<bt>Later in just one day</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">rèngu manganga titu kèna,<bt>they will feel extreme hungry,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">rèngu tangi roma iisi,<bt>they will wail in grief,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa ra madhe aapa.<bt>and they will also die a cursed death.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Toke dhèu core eele si asa d'ara ai.<bt>To the point that people pick up and throw them into the fire.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Toke ai na'e pakèpu ngi'u aae si.<bt>To the point that the fire completely burns up their corpses.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te Lamatua dhu koasa kapai risi, ka dhu papuru huku ne.<bt>God who is the most powerful, is the one who hands down this punishment.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa Lamatua dhu èra risi eele, dhu pama'ète lii langu ne.<bt>And God who is the most awesome, is the one who decided this case.</bt><note reference="18:7-8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 47:7-9</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />Dhèu aae-dhèu aae uru sa,<bt>Kings who previously</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">mai j'unu pa'èci dènge ana kabarai kota ne,<bt>came sleeping together (sexually) with the inhabitants of that city,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa mamuri karej'e-karae ètu èèna.<bt>and lived luxuriously there,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe ladhe rèdhi sèb'u dhu ca'e nèti d'ara ai,<bt>later they will see smoke that arises from the fire,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">pe re'a, na, kota ne dhu ai na'e aa'i le.<bt>later they will know that city is burned up.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ka ra tangi ne dènge d'ara pèd'a.<bt>Then they will weep bitterly for her.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Ka ra mangingi, ladhe j'aj'èra dhèu sèra.<bt>And they will feel horrified seeing that suffering of those people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa ra bani dhoka titu ètu kaj'èu di.<bt>But they only dare to stand far off.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa rèngu bani dhoka laladhe nèti nèi di.<bt>And they can only watch from over there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Hèia ra padhai lii, peka na,<bt>Then they speak, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Ira ii! Kasian èu Babel!<bt>‘Oh dear! Pity on Babel!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ira ii! Kasian kota kapai!<bt>Oh dear! Pity that great city!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te dhoka d'ara ca jam di, èu abhu huku le.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) in only just one hour, you have been punished.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te dhoka d'ara ciki oo'e di, èu laho le.&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) in just a short time, but you have been destroyed.’</bt><note reference="18:9-10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 26:16-17</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Tadèngi sèmi èèna, dhèu-dhèu dhu uru sèra, mai nèti mia-mia ho d'aga ètu èèna,<bt>Hearing that, people who previously came from all places to trade there,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">rèngu tangi roma iisi kahèi.<bt>they also cry wailing (in grief).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te abhu boe ca dhèu sa,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) there is not a single person</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu neo lasi hèli mèdha d'aga ra.<bt>who wants to buy their merchandise anymore.</bt><note reference="18:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 27:31, 36</note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="12" />Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to go buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">mèdha ra dhu tao nèti hualaa, doi pudhi,<bt>their jewelry/things from gold, silver,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">hadhu kale'e, do mutiara.<bt>jewels, or pearl.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to go buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">bèla lenan, do bèla sutra rèngu,<bt>their linen cloth, silk cloth,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">do bèla alus dhu leo, dhu mea oe sèmi mangèru sa.<bt>or other refined/expensive cloths that are red or purple.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to go buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">mèdha ra dhu tao nèti aj'u hèu mèngi, aa mèdha dhu d'ule nèti èli gajah,<bt>their things from fragrant wood, carved elephant tusk,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èli = taring ; d'ule ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">èli = taring ; d'ule = ukir</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">do aj'u dhu d'ule dhu leo sèra.<bt>or other carved woods.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to go buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">mèdha ra dhu tao nèti tabaga, bèsi, do hadhu marmar.<bt>their things from copper/bronze, iron or marble stone.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="13" />Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to go buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">kayu manis, do bubhu lara dhu leo sèra.<bt>their cinnamon or all sorts of spices.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">raa aj'u hèu mèngi ra, do èi hèu mèngi dhu leo sèra.<bt>their aromatic resin or different kinds of perfume/oil.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to go buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">èi anggor ra, èi mènyi saitun ra,<bt>their grape wine, their olive oil,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">tarigu, do are-gandum ra.<bt>wheat flour, or wheat padi.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to go buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sapi ra, kahib'i-kalèbho ra, do jara ra.<bt>their cows, sheep, or horses.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abhu heka dhu neo lasi hèli<bt>There is no one who wants to go buy anymore</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">kareta mèdha ra,<bt>their carts/carriages/chariots, [EXEG: most English versions and AGNT say “chariot” here, but LN says a different Gk word means chariot. They say the Gk word here is “a four-wheeled carriage or wagon used for travel or the transportation of loads”; BADG say “carriage” and do not give “chariot” as a gloss. Here it is used in a list of goods bought and sold by merchants. Safer just to say /kareta/ than either /kareta barang/ or /kareta paráng/.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">do ènu ra sèra.<bt>or their slaves. [EXEG: Mounce considers “the bodies and souls of men” to be a Hebrew biased idiom meaning “slave trafficking”. Additional support and discussion in TH.]</bt><note reference="18:12-13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 27:12, 13, 22</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />Èèna na dhèu d'aga sèra manyasa, ka ra peka na,<bt>Later those merchants will feel regret, and will say,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Ira ii, Babel, ee!<bt>‘Oh dear, Babel, ee!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ira ii, kota kapai, ee!<bt>Oh dear, great city, ee!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Mèdha-panyau èu dhu hua iia sèra, dhu kabarai èu d'èi risi,<bt>Those luxury goods of yours which your people/inhabitants like so much,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aad'o heka èci sa.<bt>are all gone.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa'i-aa'i ra ela aa'i mèu-mèu, toke kabarai èu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa,<bt>Everything has disappeared, to the point that your inhabitants are desolately poor</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">toke rod'o kakara d'ai rai.&gt;<bt>to the point that [you] drag on the ground.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />Uru èèna, dhèu d'aga se j'aj'i kaja, lula kota ne dhu nuka sèmi bhèni kajeo.<bt>Previously, those merchants became rich because of that city that is like a prostitute.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa limuri ne, ra loe boe manyasa.<bt>But now they are endlessly regretful.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Rèngu j'aj'i madha'u titu kèna,<bt>They have become very afraid,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">laladhe j'aj'èra ana kabarai kota ne.<bt>seeing that suffering of the people of that city.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rèngu j'aj'i mangingi titu kèna,<bt>They have become very horrified,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">laladhe hahuku ra.<bt>seeing that punishment of theirs.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa rèngu dhoka bani laladhe nèti kaj'èu di.<bt>But they only dare to look from afar.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rèngu bani dhoka titu nèti era nèi di.<bt>They only can bear to watch from over there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />Hèia ra padhai lii, peka na,<bt>Then they spoke, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Ira ii! Kasian èu Babel, ee!<bt>‘Oh dear! Pity you Babel, ee!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Ira ii! Kasian kota kapai, ee!<bt>Oh dear! Pity the great city, ee!</bt><note reference="18:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 27:31, 36</note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Uru èèna, ana kabarai èu pake mèdha bèla alus, dhu mea oe sèmi mangèru sa,<bt>Previously your people wore fine clothes that was red or purple,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">nèti bèla dhu kab'ua titu kèna.<bt>from cloth that was extremely expensive.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Uru èèna, ana kabarai èu d'èi panèu mèdha hualaa, mutiara,<bt>Previously your people decorated themselves with gold, pearls,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dènge hadhu kale'e dhu kab'ua titu kèna.<bt>and precious/flashy stones that were extremely expensive.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="17" />Te ngaa d'ara ca jam di,<bt>But in just one hour,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">mèdha-panyau èu sèra èla aa'i mèu-mèu si.<bt>your things are all gone.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhodhoka d'ara ciki oo'e èèna di,<bt>In just a short time,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">kakaja èu saku hani-hani!&gt;<bt>your riches have disappeared!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Uru èèna juraga kapa, dènge mataroo sèra,<bt>Previously there were also ships captains and ship crews</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">kako lasi-mai nèti kota èèna.<bt>sailing to and from that city.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa limuri ne, rèngu bani dhodhoka panahu nèti kaj'èu di.<bt>But now they only dare be at anchor from afar.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa limuri ne rèngu bani dhoka laladhe nèti nèi di.<bt>And now they only dare watch from over there.</bt><note reference="18:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 23:14, Yeskial 27:26-30</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="18" />Rèngu ladhe sèb'u kalua nèti d'ara ai èèna.<bt>They watch the smoke that come out of that fire.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ka re'a, na, ai na'e aa'i le.<bt>Then they know that she is burnt up consumed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Hèia ra manyasa, ka peka na,<bt>Then they express regret, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Ira ii, kasian! Abhu heka kota leo<bt>‘How pitiful! There will not be another city</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu kapai sèmi kota Babel ne.<bt>that is as great as Babel again.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aduu, kasian! Abhu heka kota dhu leo,<bt>How pitiful! There will not be another city</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu babe'a na sama sèmi nèngu ne.&gt;<bt>that is as fine/good as her again.’</bt><note reference="18:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 27:32</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19" />Rèngu soke ahu ho ceb'e mi kètu ra,<bt>They scoop up ashes to put on their heads</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soke = so'e (scoop) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">soke = so'e (scoop) ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula d'ara ra susa.<bt>because their insides are in distress (=grief).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rèngu tangi d'ara pèd'a,<bt>They cry bitterly,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula d'ara ra laho mae-mae.<bt>because their insides are destroyed/crushed (=broken hearted).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ka ra peka na,<bt>Then they speak,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Ira ii! Kasian èu Babel, ee!<bt>‘Oh dear! Pity you Babel, ee!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Ira ii! Kasian kota kapai!<bt>Oh dear! Pity the great city!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ji'i dènge kapa la'a-mai ngèti mèdha hia kabarai èu,<bt>We-exc have sailed to and fro bringing goods to your inhabitants,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">toke ji'i d'ai kaja-su'i kahèi.<bt>until we also have become rich (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ji'i hua ngèti le mèdha kabarai èu,<bt>We have carried your inhabitants' cargo,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">toke ji'i mamuri hua iia kahèi.<bt>until we also have lived luxuriously.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa dhoka d'ara ca jam di,<bt>But in only just one hour,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa'i-aa'i se saku hani-hani.<bt>all of that has been wiped away (disappeared).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hapus sapurata"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">hapus sapurata</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa dhoka ètu d'ara ciki oo'e di,<bt>In only just a short time,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">laho aa'i si mèu-mèu.&gt;<bt>all of that has been destroyed.’</bt><note reference="18:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 27:30-34</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi lii aae èci peka tabha hari, sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>Then, that voice added, saying, [DISCOURSE: quote margin because of major shift in addressee.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;He, miu dhu mamuri ètu sorga!<bt>‘Hey, all of you who live in heaven!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">miu parluu heka d'ara pèd'a.<bt>You do not need to have bitter insides (= 1) angry; 2) disappointed) anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">He, miu dhu j'aj'i le dhèu unu Lamatua!<bt>Hey, the Lord's people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">D'ara miu parluu heka susa.<bt>Your insides do not need to feel distress anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Miu dhu j'aj'i le dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua,<bt>You-pl who are the Lord's commissioned ones,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hud'i laa d'ara miu karae.<bt>Let your insides be joyful.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Miu dhu j'aj'i le dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua,<bt>You-pl who are the Lord's spokespersons!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hud'i laa d'ara miu maho'o.<bt>Let your insides be refreshed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Uru èèna, Babel pasusa le miu.<bt>Previously, Babel caused you trouble.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Uru èèna, kabarai kota ne paj'èra miu.<bt>Previously, the inhabitants of that city tortured you/caused you suffering/distress.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa limuri ne Lamatua pama'ète le lii langu miu dènge mola.<bt>But now, God has decided your case fairly.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te limuri ne Na b'ala le bhabhelu-katub'a kabarai kota èèna.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) now, He has reciprocated/revenged that city's inhabitants' evil (doublet).’”</bt><note reference="18:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 32:43, Yermia 51:48</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka ja'a ladhe kèdhi ana pajuu èci nèti sorga dhu èra titu kèna. Na mai ded'e nare hadhu aae cue, dhu kapai na sange dhèu èci. Hèia na pèci hadhu ne asa d'ara dhasi. Ka na peka,<bt>After that, I saw an angel who was very strong. He came and picked up a stone as big as a person. Then he threw that stone into the sea. He then said,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Pe ra palaho eele Babel sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>“Later they will completely destroy Babel like that.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pe ra pa'ele kota kapai èèna, sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>Later they will make that Great City completely disappear just like that.</bt><note reference="18:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 51:63-64, Yeskial 26:21</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="22" />Abhu heka ca dhèu sa,<bt>There is no longer anyone</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu karihu musiik ètu d'ara kota èèna.<bt>who plays music in that city.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abhu heka dhèu,<bt>There is no longer anyone</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu tadèngi lii gai sasadhu, tiu sakino,<bt>who hears the sound of sasando, flutes,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa lii tiu tèbhe ètu d'ara kota èèna.<bt>and trumpets in that city anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abhu heka tuka èci sa,<bt>There is no longer any craftsmen,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu sab'a ètu d'ara sab'a-la'a ra.<bt>who works in their trade/field of expertise anymore. [NOTE: TB is way off here, talking about performers in the fine arts. CEV is misleading talking about “setting up shop”, but meaning “workshop” rather than “store” as some of us misread it for earlier versions.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhu bhoke toko ètu dara kota"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">dhu bhoke toko ètu dara kota èèna.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abhu heka dhèu,<bt>There is no longer anyone</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu gili are ètu kota èèna.<bt>who mills padi in that city anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gili = mol"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">gili = mol</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 26:13, Yesaya 24:8</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="23" />Abhu heka dhèu,<bt>There is no longer anyone</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu paheo labhu ètu d'ara kota èèna.<bt>who burns lamps in that city anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abhu heka dhèu,<bt>There is no longer anyone</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu tao pesta kab'i ètu èèna.<bt>who makes wedding feasts there anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Uru èèna, ètu kota ne, dhèu pahia-pahèli mèdha ra,<bt>Previously, that city's buyers of merchandise</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">toke j'aj'i kaja-su'i.<bt>had become excessively rich.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Uru èèna, dhèu d'aga ètu Babel,<bt>Previously, Babel's merchants</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">mamuri hua iia.<bt>had lived in excessive luxury.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa rèngu pake na'i nidhu,<bt>But they used black magic</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho leko-monya dhèu ètu rai-haha.<bt>to deceive people on earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uku-kedi = siksa, hukum, (hex from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">uku-kedi = siksa, hukum, (hex from sihir)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rèngu pake seher,<bt>They used sorcery,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho kapod'e-kabèli dhèu ètu rai-haha.<bt>to con humans in the world.</bt><note reference="18:22-23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 7:34, 25:10</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="24" />Babel abhu le huku dhu bia,<bt>Babel has received this heavy/severe punishment,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula kabarai na loe boe pamadhe dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua.<bt>because her inhabitants habitually murdered God's spokespeople.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Kota kapai ne laho le,<bt>That great city is destroyed,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula kabarai na paj'èra toke madhe dhèu unu Lamatua.<bt>because her inhabitants habitually tortured the Lord's people to death.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abhu kahèi dhèu-dhèu Lamatua dhu ra pamadhe ètu era-era leo.<bt>There are also the Lord's people who were murdered in other places.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa Babel ka dhu hud'i dui nare sasala sèra.<bt>But it is Babel who must carry all those wrongs.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Kota kapai èèna ka dhu hud'i tago nare aa'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>It is that great city who must bear the responsibility.”</bt><note reference="18:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 51:49</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu ae-ae sod'a ètu sorga<bt>Many people sing in heaven</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="19" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa ana pajuu ne padhai lii nare, ka ja'a tadèngi lii dhèu ae-ae sod'a ètu sorga. Ra sod'a, peka na,<bt>When the angel finished speaking like that, then I heard a big noise like there was a many-many people singing in heaven. They sang, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Haleluya! Haleluya!<bt>“Haleluya! Haleluya!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èdhi koa-kio Ama Lamatua èdhi,<bt>We-inc praise our God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula Nèngu ka dhu dedha risi eele.<bt>because He is the highest/greatest.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Haleluya! Haleluya!<bt>Haleluya! Haleluya!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èdhi koa-kio Ama Lamatua èdhi,<bt>We praise (doublet) our God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Nèngu ka dhu koasa kapai risi.<bt>because He is the most powerful/greatest authority.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu patabuli èdhi,<bt>God is the one who has saved/rescued/delivered us</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi.<bt>from our sins (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua ka dhu pamèci èdhi,<bt>The Lord is the one who straighten out things for us</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nèti sasala-sasala èdhi.<bt>that results from our wrongs (reduplication =variety).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Èdhi koa-kio Ama Lamatua,<bt>We praise God</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Nèngu ka dhu pama'ète lii langu dènge mola.<bt>because He is the one who decides cases truly/correctly/fairly/rightly.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èdhi koa-kio Ama Lamatua,<bt>We praise God</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Nèngu ka dhu hia hahuku dhu lèke.<bt>because He is the one who hands down fair/just punishment.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua dhu huku le bhèni kajeo èèna,<bt>The Lord has handed down punishment to that prostitute,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula nèngu ka dhu dadugu dhèu ètu rai-haha,<bt>because she habitually enticed people in the world,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka madhutu tao j'ara makae sama-sama dènge ne,<bt>to go along with/participate in doing shameful things (sexually) with her,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa madhutu bhabhelu na.<bt>and follow her evil.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lamatua b'ala le bhèni aapa èèna,<bt>The Lord has repaid/reciprocated that evil woman,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula nèngu loe boe pamadhe<bt>because she habitually murdered</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ana pua-paleha Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>the Lord's servants.”</bt><note reference="19:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 32:43, 2 Dhèu Aae sèra 9:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Èle èèna ka, ra sod'a lii sod'a leo hari ètu sorga, peka na,<bt>After that, they sang yet another song in heaven saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Haleluya! Koa-kio Lamatua!<bt>“Haleluya! Praise the Lord!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Haleluya! J'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Na!<bt>Haleluya! Lift His name up high!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula sèb'u ai dhu tunu pakèpu ngi'u aae bhèni èèna,<bt>Because smoke from the fire which burns that woman's corpse,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ca'e taruu dhu loe boe ciki sa.<bt>arises continually without ever stopping.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa sèb'u nèti ai dhu tunu eele kota kapai èèna,<bt>And smoke from the fire which burns that aforementioned great city,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ca'e taruu dhu loe boe ciki sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>arises continually without ever ending.”</bt><note reference="19:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 34:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia dua nguru èpa katua, dènge badha aae èpa ngi'u sèra, patitu kètu urutuu, ho pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua dhu madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha Na. Ra pakab'ua Ne, peka na,<bt>After that, those 24 elders and those four extra-ordinary animals, fell kneeling to worship God's who sat on His ruling chair. They gave honour to Him, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Tare'a sèmi èèna! Mai ti koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua!<bt>“True! Let's praise the name/reputation of Father God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Haleluya! Mai ti j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Haleluya! Let's lift his name up high!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Pesta kab'i Ana Kalèbho<bt>The Sheep Offspring's wedding feast</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi hari lii èci dhu mai nèti kadera paredha èèna, peka na,<bt>Then I heard another voice come from that ruling chair, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;He, miu aa'i-aa'i mi dhu j'aj'i le ana pua-paleha Ama Lamatua!<bt>“Hey, God's servants!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">He, miu aa'i-aa'i mi dhu j'aj'i le ana-ana Ama Lamatua!<bt>Hey, God's people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Mai sèna ka ti j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>Let us (inc) lift God's name up high.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mai aa'i-aa'i, ana iiki-dhèu kapai, koa-kio Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Let us all small-big praise (doublet) the Lord.”</bt><note reference="19:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 115:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi oe sèmi dhèu ae-ae dhu padhai lii. Lii ra mèdhu nuka sèmi lii èi dhu hae nèti kolo ledhe, aa dou sèmi lii d'oro, ra peka na,<bt>Then I heard as if there were many people speaking to each other. That loud voice of theirs, sounded big like a waterfall, and loud like rumbling thunder. They spoke saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Haleluya! Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua.<bt>“Haleluya! We praise (doublet) God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Haleluya! Ji'i j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Na.<bt>Haleluya! We lift His name up high.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lula Nèngu ka dhu koasa kapai risi.<bt>Because He is the one who has the most authority/power.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Nèngu ka dhu paredha aa'i-aa'i.<bt>And He is the one who rules everything.</bt><note reference="19:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 1:24, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 93:1, 97:1, 99:1</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Limuri ne, d'ara èdhi karej'e le.<bt>Now our insides are happy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Limuri ne, d'ara èdhi kea rae-rae.<bt>Now are insides are joyful (idiom).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kea rae-rae = senang dgn hati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">kea rae-rae = senang dgn hati luas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èdhi koa-kio Ne.<bt>We (inc) praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula d'ai le lod'o kab'i Ana Kalèbho kèna.<bt>because the Sheep Offspring's wedding day has arrived.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èdhi j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Na,<bt>We lift His name up high,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula bhèni dhu neo j'aj'i dhèu èmu Ana Kalèbho, dhu pa'èra le.<bt>because the Sheep Offspring's bride is ready.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Ama Lamatua hia ne kodho kab'i na nèti bèla alus.<bt>God has given her bride clothes made from fine cloth.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ama Lamatua pangèd'u na mèdha-papake dhu pudhi kale'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>God has given clothes that are shiny white.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">(Mèdha-papake dhu pudhi kale'e èèna, sasoa na, tatao dhu be'a nèti dhèu unu Ama Lamatua.)<bt>(Those shiny white clothes, their meaning is God's people's good deeds.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka ana pajuu nèti sorga èèna, peka dènge ja'a, na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis! Èu hud'i suri more ku, sèmi ne'e:<bt>Then that angel told me, saying, “Yohanis! You must write like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu abhu nèru ho mai asa pesta kab'i Ana Kalèbho ne, rèngu oto tare'a-re'a!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>‘All people who receive an invitation to come to that Sheep Offspring wedding feast, they will be truly fortunate!’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia na peka hari dènge ja'a, &lt;&lt;Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua ne, lèke tare'a-re'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that angel continued his speaking again saying, “This/These Words of God, is/are indeed true!”</bt><note reference="19:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 22:2-3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka ja'a patitu kètu urutuu ho neo pahaha iisi mi ana pajuu ne. Te ngaa na kai, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu baku tao sèmi ne'e! Te ja'a ne ènu Ama Lamatua, èci èèna dènge èu ne, aa sama sèmi a'ari èu dhu lasi peka-padhai lii aj'a-nori Yesus. Te dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua peka-padhai lula-nèti Yesus kahèi, sèna ka dhèu pahaha iisi mi Nèngu. Te naneo Roh Ama Lamatua sèmi èèna. De baku pahaha iisi mi ja'a ne. Te ngaa pahaha iisi dhoka mi Ama Lamatua di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I fell kneeling in.order.to worship that angel. But he scolded me saying, “You shouldn't worship me like that! Cuz (elaboration) I am also God's servant/slave like you, and your siblings who tell people about Yesus. Cuz (elaboration) teaching of Yesus', is the same as that teaching which previously God gave to His spokespersons. So (consequently), don't worship me, but worship only God!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus mai manya'e jara pudhi<bt>The Lord Yesus comes riding a white horse</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia ja'a doa kètu, ka ladhe kèdhi babèdho sorga dhu bhoke tèke. Cag'ag'a laa, ja'a kèdhi jara pudhi ci'u kalua mai. Dhèu dhu manya'e na, ngara na &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu kèpe pa'èra lii pajaji&gt;&gt; aa &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu Mola.&gt;&gt; Lod'o Na parisa lii langu, Na pama'ète dènge mola. Ladhe Nèngu la'e pamusu, la'e dènge d'ara mola.<bt>Then I lifted my face, and saw the door/portal of heaven open. Suddenly, I saw there was a white horse coming forth/out. The person who sat on that horse, his name was, “Person who Fulfills Promises” and “Person who is True/Correct/Right”. If/When He decides/judges cases, He judges correctly. If/when He went to war, He went with a straight insides (=with righteous intentions). [EXEG: Although NLT has “a white horse standing there”, there is nothing in the Gk to push “standing”. Rather vs. 14 has armies following him, so a dynamic picture of action here is a better fit.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="War: Rev. 2:16."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">War: Rev. 2:16.</Message></Annotation><note reference="19:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 1:1, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 96:13, Yesaya 11:4</note><v n="12" />Musi madha Na heo sama sèmi ai. Na pake solo dhèu aae dhu ae, ètu kètu Na. Ngara Na dhu suri ètu ngi'u Na, te ngaa Nèngu mesa Na di, dhu ne'a sasoa ngara èèna.<bt>His eyes blazed like fire. He was wearing many king hats on top of His head. His name was written on His body, but it was only just He himself who knew the meaning of that name. [ EXEG: NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Eyes like flame of fire: Rev."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Eyes like flame of fire: Rev. 1:14, 2:18. Crowns: Rev. 12:3, 13:1.<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>No one knows but himself: Rev. 2:17.</Message></Annotation><note reference="19:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 10:6</note><v n="13" />Mèdha-papake Na, dhu cèb'u le asa d'ara raa. Dhèu paroa Ne, &lt;&lt;Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua&gt;&gt;.<bt>His clothes, had been dipped in blood. People mention/call him, saying, “God's Word(s)”.</bt><v n="14" />Ja'a kèdhi kahèi sordad'u-sordad'u nèti sorga dhu manya'e jara pudhi, dhu madhutu Ne. Sordad'u se pake mèdha alus dhu pudhi mèu kahèi.<bt>I also saw soldiers from heaven were riding white horses to follow Him. They all also wore fine clothes that was pure/clean white.</bt><v n="15" />Abhu samala èci dhu madèka, kalua nèti d'ara hèb'a Na. Na pake samala ne, ho la'e pamusu, lab'a suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha. Hèia Na segi si. Ka Na j'aj'i Dhèu Aae rèngu. Na paredha si dènge ai bèsi, toke rèngu re'a nanasa Lamatua dhu koasa kapai risi. J'ara ne'e ne, sama sèmi dhèu j'èli marèu hua anggor, ho pacèli rare èi na.<bt>There was a sharp fighting sword that came out of His mouth. He used that sword there, to go war against all the tribes on earth. Then He defeated them. And He became their King. He ruled them with an iron hand, until they also felt the anger of God who is most mighty. That was the same as people stepping all over destroying grape fruits, to express/make their juice come out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rule with a rod of iron:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rule with a rod of iron: Rev. 2:27, 12:5.</Message></Annotation><note reference="19:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:9, Yesaya 63:3, Yoel 3:13, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 14:20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Aa ètu kodho dènge ètu haree Na, dhu suri sèmi ne'e:<bt>On that Person's clothing, and on His thigh there was written like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haree = paha ; dhèta ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">haree = paha ; dhèta = tattoo</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu Aae nèti dhèu aae aa'i-aa'i ra,<bt>King of all kings</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua nèti lamatua aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Lord/Master of all lords/masters.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus segi badha bhelu dènge sordad'u na sèra [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus defeats the ferocious animal and his armies/soldiers [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka ja'a ladhe kèdhi ana pajuu ca dhèu nèti sorga dhu titu ètu dedha madha lod'o. Hèia na rodhe manu-bhui aa'i-aa'i dhu lela re talora liru, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai aa'i-aa'i mi pakaboko mi era ne'e, ho mi'a pesta kapai dhu Ama Lamatua tao!<bt>After that, I saw an angel standing on the sun. Then he yelled out to all the corpse-eating birds who were flying high in the sky, saying, “Come for you all to gather here, so that you can eat at God's big feast! [EXEG: corpse-eating birds from context (vs.17) + NLT; cf vs.21]</bt><v n="18" />Sisi dhèu madhe aa'i-aa'i ra, miu bisa mi'a. Nuka sisi nèti: dhèu aae-dhèu aae, komedhaa, dènge sordad'u sèra. Miu mi'a kahèi sisi jara dènge sisi sordad'u dhu manya'e si. Miu mi'a kahèi sisi ènu-ènu, do dhèu mardeka, do ana iiki-dhèu kapai. Peka ka laa, ngara na ngaa dhu dènge sisi, mi'e si.&gt;&gt;<bt>You may eat all the dead people's meat. They are: kings, army commanders, and soldiers. You may eat the meat of horses and the soldiers which sit on top of them. You may eat the meat of slaves or free people, small [ranking] people or big [ranking] people. The important thing is, you may the meat of all those.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="GRAMMAR @@ mi'a &amp; mi'e (imper)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">GRAMMAR @@ mi'a &amp; mi'e (imper) here</Message></Annotation><note reference="19:17-18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 39:17-20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia ja'a kèdhi badha bhelu dhu uru èèna bodho nèti d'ara dhasi. La'e pane'a lii dènge dhèu aae aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha, dènge sordad'u ra. Ka lasi pamusu, lab'a Dhèu dhu manya'e jara pudhi èèna, dènge sordad'u dhu palere-lere dènge Ne nèti sorga.<bt>After that, I saw that ferocious animal who previously appeared out of the sea. He went to plot/plan with all the kings on earth, and with their soldiers. Then they went to war against that Person who rode that aforementioned white horse, together with His army/soldiers from heaven.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pane'a lii = sakongkol, = rare"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pane'a lii = sakongkol, = rare lii èci</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Te ngaa Dhèu manya'e jara pudhi ne, kèpe nare badha bhelu dènge dhèu nèti lii padhai na dhu kapod'e-kabèli sèra. Dhèu dhu nèti padhai lii na, nuka dhèu dhu tao tadha malaa rupa-rupa ho leko-monya dhèu, dhu ra sèmi rare cap nèti badha bhelu ne, aa sogo-tagu mèdha sogo-tagu na. Te ngaa limuri ne, Dhèu dhu manya'e jara pudhi ne, pèci eele le badha bhelu dènge dhèu dhu nèti lii padhai na, asa d'ara dhasi ai èi nasu dhu heo na madhe boe.<bt>But that Person who sat on that white horse, captured that ferocious animal with his deceptive spokesperson. That spokesperson, was who previous did all sorts of miracles to trick people who accepted that wild animal's stamp and who worshipped his object of traditional worship. But now, that Person who is riding that white horse, threw away that ferocious animal and his deceptive spokesperson into the sulfur sea of fire that burns without ever stopping.</bt><note reference="19:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 13:1-18</note><v n="21" />Èle èèna ka, Dhèu dhu manya'e jara pudhi ne, la'e pamadhe aa'i sordad'u dhu leo sèra, pake dènge samala dhu kalua nèti d'ara hèb'a Na. Hèia manu-bhui dhu ra'a sisi hèu, mai ra'e aa'i ngi'u aae dhèu madhe sèra.<bt>Then that Person who rides that horse, went to kill those other soldiers, using His fighting sword that came out of His mouth. After that then, the vulture birds came and ate up all those corpses.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra èki mege naga dènge rate toke ca riho tèu<bt>They tie up the dragon snake with a chain for a thousand years</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="20" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ja'a kèdhi ana pajuu èci nèti sorga puru mai nèti dedha-liru. Na kèpe dènge rate aae èci, aa nèd'u dènge gagoe nèti ro'a j'aj'èra dhu dènge boe too-lane.<bt>After that I saw an angel come down from the sky. He was holding a big chain, and the key to the suffering hole which does not have a foundation/limit.</bt><v n="2" />Ka na la'e kèpe mege naga, nuka dhèu aae nidhu, dhu ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua nidhu&gt;&gt;. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu leko-monya dhèu rai-haha karèi nèti uru ka mai. Hèia ana pajuu ne èki mege naga ne dènge rate, ho taha ne ètu d'ara ro'a j'aj'èra dhu dènge boe lane èèna, toke ca riho tèu.<bt>The he went and captured that dragon snake, who is, the evil spirit's king, that they refer to as “the lord/master of evil spirits”. He is the one who tricked people from long ago. Then that angel tied that dragon snake up with that chain, to detain him in that hole of suffering that has no foundation/limit, for a thousand years.</bt><note reference="20:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 3:1</note><v n="3" />Hèia ana pajuu ne tule eele mege naga na asa d'ara ro'a j'aj'èra èèna. Ka na segel pamadhe hèb'a ro'a èèna, sèna ka taha mege naga ne ètu d'ara ro'a, toke èle ca riho tèu. Dènge j'ara ne'e ka, mege naga ne bisa heka leko-monya suku-suku ètu rai-haha ne, ètu d'ara ca riho tèu. Èle èèna ka, heka patabuli ne kèna, te ngaa nare boe nèbhu.<bt>Next that angel threw that dragon snake away into that aforementioned suffering hole. Then he sealed tight the mouth of that hole, in order to detain that dragon snake there, for a thousand years. In that way, that dragon snake could no longer deceive the tribes on earth for a thousand years. After that, only then did they free him, but only briefly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'èra-èra babèdho ro'a èèna, ho naga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pa'èra-èra babèdho ro'a èèna, ho naga ne hud'i nèngu sène ètu dara, toke èle ca riho tèu. Dènge j'ara ne'e ka mege ne leko-monya heka dhèu-dhèu ètu rai-haha ne toke ca riho tèu. Èle èèna ku heka patabuli ne kèna, te ngaa nare boe nèbhu.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Èle ka, ja'a kèdhi kadera paredha ae-ae, dènge dhèu madhèdi ètu dedha. Ama Lamatua dhu ded'e si j'aj'i hakim. Rèngu se dhu uru èèna lasi lole Lii Lolo Be'a nèti Yesus, dènge Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua, toke dhèu pamadhe si. Rèngu se ka dhu sogo-tagu boe badha bhelu dènge mèdha sogo-tagu na. Rèngu se dhu ro'o boe sèmi cap nèti badha bhelu ne ètu katangarèi ra, do ètu kacui-aai ra. Dhèu pamadhe si, te ngaa Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari si, sèna ka ra rèd'u paredha bera-bera dènge Kristus toke ca riho tèu.<bt>Next I saw there were many ruling chairs, and there were people who sat on top of them. God had elevated/appointed them up to be judges (loan). They were the people who previously had gone to tell people about Yesus' Good News, and God's Words, until people murdered them. They were the ones who didn't worship that ferocious animal and his object of traditional worship. They were the ones who didn't accept that animal's stamp on their forehead or arm/hand. They were murdered, but God had make them live again, so that they could rule together with Kristus for a thousand years.</bt><note reference="20:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:9, 22</note><v n="5-6" />Dènge sèmi ne'e, rèngu se'e ka dhu uru j'ara Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari si nèti mamadhe. De rèngu oto titu kèna, te rèngu j'aj'i le dhèu unu Lamatua. Ra core boe si asa era j'aj'èra èèna, ka ra abhu boe mamadhe ka dua. Te rèngu se nuka sèmi ama agama dhu bèli-camèd'a lalau-lalo'o Ama Lamatua dènge Kristus. Aa rèngu rèd'u paredha kahèi bera-bera dènge Kristus toke d'ai ca riho tèu.<bt>In that way they had become the first people whom God caused to live again from death. So (consequently) they are the ones who are truly fortunate, cuz (elaboration) they are God's people. They will not be cast out/evicted to that suffering place, and will not experience a second death. Cuz (elaboration) they have become like *priests who will serve God and Kristus. And they are who will also rule together with Kristus for a thousand years.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa dhèu madhe dhu leo sèra, hud'i mate ku d'ai ca riho tèu, heka Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari si kèna.<bt>But the other dead people, must wait for a thousand years, before God causes them to live again.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra core dhèu aae nidhu asa d'ara dhasi ai<bt>They throw the evil spirit's king into the sea of fire</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa èle ca riho tèu ku, pe Lamatua pua patalale mege naga nèti d'ara ro'a j'aj'èra.<bt>When those one thousand years are over, later God will tell them to free that dragon snake from that suffering hole. [EXEG: Gk: Satan, but here use dragon for higher level referent tracking of what has been detained in the pit. So ‘Satan’ KT moved to title.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Satanaas: da Devil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Satanaas: da Devil</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Hèia la'e leko-monya dhèu nèti suku-suku dhu ra peka na, Gog dènge Magog, dhu mai nèti mia-mia ètu rai-haha ne. Pe na pakaboko dhèu ra ho lasi pamusu. Dhèu se ae titu kèna, sama sèmi salae ètu nebhe dhasi.<bt>The he will go deceive people from the tribes who they call saying Gog and Magog, who come from all over the world. Later he will gather their people to go to war. Those people will be exceedingly many, just like sand grains on the edge of the sea.</bt><note reference="20:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 7:2, 38:2, 9, 15</note><v n="9" />Hèia sordad'u Gog dènge Magog kako lasi kaj'èu d'ai rae-rae ètu d'ara rai-haha. Ka ra reo rare kota Lamatua dènge dhèu dhu Na sue sèra. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua papuru ai nèti dedha-liru ka na'a pakèpu aa'i sordad'u se'e.<bt>Then those Gog and Magog soldiers will go far until reaching the far villages of the earth. Then they will surround God's city and His people whom He loves. But God will send down fire from the sky to burn up all those soldiers. [EXEG: in Gk ‘beloved’ modifies city (and probably saints).]</bt><v n="10" />Ka dhèu unu Lamatua sèra kèpe rare dhèu aae nidhu dhu kapod'e nare le dhèu ae. Hèia ra core ne asa d'ara dhasi ai èi nasu, dhu heo na loe boe. Èèna na, ra bèdho tèke ne sama-sama dènge badha bhelu, aa dènge dhèu nèti lii padhai kapod'e-kabèli èèna. Ètu era ne'e, rèngu abhu j'aj'èra loe boe mèu-mèda toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>Then God's people captured the king of the evil spirits who had tricked those many people. Then they threw him in to the sulfur fire sea which burns without ever stopping. Later he would be caged/shut up there together with ferocious animal and his deceptive spokesperson. There, they will tortured and suffer continually night and day, for ever. [EXEG: note this is the devil here, not the dragon.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pama'ète lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i<bt>God decides/judges all people's cases</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a ladhe kèdhi kadera paredha pudhi aae cue. Aa Ama Lamatua ka dhu madhèdi ètu kadera èèna. Cag'ag'a laa, rai-haha dènge liru, rai pakaj'èu ka ele aa'i si toke tèdhi heka senu-salao sa hèi.<bt>After that, I saw there was a big white ruling chair. And God was sitting on that chair. Suddenly, the earth and the sky ran away and disappeared completely and they could not be seen anymore. [NOTE: “from His presence” implicit]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sènu-salao = bayangan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">sènu-salao = bayangan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te rèngu taha boe ladhe rèhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Te rèngu taha boe ladhe rèhu Lamatua.</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ka ladhe kèdhi dhèu dhu madhe sèra. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ana iiki-dhèu kapai, titu tangara asa kadera paredha. Hèia ana pajuu nèti sorga mai, ka bhoke sasuri-sasuri dhu suri tatao aa'i-aa'i dhu dhèu rai-haha ad'u-ue. Ka ra bhoke hari sasuri leo èci, dhu suri ngara-ngara dhèu dhu bèli-camèd'a mamuri taa-taa dènge Ama Lamatua. Hèia Na pama'ète lii langu nèti dhèu madhe, madhutu ngaa dhu rèngu èci-èci ad'u-ue, nuka sèmi dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara sasuri sèra.<bt>Then I saw the people who had died. They all small-big [rank] were standing facing that ruling chair. And angels came opening writings which had written all the deeds of humans. Then they opened again another writing, which had written the names of the people who later would live with God forever. Then He decided/judged those dead people's cases, according to what each one of them had done, just like what was written in those writings.</bt><note reference="20:11-12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:9-10</note><v n="13" />Ka dhèu madhe sèra mai titu patangara dènge kadera paredha èèna. Rèngu se aa'i-aa'i dhu madhe le ètu rai-dedha dènge ètu d'ara dhasi. Hèia Ama Lamatua pama'ète lii langu rèngu èci-èci, madhutu tatao ra.<bt>Then those dead people came out to come stand in front of that ruling chair. They were all the people who had died, both on land and the sea. Then God judged each one of their cases, according to their deeds.</bt><v n="14" />Èle èèna ka, Ama Lamatua pèci eele Mamadhe asa d'ara dhasi ai. Aa Na core eele kahèi Era Pea Samanga Dhèu Madhe asa d'ara dhasi ai. Te dhasi ai ne, era mamadhe ka dua.<bt>After that God threw Death into that sea of fire that burns without stopping. He also threw out the Place of the Dead People's Souls into that sea of fire. Cuz (elaboration) that sea of fire, it is the place of second death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ho thanatos kai ho haaidees: switch"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">ho thanatos kai ho haaidees: switch to keep the sentences manageable.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Dhèu dhu ngara ra suri boe ètu d'ara sasuri ne'e, lèke core kahèi asa d'ara dhasi ai. Te sasuri èèna, nuka dhu suri ngara-ngara dhèu dhu mamuri dènge Ama Lamatua taa-taa toke d'ai mia-mia la'e.<bt>People whose names were not written in that writing also were thrown into that sea of fire. Cuz (elaboration) that writing, it writes the names of people who will live continually with God forever [emphasis].</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis ladhe nèdhi liru dènge rai-haha rupa hiu<bt>Yohanis sees the new style/form of sky and earth</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="21" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia ja'a ladhe kèdhi liru dènge rai-haha rupa hiu, te liru dènge rai-haha dhu dhui ele aa'i le. Dhasi aad'o heka kahèi.<bt>Then I saw a new style sky and earth, cuz (elaboration) the old sky and earth had completely disappeared. The sea also was no longer.</bt><note reference="21:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 65:17, 66:22, 2 Petrus 3:13</note><v n="2" />Ka ja'a kèdhi kota mola-mèci unu Ama Lamatua, nuka Yerusalem Hiu, puru mai nèti sorga. Kota ne, dhu pa'èra mema, sama sèmi bhèni dhu neo leo-èmu hiu, dhu lalau nare le iisi, ho la'e soru mone dhu neo j'aj'i dhèu èmu na.<bt>And I saw God's holy/clean city, which is New Yerusalem, come down from heaven. That city was prepared beforehand the same as a new bride who was going to meet her husband.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhèni dhu neo leo èmu hiu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bhèni dhu neo leo èmu hiu = new bride (CHECK previous passages)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="the holy city, the new Jerusalem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">the holy city, the new Jerusalem: Rev. 3:12. adorned: Rev. 21:19, 1 Timothy 2:9.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="21:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 52:1, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 3:12, Yesaya 61:10</note><v n="3" />Ka ja'a tadèngi lii dhu kapai èci mai nèti kadera paredha ne, peka na,<bt>Then I heard a loud voice come from that ruling chair, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ladhe paie-iie!<bt>“Look carefully!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Karèi nèti deo ne'e ne, Èmu Ama Lamatua ètu talora aae dhèu rai-haha.<bt>Starting from now God's House is in the midst of humans.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Karèi nèti deo ne'e ne, Lamatua mamuri pa'èci dènge dhèu unu Na.<bt>Starting from today God lives together with His people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te Nèngu j'aj'i le Ama Lamatua ra.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He has become their God;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa rèngu j'aj'i le ana-ana Na.<bt>And they have become His children.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Bèli-camèd'a Nèngu bera-bera dènge ra.<bt>Later He will exist continually with them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Na palere-lere dènge rèngu taa-taa.<bt>And He will be together with them forever.</bt><note reference="21:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 37:27, Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 26:11, 12</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Bèli-camèd'a Na seka pamango èi madha aa'i-aa'i ra,<bt>Later He will wipe dry all their tears,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="seka = sikat, lap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">seka = sikat, lap</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka rèngu roma iisi heka.<bt>so they will not wail in grief anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Lula ètu era èèna, abhu heka papèd'a-tarègu.<bt>Because there there is no one who is sick (doublet) anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Aa ètu era èèna, abhu heka mamadhe.<bt>And there there is no one who dies anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ngaa-ngaa dhu uru èèna rèti sasusa, aad'o heka èci sa.<bt>Everything which caused difficulty in those previous times, doesn't exist anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ngaa-ngaa dhu uru èèna rèti j'aj'èra, ele aa'i si le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Everything which brought suffering in those previous times, has disappeared gone.”</bt><note reference="21:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 25:8, 35:10, 65:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia Nèngu dhu madhèdi ètu kadera paredha èèna, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe paie-iie, te Ja'a tao pahiu aa'i le.&gt;&gt; Ka Na padhai lii hari dènge ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Suri ka! Dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa parcaya Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a ne, te aa'i-aa'i se mema lèke tare'a-re'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He who sat in that ruling chair spoke saying, “Look carefully, cuz (elaboration) I have made everything become new.” Then He spoke again with me saying, “Write! All people can believe these Words of Mine, cuz (elaboration) all of this, is indeed true!” [NOTE to daughter translations: RL's may have to get rid of these two extra quote margins in vs.5-6, They are heavy and probably signal “change of speaker” (which they are not). Check extensively. Problem, the three quote contents have real shifts between them, so if the quote margins are deleted, strong discourse particles indicating the shift may be needed. KM gets away with it on the back of Indonesian, not on its own merits.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka Na peka hari dènge ja'a, na,<bt>Then He told me again, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Aa'i-aa'i dhu Ja'a pajaji sèra, j'aj'i aa'i le.<bt>“Everything which I have promised from long ago, has happened.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te Ja'a ne,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I am</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Alpa toke Omega,<bt>Alpa until Omega.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa Ja'a ne,<bt>And I am</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">A toke Z,<bt>A until Z,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i nèti Ja'a,<bt>Everything originates from Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">karèi nèti uru ka, toke d'ai èle.<bt>beginning from its beginning until the end.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu koko-kamango,<bt>All people who are thirsty (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pe Ja'a hia ra rinu iia-iia d'ara,<bt>later I will give [them] to drink without paying</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">nèti madha èi dhu nèti mamuri hia dhèu, sèna ka dhèu sèra bisa mamuri dènge tare'a.<bt>from that water spring which brings life so that people can truly live. [KT: phrased as in other Johannine writings.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèti madha èi dhu hia dhèu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">nèti madha èi dhu hia dhèu mamuri taa-taa.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: Well of the water of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">TERM: Well of the water of life, as in 7:17</Message></Annotation><note reference="21:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 55:1</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu taha madhutu j'ara Lamatua dhu mola,<bt>All people who endure following God's straight way of life,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bèli-camèd'a rèngu unu mèngi-nale aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>later they will receive all this blessing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe Ja'a j'aj'i Ama Lamatua ra,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later I will become their God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">aa rèngu j'aj'i ana-ana Ja'a.<bt>and they will become My children.</bt><note reference="21:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Samuel 7:14, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 89:26-27</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa abhu kahèi dhèu dhu èèna na lèke core si,<bt>But there are also people who will be thrown</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">asa d'ara dhasi ai èi nasu dhu heo na ma'ète boe ciki sa.<bt>into that sulfur sea of fire that burns without ever ending.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nuka sèmi: dhèu dhu madha'u leli,<bt>Those are: cowards,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhèu dhu soro kabodho mi Lamatua Yesus,<bt>people who turn their backs on Yesus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhèu d'ara kaj'alu,<bt>dirty/defiled people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhèu dhu tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali ra,<bt>(sexually) immoral people, [KT: Gk /pornois/ here, so should be same as used for ‘fornication’ elsewhere.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhèu pamadhe dhèu,<bt>murderers,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhèu sogo-tagu nidhu,<bt>habitual traditional worshipers of evil spirits,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhèu suagi,<bt>sorcerers,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa dhèu kapod'e-kabèli.<bt>and deceivers.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Bèli-camèd'a rèngu aa'i-aa'i lèke pèci asa d'ara dhasi ai,<bt>Later they all will be thrown into that sea of fire,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu ra peka na, &lt;era mamadhe ka dua.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>which they refer to as ‘the place of second death.’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis ladhe nèdhi kota Yerusalem rupa hiu<bt>Yohanis sees Yerusalem city new style</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka ja'a ladhe kèdhi ca dhèu nèti ana pajuu dhèu pidhu nèti sorga, dhu uru èèna rèd'u bokor dhu isi dènge nanasa Lamatua. Na mai paraga dènge ja'a, ka na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai ku sa ne'e! Te ja'a neo pad'elo dènge èu bhèni dhu neo kab'i dènge Ana Kalèbho.&gt;&gt;<bt>Next I saw one of those seven angels who previously was holding the bowls that were filled with God's anger. He came to meet me, then he said, “Come here! I want to show you the woman who wants to/is going to marry the Sheep Offspring.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia ja'a abhu Roh Lamatua, ka ana pajuu ca dhèu nèti sorga mai nedhe nèti ja'a asa kolo ledhe dhu dedha aae èci. Nèti era ne'e, na pad'elo ja'a kota Yerusalem, nuka kota Ama Lamatua dhu mola-mèci, dhu puru mai nèti Ama Lamatua ètu sorga.<bt>Next I got God's Spirit, and an angel lifted took me to a very tall mountain. There he showed me Yerusalem city, which is that holy city of God's, which He was letting down from heaven.</bt><note reference="21:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 40:2</note><v n="11" />Kota ne saraga titu kèna! Abhu saraa dhu kalua nèti dadedha Ama Lamatua sèmi hadhu intan dhu kale'e, toke kota aa'i-aa'i heo lo'a-lo'a.<bt>That city is incredibly fine/beautiful! There is light that strikes out coming from God's majesty/awesomeness/glory/highness, like diamonds which are flashing/shiny, to the point that the entire city is lit up.</bt><v n="12" />Abhu tedhe dhu dedha aae oke nare kota ne, dènge canguru dua babèdho. Abhu kahèi canguru dua ana pajuu nèti sorga dhu madhenge babèdho kapai se. Ètu canguru dua babèdho se, dhu suri ngara-ngara nèti canguru dua udhu-rasa Isra'el.<bt>There is a tall big wall surrounding that city, with 12 doors/gates. There are also 12 angels who guard those great doors. On those 12 doors is written the names of the 12 Isra'el clans. [NOTE to daughter translations: TB has “di atas” which is ambiguous and could be read incorrectly as “above the doors”. While possible, more likely from the whole verse (a gapping construction in the Gk leaning on the vb of the previous clause) is “on the doors”. Just be aware of teams bringing noise from the TB on this.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ètu re dedha nèti canguru dua"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Ètu re dedha nèti canguru dua babèdho se,</Message></Annotation><note reference="21:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu dhèu d'èlu-mèu Alkitab, angka canguru dua èèna, peka na, dhèu mèci.<bt>According to people who are knowledgeable about the Bible, that number 12, is a number that shows a complete number of people.</bt></note><v n="13" />Tèlu babèdho tangara asa dhimu. Tèlu tangara asa haa. Tèlu tangara asa badae. Aa tèlu hari tangara asa balèu.<bt>Three doors face to the east side. Three face to the west side. Three face to the north side. And three more face to the south side.</bt><note reference="21:12-13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 48:30-35</note><v n="14" />Tedhe ne dhu patitu ètu canguru dua hadhu fanderen dhu kapai. Ètu hadhu se èci-èci dhu suri ngara nèti canguru dua dhèu pajuu-paleha Ana Kalèbho dhu lalau-lalo'o Ne ètu rai-haha.<bt>That wall stands on top of 12 foundation rocks which are big. On each rock is written the names of the Sheep Offspring's 12 *apostles who served Him on earth. [CEV, LN]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ka ana pajuu dhu padhai lii dènge ja'a, kèpe nare tatea a'uku nèti hualaa èci, ho neo uku kota ne dènge hèb'a babèdho kapai, aa dènge tedhe na.<bt>Then that angel who spoke to me, was holding a measuring stick from gold, to measure that city and its great doors and its wall(s).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="measuring rod: Rev. 11:1."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">measuring rod: Rev. 11:1.</Message></Annotation><note reference="21:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 40:3</note><v n="16" />Na uku uru tedhe kota. Madhera, bhabhèla dènge katitu na, èci èèna ka. Nuka, aa'i-aa'i ra, 2.220 (dua riho dua ngasu dua nguru) kilometer.<bt>He measured first that city's wall which was square. It's length and width and height were all the same, that is 2.220 kilometers.</bt><note reference="21:16" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani peka canguru dua riho <span class="Italic">stadia.</span><bt>The Yunani language Bible writes, saying, 12,000 <span class="Italic">stadia</span>.</bt></note><v n="17" />Hèia na uku ma'aa tedhe, madhutu a'uku dhèu rai-haha. Ma'aa na, èna nguru lèmi meter.<bt>Then he measured that wall's thickness there, it was 65 meters, according to human's measurements. [EXEG: NLT note + metric equivalent of CEV.]</bt><note reference="21:17" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Akitab lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;144 (ca ngasu èpa nguru èpa)<span class="Italic"> peihon</span>&gt;&gt;. Ca <span class="Italic">peihon</span>, sama sèmi dua èg'a. Canguru dua kali canguru dua, nuka cangasu èpa nguru èpa. De ladhe canguru dua èèna, sasoa na, tesa, na, 144 sasoa na, dhu tesa risi eele.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes here, saying “144 peihon”. One <span class="Italic">peihon</span> is the same as two handspans (still commonly used in villages). 12 times 12 is 144. So (consequently), if 12 means complete, 144 means most complete.</bt></note><v n="18" />Tedhe ne, tao nèti hadhu kale'e, ngara na <span class="Italic">yaspis.</span> Aa aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara kota ne, tao nèti poe dènge pai, dhu mèu aadha-aadha nuka sèmi tèru.<bt>That wall, was made from a jewel, named <span class="Italic">yaspis.</span> And all that was in that city, was made from pure gold that was clear/transparent like glass.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="le'e-le'e = mangkilat ; mèu aadha-aadha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">le'e-le'e = mangkilat ; mèu aadha-aadha = clear (of water)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Canguru dua hadhu fanderen sèra, tao nèti rupa-rupa hadhu kale'e dhu kab'ua. Fanderen ka èci, tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">yaspis,</span> dhu mangèru kale'e. Ka dua, nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">nilam</span> dhu kale'e mangèru bhidhu-bhidhu. Ka tèlu, tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">mirah</span> dhu mea kale'e. Ka èpa, tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">samrud,</span> dhu mangèru kale'e.<bt>Those 12 foundation stones, were adorned with all kinds of jewels which were expensive. That first one, used <span class="Italic">yaspis</span> stone which shone a green colour. Number two, used <span class="Italic">nilam</span> stone which shone a blue colour. Number three, used <span class="Italic">mirah</span> stone which shone a red colour. Number four, used <span class="Italic">samrud</span> stone, which shone a green colour.</bt><v n="20" />Ka lèmi, tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">unam</span> dhu pakatanga dènge karara mea sanama pudhi. Ka èna, dhu tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">sardius,</span> dhu mea kale'e. Ka pidhu, tao nèti <span class="Italic">ratna cempaka</span> dhu karara hualaa. Ka aru, dhu tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">beril,</span> dhu kale'e mangèru aae. Ka ceo, tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">krisolit,</span> dhu karara moce-moce. Ka canguru, tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">krisopras</span> dhu mangèru mud'a. Ka canguru èci, tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">lasuardi,</span> dhu mangèru dhasi. Aa ka canguru dua, tao nèti hadhu <span class="Italic">kecubung,</span> dhu kale'e mea sanama mangèru.<bt>Number five, used <span class="Italic">unam</span> stone which was layered brown and white. Number six, used <span class="Italic">sardius</span> stone, which shone a red colour. Number seven, used <span class="Italic">ratna cempaka</span> stone, which shone a gold yellow colour. Number eight, used <span class="Italic">beril</span> stone, which shone a blue-green colour. Number nine, used <span class="Italic">krisolit</span> stone, which shone a yellowish colour. Number ten, used <span class="Italic">krisopras</span> stone, which shone a light green colour. Number eleven, used <span class="Italic">lasuardi</span> stone, which shown a sea blue colour. And number twelve, used <span class="Italic">kecubung</span> stone, which shone a purple colour. [EXEG: see Martins article.] [NOTE to consultant: in Dhao text names of stones are italicised.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakatanga = lapis ; karara mea"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">pakatanga = lapis ; karara mea = coklat ; mangèru aae = biru tua ; karara moce-moce = kuning betul, like kunyit</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Aa babèdho kapai canguru dua bua sèra, tao nèti canguru bua mutiara. Babèdho èci tao nèti mutiara cue. J'ara oka-hoo ètu d'ara kota ne, tao nèti poe-pai dhu kale'e sèmi tèru.<bt>And those 12 great doors/gates, were made of 12 pearls. One door was made from one pearl. And that city's streets, were made from pure gold that shone like glass. [EXEG: Gk word for “clear as glass” in 18 is different from the word here. Here it must be something that gold can do.]</bt><note reference="21:18-21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 54:11-12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa ja'a kèdhi boe Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i ètu d'ara kota ne. Lula Ama Lamatua dhu koasa kapai risi dènge Ana Kalèbho pea taa-taa ètu d'ara kota ne. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu pahaha iisi mema mi Rèngu.<bt>But I saw, there wasn't a Worship House in that city. Because God who has the most power/authority and that Sheep Offspring are there continually in that city. That's why people go straight to worship Them.</bt><v n="23" />Kota èèna, parluu boe madha lod'o dènge hèru ho pasaraa ne, lula saraa Ama Lamatua ka dhu pasaraa ne. Aa Ana Kalèbho ne j'aj'i nuka sèmi labhu dhu heo.<bt>That city also does not need the sun or moon to make it light, because God's radiance has made it light. And that Sheep Offspring has become like a lamp which shines.</bt><note reference="21:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 60:19-20</note><v n="24" />Dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha, èèna na kako lasi mai ètu d'ara saraa èèna. Dhèu aae-dhèu aae nèti rai-haha, rèti kakaja-sasu'i ra asa nèi kahèi.<bt>People from every tribe in the world later will come and walk in that light. Kings from earth will also come bringing their incredible wealth there.</bt><note reference="21:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 60:3</note><v n="25" />Ètu era nèi, abhu boe mèda. Nèti èèna ka, parluu boe bèdho hèb'a tedhe.<bt>There there is no night. That's why they don't need to close doorways of the walls.</bt><v n="26" />Pe asa d'ara kota ne, dhèu rèti aa'i-aa'i dhu be'a kahèi, dènge hormat aa'i-aa'i nèti rai-rai ètu rai-haha.<bt>Later they will bring into that city, everything that is good and all honour from all the nations on earth.</bt><note reference="21:25-26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 60:11</note><v n="27" />Te ngaa dhu bisa boe maso asa nèi, nuka aa'i-aa'i dhu karehe, nuka sèmi: dhèu sogo-tagu nidhu, dhèu dhu tao j'ara makae, dènge dhèu kapod'e-kabèli. Dhu bisa maso, nuka rèngu dhu ngara ra abhu ètu d'ara sasuri Ana Kalèbho. Rèngu se'e ka dhu mamuri taa-taa dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>But those who cannot enter that city, are all who are evil, such as: people who follow traditional worship of evil spirits, people who do shameful things (sexually), and liars/deceivers. Those who can enter, are people whose names are written in that Sheep Offspring's writing. These are the ones who will live forever with God.</bt><note reference="21:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 52:1, Yeskial 44:9</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èi loko dènge aj'u dhu rèti mamuri [\s2]<bt>A/the river water and the tree that brings life [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="22" />
      <v n="1" />Èle ka ana pajuu nèti sorga pad'elo dènge ja'a loko èci, dhu èi ne nèti mamuri. Èi ne mèu aadha-aadha nuka sèmi tèru. Na hae mai nèti kadera paredha Ama Lamatua dènge Ana Kalèbho.<bt>Afterwards then, that angel showed me a river, whose water brings life. That water was clear like glass. It flowed out from God and that Sheep Offspring's ruling chair.</bt><note reference="22:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 47:1, Sakaria 14:8</note><v n="2" />Hèia hae la'e asa talora aae j'ara oka-hoo ètu d'ara kota ne. Nèti sebhe-sebhe loko ne, abhu aj'u dhu hua na nèti mamuri. Aj'u ne d'ara ca tèu, hua canguru dua hari; ca hèru, ca tèka. Rèu na bisa j'aj'i èi na'i ho puri-pa'èle suku-suku ètu rai-haha nèti papèd'a ra.<bt>Next it flowed in the middle of the big street in that city. On that river's sides, there was a tree that brings life. Thàt tree bore fruit in one year, 12 times; one month, one time. It's leaves could be/become medicine to heal the tribes on earth.</bt><note reference="22:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:9</note><v n="3" />Te ngaa rèngu dhu Ama Lamatua tule eele aa dhoo si, abhu boe ètu d'ara kota ne. Dhu ètu ne'e, nuka Ama Lamatua dènge Ana Kalèbho dhu madhèdi ètu dedha kadera paredha, aa dènge ana pua-paleha Ra dhu pahaha iisi mi Rèngu.<bt>But all that God ever refused/rejected and cursed, they are not in that city. Those who are there, are God and the Sheep Offspring who sit ruling on Their ruling chair(s), and Their servants who worship Them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: katathema 'curse'."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">TERM: katathema 'curse'.</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 14:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i bisa ladhe rèdhi rèhu Ama Lamatua. Ètu katangarèi dhèu se'e, dhu suri ngara Lamatua.<bt>They all can see God's face. And the Lord's name is written on their foreheads.</bt><v n="5" />Mèda abhu boe ètu kota ne'e. De dhèu unu Lamatua parluu boe madha lod'o, do labhu, lula Ama Lamatua ka dhu pasaraa kota ne. Bèli-camèd'a rèngu sama-sama rèd'u paredha toke d'ai mia-mia la'e.<bt>There, there is no night. So God's people don't need the sun or, lamps or, because God himself is the one who makes that city light. Later they will rule there forever.</bt><note reference="22:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 60:19, Daniel 7:18</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus katange lii padhadha Na<bt>The Lord Yesus closes His requests/promises/ message/instructions</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka ana pajuu ne peka dènge ja'a, na, &lt;&lt;Aa'i-aa'i dhu ja'a peka kore dènge èu se'e, lèke tare'a-re'a. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa parcaya lii ja'a se. Uru èèna, Ama Lamatua pake Roh Na ho peka-padhai Lii Holo-Nori Na mi dhèu rèti lii padhai Na. Te ngaa limuri ne, Na pake ana pajuu Na nèti sorga ho lole mi dhèu unu Na, lula-nèti j'ara aa'i-aa'i se dhu nèbhu heka hud'i j'aj'i ku.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that angel told me saying, “All that I have told you here, is certainly true. All people can believe that speaking of mine. Previously God used His Words to tell His spokespersons. But now He has sent His angel to tell His people about all these things which must soon happen.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 19:10."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 19:10.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia Yesus padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e paie-iie! Nèbhu heka, te Ja'a neo mai. Ètu d'ara sasuri ne, dhu suri aa'i mèu-mèu le, ngaa dhu bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhutu isi sasuri ne, pe rèngu abhu a'oto.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yesus spoke saying, “Remember well! Not much longer (=soon), I will come. In this writing everything has been written, about what will happen. All people who follow this writings words, later they will be most fortunate.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sanèd'e paie-iie = think about this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">Sanèd'e paie-iie = think about this carefully (and often)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Dhu suri sasuri ne, nuka ja'a, Yohanis. Aa'i-aa'i se ja'a nanene dènge ro'a dhilu ja'a, aa kèdhi dènge musi madha ja'a. Ropa tadèngi kore, hèia ja'a patitu kètu urutuu ho pahaha iisi ètu madha ana pajuu nèti sorga ne, dhu pad'elo le aa'i-aa'i se mi ja'a.<bt>The one who writes this writing, is me, Yohanis. All of these things are what I have heard with my own ears, and seen with my own eyes. [NOTE: strong form of evidential in Dhao.] After hearing them, I fell kneeling to worship at the feet of that angel who showed all these things to me. [NOTE to daughter translations: not worship the angel, but worship before his feet; remember earlier when John tried to worship the angel it was rejected as improper, as in vs 9 below.]</bt><v n="9" />Te ngaa na kai ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ee! Èu baku tao sèmi èèna! Èu dhodhoka pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua di! Baku mi ja'a ne. Te ja'a ne ènu Lamatua kahèi, èci èèna ka dènge èu dènge a'ari èu dhu j'aj'i dhèu rèti lii padhai Na, aa dènge dhèu leo aa'i-aa'i ra dhu tao madhutu ngaa dhu suri ètu d'ara sasuri ne'e.<bt>But he forbade me saying, “Ee [+protest]! You don't do like that! Don't worship me. But you must worship only God. Not me. Cuz (elaboration) I also am God's servant/slave the same as you, and your siblings who have become His spokespersons, and all the other people who have done according to what is written in this writing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 19:10."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 19:10.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Èu baku pahuni isi sasuri ne dènge dhèu leo. Te nèbhu heka, aa'i-aa'i dhu suri ètu d'ara sasuri ne, hud'i j'aj'i ku.<bt>You don't hide this writing's contents from other people. Cuz (elaboration) not much longer, everything which is written in this writing, surely will have happened. [DISCOURSE: do not put quote margin here. There is no shift of speaker or audience.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu ad'u-ue bhabhelu, na,<bt>All people who do evil, well,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hud'i rèngu sène ra tao kaj'alu taruu.<bt>just leave them so they just keep on doing evil.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri mola-mèci,<bt>But all who live holy,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hud'i laa ra mamuri mola taruu.<bt>they must keep on living holy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tao karehe,<bt>All people who do bad things,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hud'i rèngu sène ra tao bhelu taruu.<bt>just let them go on doing evil continually.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu tao be'a,<bt>But everyone who does good/well</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hud'i laa ra tao taruu dhu be'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>must continue doing good.”</bt><note reference="22:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 12:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus lii hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e paie! Te nèbhu heka, Ja'a dhiu. Pe Ja'a b'ala hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i, madhutu ngaa dhu ra ad'u-ue.<bt>After that, Yesus spoke again saying, “Remember well! Cuz (elaboration) not much longer, I will come. I will repay/reciprocate to each person, according to what they have done.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 11:8, 18:6, 2:23, 20:12,13."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 11:8, 18:6, 2:23, 20:12,13.</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 40:10, 62:11, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 28:4, Yermia 17:10</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />Ja'a ne,<bt>I am</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Alpa toke Omega.<bt>Alpa until Omega.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a ne,<bt>I am</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">A toke Z.<bt>A until Z.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa'i-aa'i j'aj'aj'i ra nèti Ja'a,<bt>Everything originates from Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">karèi nèti uru, toke d'ai èle.<bt>beginning from it's beginning until the end.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: First and last: Rev. 1:8,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">TERM: First and last: Rev. 1:8, 17, 18, 2:8, 21:6. Phrased a little bit different each time.</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 1:8, Yesaya 44:6, 48:12, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 1:17, 2:8</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />Dhèu dhu rase pamèu le mèdha-papake ra, rèngu ka dhu oto.<bt>The people who have washed clean those clothes of theirs, they are the ones who are fortunate.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te rèngu ka abhu hak ho maso re babèdho kapai dhu la'e asa d'ara kota ne.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later they will have the right to enter those great doors/gates going into that city.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu dhu mamuri mola, rèngu ka dhu oto.<bt>Those people who live holy, they are the ones who are fortunate.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te bèli-camèd'a rèngu abhu ijin ho ra'a hua dhu hia dhèu mamuri taa-taa.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later they will be given permission to eat that fruit which makes people live forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 7:14, 22:2."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 7:14, 22:2.</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:9, 3:22</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa dhèu leo bisa boe maso asa era èèna.<bt>But other people, may not enter there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu dhu unu boe Lamatua, bisa boe pea ètu era èèna.<bt>Those who are not God's people, may not stay/live there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nuka rèngu dhu parcaya boe Lamatua,<bt>That is, people who don't believe in God, [EXEG: Gk “dogs”.]</bt><note reference="22:15" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;busa&gt;&gt;. Dhèu Yahudi d'èi pakasame dhèu Yahudi boe dènge &lt;&lt;busa&gt;&gt;. Dhèu se'e nuka &lt;&lt;dhèu leo dhu parcaya boe Lamatua&gt;&gt;. Ètu d'ara ayat ne'e, Yohanis padhue lula-nèti rupa-rupa dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe maso asa d'ara sorga. Risi-risi, nuka &lt;&lt;dhèu dhu parcaya boe Lamatua&gt;&gt;. J'ara ne'e lai lula boe busa maso sorga, do aad'o. Te ngaa peka mi rèngu dhu parcaya boe Lamatua.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes, saying, “dogs”. Yahudi people often used the word “dog” as a figurative way to refer to non-Yahudi people, that is other (category) people “who don't believe in God”. In this verse, Yohanis is speaking about various groups who won't be able to get into heaven. The first/foremost is “people who don't believe in God”. This is not a dispute over whether dogs can get into heaven or not. But about those who do not believe (in) God.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhèu dhu tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali ra, tuka sogo-tagu,<bt>people who do defiling things with persons who are not their spouse, traditional worshipers of idols,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tuka pamadhe dhèu, tuka suagi,<bt>murderers, sorcerers,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge rèngu dhu leko-monya.<bt>and habitual liars/deceivers.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra bisa boe ara asa d'ara.<bt>All those aforementioned, may not enter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ara = maju"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">ara = maju</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra pea dhoka mi li'u di.<bt>All those aforementioned, are just left outside.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rev. 21:8."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Rev. 21:8.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ja'a ne, Yesus. Ja'a ka dhu paleha ana pajuu Ja'a nèti sorga, ho bhoke j'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i ra, sèna ka pe miu lami lole peka lii pajaji Ja'a se'e mi pidhu juma'at sèra.<bt>I am Yesus. I am the one who sent My angel from heaven to reveal/open these things, so that you later go tell My instructions/message/requests to those seven congregations.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a ne, ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud.<bt>I am king Daud's descendant.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a ne, Dhèu Aae dhu kèd'u paredha.<bt>I am the Raja who rules/governs.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Saraa nèti Ja'a heo lo'a-lo'a,<bt>My radiance is extremely bright,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka sèmi Hua-hètu Oe Mèu.<bt>like the Almost Daylight Star.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Saraa nèti Ja'a madèka titu kèna,<bt>My rays are very sharp,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka sèmi hua-hètu èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>like that star.” [NOTE to daughter translations: These 2 stars need to be understood to be the same.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Morning Star: seems to refer to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Morning Star: seems to refer to the Messiah, Numbers 24:17, Rev. 2:28.</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 11:1, 10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Roh Ama Lamatua mai paroa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai asa ne'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>God's Spirit is inviting saying, “Come here!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Bhèni dhu neo kab'i paroa kahèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>That bride also calls out, saying, “Come on!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa'i-aa'i dhu tadèngi peka kahèi, &lt;&lt;Mai ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Let all who hear also say, “Come on!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu cee dhu koko-kamango, mai ho minu!<bt>Let everyone who is thirsty, come and drink!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu cee dhu neo ninu èi dhu nèti mamuri,<bt>Let everyone who wants to drink that water that brings life,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">mai mere ka!<bt>come and get it!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu bisa rare èi ne<bt>People can take that water</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu iia-iia d'ara.<bt>unimpeded/without cost/free.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu bisa rinu èi ne<bt>People can drink that water</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu b'ae boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>with out a price/payment.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The bride: Christ's people: Rev. 19:7."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">The bride: Christ's people: Rev. 19:7.</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 55:1</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii moa Yohanis dhu limuri tèka<bt>Yohanis' final request/instruction/message</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ja'a, Yohanis, pasanèd'e dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu èèna na tadèngi ngaa dhu Ama Lamatua bhoke mema hia ja'a ètu d'ara sasuri ne: ladhe abhu dhèu dhu patabha hari ngaa-ngaa ètu d'ara sasuri ne, èèna na Ama Lamatua pabie hari hahuku Na mi nèngu dènge pidhu calaka sèra dhu Na dutu mai asa rai-haha.<bt>I, Yohanis here, want to remind/warn all people who will hear what God has revealed beforehand to me in this writing, like this: if there is a person who adds anything more to this writing, later God will add a punishment to him of those seven catastrophes which He poured out on the earth.</bt><v n="19" />Aa ladhe abhu dhu pakura hari isi sasuri ne, pe Ama Lamatua tao eele hak nèngu, sèna ka bisa boe maso asa d'ara kota dhu mola-mèci, aa bisa boe na'a hua aj'u dhu hia dhèu mamuri taa-taa.<bt>And if there is a person who takes away/reduces anything more from this writing, later God will take away his right so that he can't enter that holy city, and he can't eat that fruit which makes people live forever. [CHECK @@ term for “take away”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bete = cabut ; pakura"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z">bete = cabut ; pakura</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Their share: rev. 20:6, 21:8."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:02:53Z" status="Information">Their share: rev. 20:6, 21:8.</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:18-19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 4:2, 12:32</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Yesus mesa Na ka dhu bhoke j'ara aa'i-aa'i sèra. Na moa le, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a-re'a sèmi èèna! Nèbhu heka, Ja'a neo dhiu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus himself is the one who has open/revealed shown these things. He has promised/instructed saying. “It's true! Not much longer, cuz (elaboration) I will come.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De mai ka, Lamatua Yesus!<bt>Well, come on Lord Yesus!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Lamatua Yesus pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi dhèu unu Na aa'i-aa'i. Lèke tare'a sèmi èèna! Amin!<bt>I request the Lord Yesus to show His grace/goodness/ generosity to all of His people. That's really how it is! Amin!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti ja'a,<bt>From me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yohanis<bt>Yohanis</bt></p>
  </book>
</bible>